Wow, this dish you cooked is goodah (delicious)!

etymology: Slang, from English 'good shot', possibly meaning trying to make a good impression or 'take a good shot' at getting something desired by acting good.

definitions.meaning: Ang magpakabait o gumawa ng mabuti para makuha ang gusto o pagbigyan sa isang hiling.
To act good or be on one's best behavior, usually with the intention of gaining favor or having a request granted.

examples.example: Magpapa-goodshot ako kay boss para pagbigyan niya ang leave request ko.
I will try to goodshot (be good to) the boss so my leave request will be granted.

etymology: From English 'goon', referring to a thug, hired muscle, or gangster.

definitions.meaning: Isang maton, gangster, o bayarang tauhan para sa maruming trabaho.
A thug or gangster, especially one hired for rough work.

examples.example: Maraming goon na kalaban si Cardo sa serye.
Cardo has many goons as enemies in the series.

etymology: Slang, likely a playful alteration of English 'go' or Tagalog 'tara' (let's go). Common in Bekimon.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang pumunta, umalis, o 'tara na'.
Slang term meaning to go, to leave, or 'let's go'.

examples.example: Gora na tayo sa party, baka ma-late tayo!
Let's gora (go) to the party, we might be late!

etymology: Slang, an elaborated and more emphatic form of 'gora', adding the common Bekimon suffix '-bels'. Means 'Go ahead!', 'Let's do it!', 'It's okay!'.

definitions.meaning: Isang ekspresyon na nangangahulugang 'Sige lang!', 'Ituloy mo lang!', o 'Okay lang!'.
An expression meaning 'Go ahead!', 'Just go with it!', or 'It's okay!'.

examples.example: Kahit mahirap, gorabels lang sa hamon ng buhay!
Even if it's hard, just gorabels (go for it) with life's challenges!

etymology: Standard English contraction of 'got you', used when catching someone or understanding something.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyon na katumbas ng 'Huli ka!' o minsan 'Naintindihan ko'.
Expression equivalent to 'Got you!' (meaning I caught you or I understand).

examples.example: Akala mo makakatakas ka ha, gotcha!
You thought you could escape, gotcha!

etymology: Tagalog word, often implies being tricked or fooled, or refers to someone who is easily fooled or perhaps somewhat foolish/mischievous.

definitions.meaning: Pagiging naloko, nadaya, o nauto. Maaari ring tumukoy sa taong nanloloko o madaling maloko.
Being duped, tricked, or fooled.

examples.example: Goyo talaga si France. Hindi man lang ako sinabihan na bukas ang zipper ko.
France is such a goyo (trickster/fool). He didn't even tell me my fly was open.

etymology: Reduplication of the Tagalog word 'goyo', forming a verb meaning 'to fool', 'to trick', or 'to dupe' someone.

definitions.meaning: Ang manloko, mandaya, o mang-uto ng ibang tao.
To fool, trick, or dupe someone.

examples.example: Huwag mo akong goyo-goyoin, alam ko ang totoo.
Don't try to goyo-goyo (fool) me, I know the truth.

etymology: From Spanish 'grave' (grave, serious), adopted into Tagalog as an expression of intensity, meaning 'excessive', 'intense', 'severe', 'amazing', 'terrible', or simply 'wow!'.

definitions.meaning: Isang ekspresyon na nagpapahiwatig ng kasobrahan, katindihan, o pagkamangha/pagkagulat; sobra o labis.
An expression indicating intensity, excessiveness, or extremity (can be positive or negative); excessive, intense, severe, wow!

examples.example: Grabe, ang laki ng katawan ni Mark!
Wow (Grabe), Mark's body is huge!

etymology: Slang, metaphorical use of 'graduate' in basketball to mean being ejected from the game due to accumulating too many fouls (fouling out).

definitions.meaning: Sa basketbol, ang matanggal sa laro dahil sa pag-abot sa maximum na bilang ng mga foul; ma-foul out.
In basketball, to be removed from the game after committing the maximum number of personal fouls allowed; to foul out.

examples.example: Graduate na si Yves kasi ang dami niyang foul, pang-anim na.
Yves is a graduate (fouled out) for having too many fouls, that was his sixth.

etymology: Slang/euphemistic expression using 'grand finals' (term for the final round of a competition) to refer to the last day/night of a funeral wake before burial.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyong balbal para sa huling araw o gabi ng lamay bago ang libing.
Slang expression for the last day or night of a funeral wake before the burial.

examples.example: Hindi pa ba tayo pupunta sa St. Peter? Ngayon na ang grand finals ni lola.
Aren't we going to the wake at St. Peter? It's grandma's grand finals (last night of wake) today.

etymology: Standard English slang term for marijuana, adopted into Filipino usage.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal mula Ingles para sa marijuana.
Slang term for marijuana.

examples.example: Hoy, bakit ka nagdala ng grass dito? Bawal 'yan!
Hey, why did you bring grass (marijuana)? That's illegal here!

etymology: Slang expression, possibly referencing Granada, Spain, or 'granada' (grenade), used dramatically to express shock, surprise, or being overwhelmed.

definitions.meaning: Isang ekspresyon na nagpapahiwatig ng matinding gulat, pagkagimbal, o pagkamangha.
An expression used to show great shock, surprise, or being overwhelmed.

examples.example: Granada de espaÃ±a, napapalibutan ako ng mga macho dito!
Granada de espaÃ±a (Oh my gosh), I'm surrounded by macho men here!

etymology: Slang expression, wordplay on 'Gorilla in Manila' (possibly referencing the 'Thrilla in Manila' boxing event) but using 'grilla' (suggesting 'girl') to refer to a fight between lesbians.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyong balbal para sa awayan o bangayan sa pagitan ng mga tomboy.
Slang expression for a fight or argument among lesbians.

examples.example: Ayaw kong magpunta sa eskinita na 'yan kasi laging may grilla in Manila.
I don't want to go to that alley because there's always a grilla in Manila (lesbian fight) happening.

etymology: Slang, derived from 'gripo' (faucet, tap). Metaphorically means 'to stab', possibly because a tap pierces a pipe or container, or due to the shape/action.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang saksakin gamit ang patalim.
Slang term meaning to stab someone with a knife.

examples.example: Gripuhan mo na 'yan para magtanda!
Gripuhan (Stab) him so he'll learn his lesson!

etymology: From English slang 'groovy' (popular in the 1960s), meaning cool, excellent, or enjoyable.

definitions.meaning: Mula sa Ingles, nangangahulugang cool, astig, kasiya-siya, o kuwela.
From English, meaning cool, fun, excellent, or enjoyable.

examples.example: Kulubot na siya pero groovy pa rin si lolo.
He's wrinkled and old, but grandpa is still groovy (cool/fun).

etymology: Slang, origin uncertain. Means to take or seize something, often forcefully or illicitly.

definitions.meaning: Ang kunin o agawin ang pag-aari ng iba, madalas sa pwersahang paraan.
To take or seize something, often forcefully or illicitly.

examples.example: Gungag mo na ang mga alahas para makatakas na tayo!
Gungag (Seize/Grab) the jewelry so we can get out of here!

etymology: Slang, metaphorical use of 'graduate' in basketball to mean being ejected from the game due to accumulating too many fouls (fouling out).

In basketball, to be removed from the game after committing the maximum number of personal fouls allowed; to foul out.

examples.example: Graduate na si Yves kasi ang dami niyang foul, pang-anim na.
Yves is a graduate (fouled out) for having too many fouls, that was his sixth.

Aren't we going to the wake at St. Peter? It's grandma's grand finals (last night of wake) today.

Granada de espaÃ±a (Oh my gosh), I'm surrounded by macho men here!

I don't want to go to that alley because there's always a grilla in Manila (lesbian fight) happening.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang saksakin gamit ang patalim.
Slang term meaning to stab someone with a knife.

examples.example: Gripuhan mo na 'yan para magtanda!
Gripuhan (Stab) him so he'll learn his lesson!

From English, meaning cool, fun, excellent, or enjoyable.

examples.example: Kulubot na siya pero groovy pa rin si lolo.
He's wrinkled and old, but grandpa is still groovy (cool/fun).

etymology: Slang, origin uncertain. Means to take or seize something, often forcefully or illicitly.

definitions.meaning: Ang kunin o agawin ang pag-aari ng iba, madalas sa pwersahang paraan.
To take or seize something, often forcefully or illicitly.

examples.example: Gungag mo na ang mga alahas para makatakas na tayo!
Gungag (Seize/Grab) the jewelry so we can get out of here!

etymology: Slang, using 'gulay' (vegetable) metaphorically to refer to a girl or woman. The connection is unclear, possibly related to perceived passivity or being 'picked'.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa babae.
Slang term for girl or woman.

examples.example: Tigang na talaga ako sa gulay. (sexually deprived of women)
I'm really longing for gulay (women).

etymology: Tagalog slang term for an old person, often used informally and can sometimes be slightly derogatory depending on context.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa matandang tao.
Slang term for an old person.

examples.example: Ayaw naman talaga ni Jeng kay Alfred kasi gurang na daw.
Jeng doesn't really like Alfred because he's already gurang (old).

etymology: Slang, derived from 'guwapo' (handsome) with the '-ing' suffix added for effect or possibly influenced by English.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa guwapo o magandang lalaki.
Slang term for a handsome or good-looking man.

examples.example: Mahilig ka kasi sa guwaping, e hindi ka naman kasi kagandahan.
You like guwaping (handsome men), but you're not even that pretty yourself.

etymology: Acronym for the English phrase 'Holding Hands While Walking'.

definitions.meaning: Akronim mula sa Ingles na 'Holding Hands While Walking'; ang paglalakad nang magkahawak ang mga kamay.
Acronym for 'Holding Hands While Walking'.

examples.example: Gustong-gusto ko talaga ka-h.h.w.w. si Peter tuwing nasa mall kami.
I really like h.h.w.w. (holding hands while walking) with Peter whenever we're at the mall.

etymology: Slang, likely derived from English 'head' (referring to oral sex) or another related term.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa oral sex o paggamit ng bibig sa pakikipagtalik.
Slang term for performing oral sex (fellatio).

examples.example: Bakit ka naman nakipag-hada sa taong kakakilala mo pa lang? Gumamit ka ba ng proteksiyon?
Why did you engage in hada (oral sex) with someone you just met? Did you use protection?

etymology: Tagalog word, can mean pursuer or someone chasing. In this context, slang for police escort, bodyguard, or chaperone.

definitions.meaning: Isang taong nagbabantay o sumasama bilang eskort o chaperone; maaaring pulis o bodyguard.
A police escort, bodyguard, or chaperone.

examples.example: Daming hagad ni Manny Pacquiao nung dumayo siya sa iskwater para mamigay ng tulong.
Manny Pacquiao had so many hagad (escorts/bodyguards) when he went to the squatter's area to give aid.

etymology: Slang, likely using the surname 'Hagedorn' (associated with a Filipino politician) as wordplay on 'haggard' or 'hapo' (tired, weary).

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang pagod o mukhang pagod.
Slang term meaning tired or looking tired/haggard.

examples.example: Hindi ka guwapo sa retrato, hagedorn ka na kasi dahil sa trabaho.
You don't look good in the picture because you're already hagedorn (tired-looking) from work.

etymology: Slang code word using 'hair spa' (a beauty treatment) to refer to methamphetamine (shabu), possibly due to the crystalline appearance or the stimulating effect.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal o code word para sa shabu (methamphetamine).
Slang code word for methamphetamine (shabu).

examples.example: Adik sa hair spa si Leslie kaya laging puyat at payat.
Leslie is addicted to hair spa (methamphetamine), and that's why she doesn't get enough sleep and is thin.

etymology: Slang, wordplay combining 'hair' and 'choreography' or 'pornography'. Refers to the act of dramatically flipping or tossing one's long hair, often to attract attention.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagwagayway o paglulugay ng mahabang buhok (karaniwan sa hangin) bilang paraan ng pagpapansin o pagpapakita.
The act of flipping or tossing one's long hair dramatically, especially to attract attention.

examples.example: Haironography na naman ako nang haironography, 'di pa rin niya ako napapansin!
I keep doing haironography (tossing my hair), but he still doesn't notice me!

etymology: Slang expression, playful elaboration of 'hair', adding 'ora' (common Bekimon suffix) and 'boulevard' for dramatic or humorous effect.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa buhok.
Slang term for hair.

examples.example: Ang haba ng hairora boulevard mo, girl, kaya patay na patay siya sa'yo.
Your hairora boulevard (hair) is so long, girl, and that's why he's really into you.

etymology: Slang, possibly derived from Japanese 'hyaku' (ç™¾) meaning 'hundred', or another source. Refers to one hundred pesos.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa isandaang piso (â‚±100).
Slang term for one hundred pesos (â‚±100).

examples.example: Tol, baka naman may haku ka diyan? Pambili ko lang ng yosi.
Dude, can you lend me haku (one hundred pesos)? I'll just buy a cigarette.

etymology: Slang, origin uncertain, distinct from the common interjection 'hala!'. Means to actively pursue or try to pick up someone, usually a man.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang manukso o subukang akitin ang isang lalaki (mamik-ap).
Slang term meaning to actively try to pick up or seduce a man.

examples.example: HalÃ¡ na si Robbie kay Gerard papunta sa motel.
Robbie just halÃ¡-ed (hit on/picked up) Gerard on the way to the motel.

etymology: Slang, possibly related to 'hada' or other similar terms for oral sex.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa pag-oral sex; tsumupa.
Slang term meaning to perform oral sex (fellatio).

examples.example: Nagpa-halÃ¡ siya sa CR.
He asked for/received a halÃ¡ (blow job) in the restroom.

etymology: Slang, possibly derived from 'halÃ¡' (pick up/seduce) or 'hala!' (interjection, implying brazenness), combined with '-an' suffix denoting action or place. Refers to the act of cruising or soliciting sex.

definitions.meaning: Ang paghahanap o pag-aalok ng serbisyong sekswal kapalit ng bayad; pag-book.
The act of cruising or soliciting for paid sex.

examples.example: Halaan na naman ang gagawin mo diyan sa kanto mamayang gabi?
Are you planning to make halaan (cruise/solicit) again on the corner tonight?

etymology: Slang, using 'ham' (the food) possibly as code or because â‚±100 bills were once reddish, similar to ham? Refers specifically to â‚±100 bills.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa pera na puro isandaang piso.
Slang term for money consisting of one-hundred-peso bills.

examples.example: Kitang-kita ko 'yung makapal na ham sa bag ni Mona.
I clearly saw the thick stack of ham (â‚±100 bills) in Mona's bag.

etymology: Slang, referencing the expensive 'Hummer' vehicle brand to imply high cost. Refers to a male sex worker who charges high fees.
sangkahulugan: mahal maningil (na lalaking nagbebenta ng aliw)

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa isang lalaking nagbebenta ng aliw na mataas o mahal maningil.
Slang term for a male sex worker who charges a high price, referenced from the expensive Hummer car brand.

examples.example: Hindi ko kaya i-book 'yan, hammer daw 'yan eh.
I can't afford to book him, they say he's a hammer (expensive).

etymology: Slang, likely derived from Japanese 'hanashi' (è©±) meaning 'talk' or 'story', but used in Filipino slang to mean lies or gossip.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa kasinungalingan, tsismis, o kwentong hindi totoo.
Slang term for lies, gossip, or untrue stories.

examples.example: Puro hanashi lang ang kinukuda ni Deborah kaya hindi na ako naniniwala sa kaniya.
Deborah is full of hanashi (lies/gossip), so I don't believe her anymore.

etymology: Tagalog slang expression, possibly related to 'hayop' (animal) but used as an intensifier meaning amazing, incredible, cool, or sometimes expressing exasperation.

definitions.meaning: Isang ekspresyon na nagpapahiwatig ng paghanga, pagkagulat, o kung minsan ay pagkadismaya; kahanga-hanga o grabe.
An expression denoting amazement, admiration, or sometimes exasperation; amazing, incredible, awesome.

examples.example: Hanep ka talaga, pare, pati utol ni Jake pinatulan mo!
Dude, you're so hanep (amazing/unbelievable), you even hit on Jake's sister!

etymology: Idiomatic expression literally meaning 'only up to the pier'. Used metaphorically for a spouse (usually the wife) who is abandoned by their partner who leaves (often implying going abroad by ship).

definitions.meaning: Isang idyoma para sa asawang iniwan o inabandona, lalo na ng partner na lumisan (hal. nag-abroad).
An idiom for a spouse who has been abandoned by their partner, especially one who has left (e.g., gone abroad).

examples.example: Kawawa naman si Claire, hanggang pier lang, dahil sumama sa iba si Jaime nang mag-barko ito.
Poor Claire, hanggang pier lang (abandoned at the pier), after Jaime ran away with another woman when he went abroad.

etymology: From English 'hangout', adopted into Filipino usage.

definitions.meaning: Isang lugar kung saan madalas magpunta o tumambay ang isang tao o grupo para magpalipas ng oras.
A place where someone frequently spends time; a favorite spot for relaxing or socializing.

examples.example: Sa mall ang paborito naming hangout ng barkada.
The mall is our favorite hangout spot for our group of friends.

etymology: From Hokkien Chinese (Min Nan) 'hÃ² siÃ u' (å¥½ç¬‘), literally 'good laugh' or 'funny', but used in Philippine context (especially media) to mean fake, bogus, corrupt, or unreliable, particularly referring to corrupt journalists who extort money.

definitions.meaning: Isang mapanirang termino, lalo na sa media, para sa isang pekeng mamamahayag na ginagamit ang posisyon para mangikil o gumawa ng korapsyon.
A derogatory term, especially in media circles, for a corrupt or fake journalist, often one involved in extortion.

examples.example: Mahirap magtiwala sa balita niya, hao siao kasi 'yang reporter na 'yan.
It's hard to trust his news report, because that reporter is known to be hao siao (corrupt/bogus).

etymology: Slang, reduplication of English 'happy' for emphasis or playful effect.

definitions.meaning: Ang maging masaya o magpakasaya.
To be happy or to have fun.

examples.example: Let's get hapi-hapi tayo sa bahay ni Mina!
Let's get hapi-hapi (let's have fun/be happy) at Mina's house!

etymology: Tagalog word literally meaning 'block' or 'obstruction'. Used metaphorically in slang to mean excessively high price, as if the price itself is an obstruction to buying.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang sobrang mahal o napakataas ng presyo.
Slang term meaning very expensive or overpriced.

examples.example: Harang naman 'yung presyo ng sapatos na 'yun, hindi ko mabili.
The price of those shoes is harang (very expensive). I can't afford them.

etymology: Tagalog word imitating the sound of speeding or rushing. Means to speed up, accelerate quickly, or rush.

definitions.meaning: Ang pabilisin ang takbo, lalo na ng sasakyan; magmadali.
To speed up, accelerate quickly, or rush.

examples.example: Humarurot na naman si Mike sa bago niyang motor, ang bilis!
Mike harurot (sped off/zoomed) again on his new motorcycle, so fast!

etymology: From English 'has-been', referring to someone who was once famous or successful but is no longer.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na dati'y sikat o matagumpay ngunit ngayo'y lipas na o laos na.
Someone who is no longer famous or successful.

examples.example: Has-been na kasi si Cherry kaya wala nang kumukuhang direktor sa kaniya.
Cherry is a has-been, and that's why no director is getting her to act anymore.

etymology: From English 'hassle', adopted into Filipino usage.

definitions.meaning: Isang abala, sagabal, o problema.
A problem, obstacle, nuisance, or inconvenience.

examples.example: Ang hassle naman ng traffic papuntang airport!
The traffic going to the airport is such a hassle!

etymology: From English 'hassle', used as a verb in Filipino slang.

definitions.meaning: Ang mang-abala, mang-istorbo, o mangulit.
To annoy, bother, or pester someone.

examples.example: Huwag mo akong i-hassle, marami akong ginagawa.
Don't hassle me, I have a lot to do.

etymology: Tagalog word literally meaning 'strike' or 'hit'. Used metaphorically to describe an energetic, powerful, or impressive performance.

definitions.meaning: Isang mahusay, todo-bigay, o impresibong performance.
An impressive, energetic, or all-out performance.

examples.example: Hataw ang performance ng big winner na si Ai-Ai sa concert niya.
Ai-Ai was so hataw (gave an impressive performance) in her concert.

etymology: Tagalog word literally meaning 'strike' or 'hit'. Used metaphorically in the context of dancing to mean dancing energetically or wildly.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagsayaw nang todo-bigay o buong enerhiya.
Dancing energetically or giving an all-out dance performance.

examples.example: Hataw kung hataw ang grupo nila sa dance floor.
Their group was really hataw (dancing all out) on the dance floor.

etymology: Slang, playful alteration of English 'have', adding the common Bekimon suffix '-ella'.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa 'mayroon' o 'meron'.
Slang term for 'have' or 'possess'.

examples.example: Do you havella some extra money na pwedeng ipahiram?
Do you havella (have) some extra money you can lend?

etymology: Slang expression, emphatic reduplication of 'have', implying someone 'has it' in terms of looks.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyong balbal na nangangahulugang ubod ng ganda o kagwapuhan; 'may dating'.
Slang expression meaning very beautiful or handsome; gorgeous.

examples.example: Sobrang have-na-have si Irene sa suot niyang gown.
Irene is so have-na-have (gorgeous) in the gown she's wearing.

etymology: Slang, likely derived from 'have' (implying something 'has' quality) or possibly related to 'heavy' (impressive). Means good, great, successful, impressive.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang maganda, mahusay, panalo, o aprubado.
Slang term meaning great, grand, beautiful, impressive, or successful.

examples.example: Havey ang gown ni Mareng Winnie sa kasal, lahat napatingin.
Mareng Winnie's wedding gown was so havey (impressive/beautiful), everyone looked.

etymology: Tagalog interjection expressing a sigh, often indicating relief, resignation, weariness, or exasperation.

definitions.meaning: Isang interjection na katumbas ng buntong-hininga; nagpapahiwatig ng ginhawa, pagod, pagkadismaya, atbp.
An interjection representing a sigh, expressing relief, weariness, resignation, exasperation, etc.

examples.example: Hay, buti na lang hindi ako tumuloy pumusta. Talo pala.
Hay (Sigh), it's a good thing I didn't place a bet. I would have lost!

etymology: Slang, likely from reversing syllables of 'bahay' (house) -> 'hay-ba' and adding '-ol' suffix, or other playful alteration.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa bahay o tirahan.
Slang term for house or home.

examples.example: Ang gara naman ng haybol nina Joan.
Joan's haybol (house) is so charming.

etymology: Acronym for the English phrase 'Hidden Desire'.

definitions.meaning: Akronim para sa Ingles na 'Hidden Desire'; isang lihim na pagnanasa o pagkagusto sa isang tao.
Acronym for 'Hidden Desire'; a secret longing or crush on someone.

examples.example: Alam ko namang matagal ka nang may HD diyan kay Mark.
I know you've had an HD (hidden desire) for Mark for a long time now.

etymology: From English 'heaven', used metaphorically to describe a state of extreme pleasure, bliss, or happiness, sometimes specifically sexual pleasure.

definitions.meaning: Ang pakiramdam ng sukdulang kaligayahan, sarap, o bliss; pakiramdam na parang nasa langit.
A feeling of extreme happiness, pleasure, or bliss; feeling like one is floating or in paradise.

examples.example: Heaven ang pakiramdam ko nang kainin ako ni Maning.
It felt like heaven when Maning performed oral sex on me.

etymology: From English 'heavy', used to describe an emotional burden or sadness.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa pakiramdam na mabigat sa kalooban dahil sa lungkot o problema.
Referring to a feeling of emotional heaviness, sadness, or burden.

examples.example: Heavy sa pakiramdam ang pagkamatay ng pusa kong si Aureng.
I feel heavy (sad/burdened) because of the death of my cat, Aureng.

etymology: From English 'heavy', used as an exclamation similar to 'wow' or 'grabe' to express awe, surprise, or intensity.

definitions.meaning: Isang ekspresyon ng pagkamangha, pagkagulat, o pagdama sa intensidad ng isang bagay.
An expression used to show awe, surprise, or intensity.

examples.example: Nanalo siya sa lotto? Heavy!
He won the lottery? Heavy (Wow/Intense)!

etymology: Taglish slang combining English 'heavy' and Tagalog 'bigat' (weight/heavy), often with '-in-' infix (becoming 'hebigat'). Means literally heavy, or metaphorically powerful, influential, or difficult to deal with.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang mabigat, o sa metaporikal na gamit, bigatin, makapangyarihan, o malakas.
Slang term meaning heavy, or metaphorically, powerful, influential, or formidable ('heavyweight').

examples.example: Hebigat ang mga binabangga mong tao kaya mag-ingat ka.
The people you're fighting are hebigat (powerful/influential), so be careful.

etymology: Slang, origin uncertain, possibly related to other coded terms for sexual activity.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa pagtatalik o sex.
Slang term for sexual intercourse; sex.

examples.example: Nauwi sa hekya ang date nina Danding at Lupe.
Danding and Lupe's date ended up in hekya (sex).

etymology: Tagalog idiom. 'Hele-hele' implies swaying or hesitation (like rocking a baby). 'Kyere' likely from Spanish 'quiere' (wants/loves). The phrase describes someone who initially acts coy, hesitant, or uninterested ('hele-hele') but eventually gives in or reveals their true desire ('kyere'). Playing hard to get.

definitions.meaning: Isang idyoma para sa taong nagpapakipot o kunwaring ayaw sa simula, ngunit may lihim na pagnanasa o pagpayag din pala sa huli.
An idiom describing someone who pretends to be uninterested or plays hard to get initially, but actually has hidden desire or eventually agrees.

examples.example: Pa-hele-hele bago kyere pa si Luis noon, pero naging mag-jowa rin kami kalaunan.
Luis was very hele-hele bago kyere (playing hard to get) back then, but we became lovers eventually.

etymology: Slang, metaphorical use of 'helmet' (protective headgear) to refer to a condom, implying protection.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa condom.
Slang term for a condom.

examples.example: Magsuot ka ng helmet bago kayo gumawa ng milagro.
Wear a helmet (condom) before you do it (have sex).

etymology: Slang, possibly related to 'hipon' (shrimp - slang for someone with a good body but unattractive face) and 'maliit' (small). Refers specifically to a short person with a good body but an unattractive face.
synonyms: short person with a good body but ugly face

definitions.meaning: Isang taong pandak o maliit na maganda ang katawan ngunit pangit ang mukha; kombinasyon ng 'hipon' at 'maliit'.
A short person with an attractive body but an unattractive face; a blend of 'hipon' (shrimp/butterface) and 'maliit' (small).

examples.example: Puro hibi ang nakikita ko sa gym na 'to.
There are a lot of hibi (short guys with good bodies but ugly faces) in this gym.

etymology: Tagalog word for 'hairy caterpillar'. Used metaphorically in slang to refer to a promiscuous or flirtatious person, possibly because caterpillars move around a lot or due to the irritating nature of some caterpillars.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa taong malandi, makati, o promiscuous.
Slang term for a flirtatious or promiscuous person.

examples.example: Mahilig pumatol sa may asawa ang higad na 'yan kaya nasira ang pamilya nila.
That higad (promiscuous person/homewrecker) likes to get involved with married people.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa hika.
Slang term for asthma.

examples.example: Inatake na naman ng hiks si Girlie kaya napahinto sila sa pagse-sex.
Girlie had a hiks (asthma attack), and that's why she had to stop making love to her partner.

etymology: Tagalog word meaning dizzy or nauseated. In slang, can also mean absent-minded, confused, or not focused.

definitions.meaning: Pagiging wala sa sarili, lutang, o hindi alam ang ginagawa.
Being absent-minded, distracted, confused, or spaced out.

examples.example: Mag-pokus ka nga! Hilo ka na naman sa iniisip mo!
Just focus! You're hilo (distracted/spaced out) again!

etymology: Tagalog word meaning dizzy or nauseated.

definitions.meaning: Ang pakiramdam na umiikot ang paningin o nasusuka.
Feeling dizzy, giddy, or nauseated.

examples.example: Nahihilo ako sa taas ng building.
I feel hilo (dizzy) from the height of the building.

etymology: Tagalog derogatory term combining 'hina-' (prefix implying lack or lowliness) and 'hayop' (animal). Means animalistic, shameless, rude, or despicable.

definitions.meaning: Isang mapanirang termino para sa taong may asal-hayop, walang hiya, bastos, o kasuklam-suklam.
A derogatory term for someone who acts like an animal; shameless, rude, disrespectful, or despicable.

examples.example: Hinayupak talaga si Jake, ang bastos ng bunganga!
Jake is really a hinayupak (shameless/rude person). He's so rude!

etymology: Taglish expression combining Tagalog 'hindi' (not) and English 'take' (tolerate, stand).

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyon na nangangahulugang hindi makaya, hindi matiis, o hindi matagalan ang isang bagay o sitwasyon.
Expression meaning one cannot tolerate, stand, or bear something or a situation.

examples.example: Hindi ko ma-take ang amoy ng putok ni Princess, nananapak talaga!
Princess's body odor smells bad, hindi ma-take (I can't take/stand it)!

etymology: Tagalog idiom literally meaning 'we are not defeated/unequal' or 'we are not opponents'. Used to mean 'we are the same', 'we are in the same boat', 'we are not rivals', or 'we are equals (so we can't be together)'. Context determines the exact nuance.

definitions.meaning: Isang idyoma na nangangahulugang 'pareho lang tayo', 'hindi tayo magkaaway', o 'pantay lang tayo' (kaya hindi maaaring maging magkarelasyon, sa ibang konteksto).
An idiom meaning 'we are the same', 'we are not opponents', or 'we are equals' (implying incompatibility as a couple in some contexts).

examples.example: Troll ka, memer ako, kaya hindi tayo talÃ³ (pareho lang tayong nanggugulo online).
You are a troll, I just make memes, hindi tayo talÃ³ (we are the same/not opponents).

etymology: Visayan curse word, used here in slang to mean 'easy to get', possibly derived from the vulgar connotations.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal (mula sa Visayan na mura) na nangangahulugang madaling makuha o 'easy to get' (madalas tumutukoy sa babae, mapanira).
Slang term (from a Visayan curse word) meaning easy to get (often referring to a woman, derogatory).

examples.example: Maraming nagsasabi na hindot daw si Ana.
Many say that Ana is hindot (easy to get).

etymology: Visayan curse word, used as an interjection to express strong emotion like surprise, anger, or frustration.

definitions.meaning: Isang bulalas (mula sa Visayan na mura) na nagpapahayag ng matinding emosyon tulad ng pagkagulat, galit, o pagkadismaya.
An interjection (from a Visayan curse word) expressing strong emotion such as surprise, anger, or frustration.

examples.example: Hindot! Naiwan ko ang wallet ko!
Hindot (Damn it)! I left my wallet!

etymology: Visayan curse word, used here in slang as a vulgar term for sexual intercourse.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal (mula sa Visayan na mura) na nangangahulugang makipagtalik.
Slang term (from a Visayan curse word) meaning to have sex.

examples.example: Nag-hindot sila sa kotse.
They hindot-ed (had sex/fucked) in the car.

etymology: Slang expression, wordplay using the phrase 'Hip Hop Hooray' (title of a song) to sound like 'hepatitis'.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal o code word para sa sakit na hepatitis o paninilaw (jaundice).
Slang term or code word for hepatitis or jaundice.

examples.example: Huwag kang kakain ng street food kila Bebang. Doon ako nagka-hip hop hooray dati.
Don't eat street food from Bebang's stall. That's where I got hip hop hooray (hepatitis) before.

etymology: Slang derogatory term combining 'hipon' (shrimp; slang for person with good body but ugly face) and 'Hapones/Haponesa' (Japanese). Refers to a person, often with East Asian features, who fits the 'hipon' description.

definitions.meaning: Isang mapanirang termino para sa taong may magandang katawan ngunit pangit ang mukha, at may hitsurang Hapon o Chinito/Chinita.
A derogatory term for a person with an attractive body but unattractive face, who also has East Asian features (like almond eyes).

examples.example: Mabait ba 'yang hipones mong manliligaw?
Is that hipones (good body/ugly face guy with Asian features) who is courting you a good guy?

etymology: Tagalog word. Can mean to pull tight, strain, or in this context, to make an additional request, plea, or comment; to ask for more.

definitions.meaning: Ang humiling ng dagdag, humabol ng komento, o gumawa ng karagdagang pakiusap.
To ask for more, make an additional request or comment, or interject.

examples.example: Hihirit ka pa ng dessert, busog na busog ka na nga!
You are still making hirit (asking for more) for dessert, even though you're already very full!

etymology: Tagalog word. Related to the idea of 'stretching' or 'pulling', can mean speaking continuously or delivering a long line/speech without interruption.

definitions.meaning: Ang magsalita nang tuloy-tuloy o walang patid; bumanat ng mahabang linya.
To talk uninterruptedly or deliver a long line/speech.

examples.example: Humirit siya ng paliwanag nang walang tigil.
He made a hirit (spoke continuously) explaining without stopping.

etymology: From English 'hit-and-run' (referring to traffic accidents), used metaphorically to mean abandoning a task, responsibility, or situation irresponsibly.

definitions.meaning: Ang pag-iwan o pagtakas sa isang gawain o responsibilidad nang hindi ito tinatapos o inaayos.
To abandon a task or responsibility unfinished; to act irresponsibly by leaving.

examples.example: Nag-hit-and-run na naman si Juan sa trabaho niya, iniwan lang basta.
Juan did a hit-and-run from work again, just leaving it unfinished.

etymology: Slang, using the name 'Hitler' metaphorically to refer to someone perceived as extremely strict, authoritarian, or dictatorial, like a boss or teacher.

definitions.meaning: Isang termino para sa isang amo, guro, o sinumang nasa awtoridad na napakahigpit, masungit, o diktador magdisiplina.
A term for a boss, teacher, or authority figure who is extremely strict, harsh, or dictatorial.

examples.example: Hitler naman si Ms. Cruz kaya walang pumapasa sa klase niya.
Ms. Cruz is a Hitler (very strict/tyrannical), and that's why almost everyone in her class fails.

etymology: Slang, derogatory term using the onomatopoeia for a horse's sound ('neigh' or 'hee-haw' suggested by 'hiyah') to describe a gay person perceived as having horse-like facial features.

definitions.meaning: Isang mapanirang termino para sa baklang sinasabing mukhang kabayo.
A derogatory term for a gay person said to look like a horse.

examples.example: Inaamin naman ni Vice Ganda (pabiro) na hiyah-hiyah siya.
Vice Ganda admits (jokingly) that he's a hiyah-hiyah (looks like a horse).

etymology: Tagalog word meaning 'gem' or 'jewel'. Used metaphorically and euphemistically in slang to refer to the vagina.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal (euphemism) para sa ari ng babae.
Slang term (euphemism) for vagina.

examples.example: Mabango daw ang hiyas ni Martha kaya enjoy na enjoy si Yoyoy.
They say Martha's hiyas (vagina) smells good, and that's why Yoyoy is enjoying it so much.

etymology: Slang, likely a playful alteration or code word for 'lalaki' (man) or 'hombre' (man). Origin unclear.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa lalaki.
Slang term for man or guy.

examples.example: Napagtanto ni Ricardo na homebash pala ang tipo niya, hindi babae.
Ricardo realized that he likes homebash (men), not women.

etymology: From Spanish 'hombre' meaning 'man'. Used in Filipino specifically to refer to a Spanish man, or more broadly, a Caucasian man, often one perceived as attractive or 'macho', sometimes specifically hairy.

definitions.meaning: Lalaking Espanyol, o mas pangkalahatan, lalaking puti (Caucasian), lalo na kung balbon.
A Spanish man, or more generally, a Caucasian man, especially a hairy one.

examples.example: Gusto ni Michelle ang hombreng si Isaac dahil mukha itong foreigner.
Michelle likes the hombre Isaac because he looks like a foreigner.

etymology: Slang, likely derived from English 'home' + '-li' suffix, or related to 'homebody'. Refers to a homebody.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na mas gustong mamalagi sa bahay kaysa lumabas; taong-bahay.
Someone who prefers to stay at home; a homebody.

examples.example: Naging mabuti pa nga ang ECQ (Enhanced Community Quarantine) dahil bumagay ito sa pagiging homli ni Mario.
The ECQ was actually favorable for the homli (homebody) Mario.

etymology: Shortened form of 'homosexual'. Often used colloquially, sometimes neutrally, sometimes derogatorily.

definitions.meaning: Pinaikling salita para sa 'homosexual'; bakla o binabae.
Shortened form of 'homosexual'; gay.

examples.example: Hindi niya itinatago na isa siyang homo.
He doesn't hide the fact that he is homo (gay).

etymology: Slang term using the surname of Filipino politician Gringo Honasan (known for leading coup attempts) and adding the Japanese honorific '-san'. Refers to a rebel or someone perceived as rebellious.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa rebelde, mula sa pangalan ni Gringo Honasan na dinugtungan ng '-san'.
Slang term for a rebel, derived from the name Gringo Honasan combined with the Japanese honorific '-san'.

examples.example: Laging kontra sa management, parang ho-na-san.
Always against management, like a ho-na-san (rebel).

etymology: Slang, using the car brand 'Honda', possibly implying old or outdated, perhaps referencing older models or simply as wordplay.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang matanda na o napag-iwanan na ng panahon.
Slang term meaning old or outdated.

examples.example: Honda na ang lolo mo kaya kailangan nang alalayan maglakad.
Your grandfather is honda (old), so you need to assist him when walking.

etymology: Slang, likely a blend of English 'hormone' (referring to hormone therapy) and Spanish 'mamada' (suckling, relating to breasts) or '-ada' suffix. Refers to a gay person taking hormones to develop breasts.

definitions.meaning: Isang beki na umiinom ng hormones para lumaki ang dibdib.
A gay person taking hormones, typically to induce breast growth.

examples.example: Matagal na siyang hormonada kaya malaki na ang dibdib.
She's been a hormonada (taking hormones) for a long time, that's why her breasts are large.

etymology: Slang, possibly derived from 'host' or 'hostess', specifically referring to male dancers or performers in certain types of bars ('hosto bars'). Often implies they entertain customers, potentially including sexual services.

definitions.meaning: Isang lalaking mananayaw o entertainer sa isang hosto bar, na maaaring umaliw sa mga kostumer.
A male dancer or entertainer in a 'hosto bar'.

examples.example: Naniniwala siyang masarap magmahal ang isang hosto.
She believes it must be wonderful to be loved by a hosto (male bar dancer/entertainer).

etymology: Slang term for a bar featuring 'hostos' (male dancers/entertainers) who interact with customers, often implying paid companionship or potential sexual services.
sangkahulugan: bar na may mga lalaking mananayaw

definitions.meaning: Isang bar o bahay-aliwan na nagtatampok ng mga lalaking mananayaw (hosto) na umaaliw sa mga kostumer.
A bar or entertainment venue featuring male dancers (hostos) who entertain customers.

examples.example: Nagpauto ka na naman! Sa hosto bar 'yon nagtatrabaho, sanay 'yon mambola.
You are so gullible! He works at a hosto bar; he's used to sweet-talking people.

etymology: Slang, playful alteration of 'hostess', possibly blending with 'hustisya' (justice) ironically, or just adding a suffix. Refers to a hostess in a bar, often implying prostitution.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa hostess sa bar, na kadalasan ay may implikasyon ng pagiging prostitute.
Slang term for a bar hostess, often implying prostitution.

examples.example: Huwag mo nang ipaalala ang nakaraan ko. Graduate na ako bilang hostisiya.
Don't remind me of my past. I already graduated from being a hostisiya (hostess/prostitute).

etymology: Tagalog word for 'chameleon'. Used metaphorically in slang to refer to a closeted gay man who 'changes color' or hides his true identity.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa isang lalaking bistado nang bakla (o pinaghihinalaang bakla) ngunit ayaw pang umamin o itinatago pa rin ito.
Slang term for a man perceived to be gay but who has not come out or denies it; a closeted gay man.

examples.example: Tingin ko si Sir John, hunyango 'yan. Halata naman pero ayaw umamin.
I think Sir John is a hunyango (closeted gay). It's obvious, but he won't admit it.

etymology: Text speak/online slang abbreviation or phonetic spelling of 'Who you?' or 'Who are you?'.

definitions.meaning: Sa text/chat, pinaikling tanong na 'Sino ka?'.
Text/chat slang for 'Who are you?'.

examples.example: Hu u? Wrong send ka yata ng message.
Hu u (Who are you)? You must have messaged the wrong number.

etymology: Slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'bibig' (mouth) or other words related to speaking.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang sabihin o ipahayag.
Slang term meaning to say or state something.

examples.example: Ibera mo na ang lahat ng nalalaman mo tungkol sa kaso.
Ibera (Say/Tell) everything you know about the case.

etymology: Text speak/online slang abbreviation for the English phrase 'I see'.

definitions.meaning: Sa text/chat, daglat para sa 'I see'; nangangahulugang naintindihan.
Text/chat slang abbreviation for 'I see'; meaning 'I understand'.

examples.example: A: Busy ako mamaya. B: ic
A: I'm busy later. B: ic (I see)

etymology: Slang, possibly a playful alteration of 'huwag' (don't) or English 'don't'.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa 'huwag'.
Slang term for 'don't'.

examples.example: Idush mo akong subukan. Hindi mo kakayanin ang galit ko.
Idush (Don't) you dare try me. You will not like it when I am angry.

definitions.meaning: Pinaikling salita para sa 'kaibigan'.
Shortened term for 'kaibigan' (friend).

examples.example: Igan, usap tayo mamaya tungkol diyan.
Igan (Friend), let's talk about that later.

etymology: Slang expression using the name of Filipina actress Nora Aunor as wordplay on 'ignore'. Refers to the act of ignoring someone or being a snob.

definitions.meaning: Ang hindi pagpansin sa isang tao; mag-snob.
To ignore someone; to snob.

examples.example: Ignora aunor naman sa personal si Nadine, hindi man lang ngumingiti.
Nadine is ignora aunor (a snob/ignores people) in person; she doesn't even smile.

etymology: Slang, playful alteration of 'ikaw' (you), adding the common Bekimon suffix '-chi'.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa panghalip na 'ikaw'.
Slang term for the pronoun 'you'.

examples.example: Ikawchi na ang magbayad ng kinain natin sa motmot (mall).
Ikawchi (You) pay for what we ate at the motmot (mall).

etymology: Slang, origin uncertain. Means 'not much', 'not very', or 'slightly'.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang 'hindi masyado' o 'hindi gaano'.
Slang term meaning 'not much' or 'not very'.

examples.example: Iklay lang naman siyang maganda, mas maganda ka pa.
She's iklay (only slightly/not very) pretty; you are prettier.

etymology: Slang expression literally meaning 'how many watts?'. Used metaphorically to imply someone is dim-witted or stupid, as if their brain has low wattage.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyong balbal na nangangahulugang bobo, tanga, o mahina ang pag-iisip.
Slang expression meaning stupid, dumb, or dim-witted.

examples.example: Ilang watts talaga si Berting kaya hindi pumapasa sa mga exam niya.
Berting is really ilang watts (stupid/dim-witted), that's why he doesn't pass his exams.

etymology: Tagalog word for 'funnel'. Used metaphorically in slang to mean annoyed, irritated, or fed up, possibly because funnels get clogged or backed up.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang naiinis, nayayamot, o napipikon.
Slang term meaning irritated, annoyed, or fed up.

examples.example: Naka-imbudo na ako sa crush ko. Hindi man lang ako pinapansin!
My crush is so imbudo (making me annoyed/irritated). He doesn't notice me!

etymology: Slang, possibly a blend of 'criminal' and 'thin', or another obscure wordplay. Means extremely thin or emaciated.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na tumutukoy sa sobrang kapayatan; buto't balat.
Slang term for being extremely thin; skin and bones.

examples.example: Nagkasakit ba siya? Mukhang incri-mhin na siya ngayon.
Was he sick? He looks incri-mhin (very thin) now.

etymology: Slang expression using 'Inday' (common Visayan term of address for a young woman, sometimes used for house helpers) and 'G' (possibly for 'Gutom' - hungry, or implying lack). Means poor or not rich.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang mahirap o hindi mayaman.
Slang term meaning not rich or poor.

examples.example: Malalaman mo kung sino ang Inday G. kapag dating sa bayaran.
You'll know who is Inday G. (the poor one/not rich) when it comes to paying.

etymology: Slang expression, using the name 'Indiana Jones', likely as wordplay on 'Indian' (Filipino slang for someone who doesn't show up for an appointment) + 'Jones' (common surname, or just for effect). Refers to a person who flakes or doesn't show up.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na hindi sumisipot sa usapan o appointment; indiyanero.
A person who doesn't show up for an agreed meeting or appointment; a no-show or flaker.

examples.example: Indiana jones si Miguel, laging di dumarating sa meeting.
Miguel is an Indiana Jones (no-show/flaker), always absent from meetings.

etymology: Slang expression, related to the above, referring to the act of not showing up.

definitions.meaning: Ang akto ng hindi pagsipot sa isang usapan o appointment.
The act of not showing up for an appointment; absence or flaking.

examples.example: Nainis ako sa Indiana Jones niya kahapon.
I was annoyed by his Indiana Jones (not showing up) yesterday.

etymology: Slang, derived from 'Indian' (Filipino slang for someone who doesn't show up, origin debated) + '-ero' (Spanish suffix for doer). Refers to a person who habitually doesn't show up for appointments.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na ugaling hindi sumipot sa mga usapan o appointment.
Someone who habitually doesn't show up for agreed-upon meetings; a no-show or flaker.

examples.example: Huwag kang umasa diyan, indiyanero 'yan.
Don't count on him, he's an indiyanero (flaker).

etymology: Slang, playful Bekimon-style alteration of English 'in love'.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa 'in love' o umiibig.
Slang term for being 'in love'.

examples.example: Inlavavoh ka na naman kaya pilyo ang ngiti mo.
You're inlavavoh (in love) again, that's why you're grinning mischievously.

definitions.meaning: Pinaikling salita para sa 'pinsan'.
Shortened word for 'pinsan' (cousin).

examples.example: Insan ko si Piolo kaya medyo magkamukha kami.
Piolo is my insan (cousin), that's why we look somewhat alike.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal (wordplay) na nangangahulugang 'insecure' o kulang sa tiwala sa sarili.
Slang term (wordplay) meaning 'insecure' or having low self-esteem.

examples.example: Takot makipag-usap sa mga tao si Rodel dahil sa pagka-insect niya.
Rodel is afraid of talking to people because of his insect (insecure) attitude.

etymology: Slang, derogatory wordplay using 'insecticide' (pesticide) to refer to a Chinese person ('Intsik').

definitions.meaning: Mapanirang salitang balbal (wordplay) para sa 'Intsik'.
Derogatory slang term (wordplay) for a Chinese person.

examples.example: Huwag naman sanang sakupin ng mga insecticide ang Pilipinas.
I hope the insecticide (Chinese people) won't invade the Philippines.

etymology: From Spanish 'intriga' (intrigue) + '-era' (feminine suffix for doer). Refers to a woman who creates intrigues, spreads gossip, or causes trouble.

definitions.meaning: Isang babae na mahilig gumawa ng intriga, magkalat ng tsismis, o manggulo.
A woman who creates intrigues, spreads gossip, or causes trouble; an intriguer.

examples.example: Intrigera talaga si Tita Cristy, lahat na lang pinupuna.
Tita Cristy is such an intrigera (intriguer/gossip).

etymology: From Spanish 'entrometido/a' (meddlesome). Refers to a person who meddles or interferes in other people's affairs; a busybody.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na mahilig makialam o manghimasok sa usapin o buhay ng iba; pakialamero/a.
Someone who meddles or interferes in other people's business; a busybody.

examples.example: Ayaw ni Monching sa biyenan niyang intrimitida dahil laging nakikialam sa buhay nila.
Monching doesn't like his mother-in-law who is an intrimitida (meddler).

etymology: Slang expression using the name 'Irma dela Cruz' as wordplay, possibly on 'dumi' (dirt/feces) or other related terms. Means to defecate.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang dumumi o tumae.
Slang term meaning to defecate.

examples.example: Ilang araw nang hindi maka-irma dela cruz si Tess dahil constipated.
Tess hasn't been able to irma dela cruz (defecate) for days because she's constipated.

etymology: Tagalog name for grilled chicken or pork intestines, a popular Filipino street food.

definitions.meaning: Inihaw na bituka ng manok o baboy na karaniwang tinitinda bilang street food.
Grilled chicken or pork intestines, a common Filipino street food.

examples.example: Paboritong pulutan ni Dessa ang isaw.
Dessa's favorite appetizer/snack is isaw (grilled intestines).

etymology: Tagalog word for 'fish'. Used metaphorically in slang, possibly implying the younger partner is being 'caught' or supported by the older one, or related to age gap dynamics.
sangkahulugan: batang bakla (na may karelasyong matandang bakla)
synonyms: young gay man (with an older gay partner)

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa isang batang bakla na karelasyon o kasama ng isang matandang bakla.
Slang term for a young gay man who is in a relationship with or accompanies an older gay man.

examples.example: Nakatutuwang pagmasdan ang mga isda kapag kasama ang kanilang 'tatay-tatayan'.
It's amusing to see the isda (young gay partner) when he's with his sugar daddy.

etymology: Tagalog derogatory expression literally meaning 'cockroach-brained'. Implies stupidity or lack of intelligence.

definitions.meaning: Isang mapanirang ekspresyon na nangangahulugang mangmang, bobo, tanga, o walang alam.
A derogatory expression meaning ignorant, stupid, or dumb.

examples.example: Isip-ipis pa rin hanggang ngayon si Marie kaya walang seryosong nagkakagusto sa kaniya.
Marie is still isip-ipis (stupid/ignorant), that's why no guy will seriously like her.

etymology: Shortened colloquial term for 'iskolar' (scholar), specifically referring to students of state universities like the University of the Philippines (UP), who are often called 'Iskolar ng Bayan' (Scholar of the Nation). 'Isko' for male, 'Iska' for female.
sangkahulugan: estudyante ng UP (o ibang state university)

definitions.meaning: Kolokyal na tawag sa isang iskolar, lalo na sa estudyante ng Unibersidad ng Pilipinas (UP) o ibang pampublikong unibersidad.
Colloquial term for a scholar, especially a student of the University of the Philippines (UP) or another state university.

examples.example: Maraming matatalinong isko at iska sa UP.
There are many smart isko (male scholars) and iska (female scholars) at UP.

etymology: From English 'score', used in slang to mean succeeding in finding a sexual partner or 'getting lucky'. The definition 'to puff' seems less common or possibly incorrect context.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal mula sa Ingles na 'score'; ang magtagumpay na makakuha ng kasiping o ka-sex.
Slang from English 'score'; to succeed in finding a sexual partner; to get lucky or hook up.

examples.example: Brad, naka-iskor ka raw kagabi kay Ester, ah? Congrats!
Bro, heard you were able to iskor (score/get lucky) with Ester last night, huh? Congrats!

etymology: Tagalog slang, from the title of a popular old Filipino comedy TV show 'Iskul Bukol'. Refers to someone who doesn't take school seriously, a slacker, or a truant.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao (karaniwan ay estudyante) na bulakbol, tamad mag-aral, o hindi sineseryoso ang pag-aaral.
Someone (usually a student) who is a slacker, truant, or doesn't take school seriously.

examples.example: Iskul-bukol ako noong high school. Wala tuloy akong natapos na kurso.
I was an iskul-bukol (slacker student) back in high school. That's why I couldn't finish a degree.

etymology: Slang, origin uncertain, possibly playful or onomatopoeic. Means naive, ignorant, or clueless.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal na nangangahulugang walang alam, inosente, o mangmang.
Slang term meaning naive, ignorant, or clueless.

examples.example: Marami talagang iskurukutoy na nagkakalat ng fake news sa Facebook.
There are really a lot of iskurukutoy (naive/clueless people) spreading fake news on Facebook.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa 'iskwater'; isang taong umuukopa ng lupa o ari-arian nang walang pahintulot.
Slang term for 'squatter'; someone occupying land or property without legal right or permission.

examples.example: Hindi ko akalain na mapupunta lang sa pagtulong sa mga iskwakwa ang perang pinag-ipunan namin.
I didn't expect that the money we saved would just end up helping iskwakwa (squatters).

etymology: Slang verb derived from English 'small', often with Tagalog affixation (e.g., 'in-ismol'). Means to belittle, underestimate, or look down on someone.

definitions.meaning: Ang maliitin, hamakin, o babaan ang tingin sa isang tao.
To belittle, underestimate, or look down on someone.

examples.example: Huwag mong ismolin si Lito dahil lang mahirap siya; bigatin 'yan sa ibang bagay.
Don't you ismolin (belittle/underestimate) Lito just because he's poor; he's a heavyweight ('bigatin') in other aspects.

etymology: Humorous slang expression mocking Filipinos who try too hard to speak English with an American accent ('dollar'), often incorrectly ('ispokening' instead of 'speaking').
synonyms: trying hard to speak English (with accent)

definitions.meaning: Isang mapanuyang termino para sa Pilipinong pilit na nag-iingles na may puntong Amerikano, madalas mali-mali pa.
A mocking term for a Filipino who tries too hard to speak English, especially with an American accent, often making grammatical errors.

examples.example: Grabe si Kulas, ispokening dolar pero pilipit naman ang dila at mali-mali ang grammar.
I can't believe Kulas. He's ispokening dolar (trying hard to sound American), but his tongue is twisted and his grammar is wrong.

etymology: Slang, origin uncertain, possibly onomatopoeic or playful invention. Refers to a sudden, often mischievous or unconventional, idea or impulse.

definitions.meaning: Isang biglaang ideya, naiisip na kalokohan, o pakana.
A sudden idea, whim, impulse, or mischievous thought.

examples.example: Ayan ka na naman, bakla. Kinakabahan ako sa mga isprikitik mo sa utak.
There you go again, friend. I get nervous with your isprikitik (sudden weird ideas). You always get us in trouble.

etymology: Slang, likely derived from English 'sporting' (as in sporting fancy clothes) or 'spotting' (being noticeable), possibly with Bekimon suffix.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang taong nakadamit nang magara, nakaporma, o fashionable.
Referring to someone who is well-dressed, fashionable, or wearing fancy clothes.

examples.example: Ang taray talaga, laging isputing si Gretchen!
She's so fierce, Gretchen is always isputing (well-dressed/fashionable)!

definitions.meaning: Taong madalas tumigil o manatili sa isang lugar nang walang partikular na ginagawa.
Someone who frequently stays or hangs around in one place, often without doing anything productive; an idler or loafer.

examples.example: Istambay lang si Mario, tinutustusan lang ng magulang.
Mario is just an istambay (idler) who gets support from his parents.

definitions.meaning: Humimpil, tumigil, o manatili sa isang lugar.
To stay, stand by, hang around, or loiter.

etymology: Combination of English 'star' and Filipino 'taray' (fierce, sharp)

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang taong sikat, popular, o tanyag, madalas may halong paghanga o bahagyang sarkasmo.
Referring to someone who is famous or popular, often used admiringly or slightly sarcastically.

examples.example: Istariray ka, day! Ang dami mong tagahanga.
You're istariray (a star)! You've got so many fans.

etymology: Likely from English 'steer' (as in mislead) or 'stir' (as in cause trouble/deceive), adapted into Bekimon/slang.

definitions.meaning: Manloko, mambola, o magpaasa, lalo na sa pamamagitan ng hindi totoong pangako.
To deceive, fool, or lead someone on, especially with false promises.

examples.example: Sasama ka ba talaga o ini-istir mo lang ako?
Are you going to join or are you just istir-ing (leading me on / making empty promises)?

etymology: Bekimon/slang term, origin uncertain. Could be a playful transformation.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa pagtakas o paglayas sa bahay, lalo na kasama ang isang kasintahan o dahil sa isang alitan.
Referring to the act of running away from home, often secretly or to elope.

examples.example: Iniisip ni Marie na mag-istokwa kasama ang kaniyang kasintahan.
Marie is thinking of going istokwa (running away) with her boyfriend.

etymology: Bekimon/gay slang formation, playful alteration of 'ito' (this/it) with a Japanese-sounding suffix '-shiwa'.

definitions.meaning: Isang panghalip na pamatlig (demonstrative pronoun); ito, iyan, o iyon.
A demonstrative pronoun; this, that, or it.

examples.example: Itashiwa ba ang hinahanap mong suklay?
Are you looking for itashiwa (this/that) comb?

definitions.meaning: Makipagtalik.
To have sexual intercourse.

examples.example: Iyot na tayo agad pagkauwi, milabs.
Let's iyot (have sex) when we get home, milabs (my love).

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain, possibly related to or influenced by other words for 'small' or a playful invention. Sometimes associated with comedian Babalu, but connection is unclear.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang taong maliit ang taas o pandak.
Referring to a person of short stature; short.

examples.example: Mahal niya si Entong kahit na jabar ito.
She loves Entong even though he is jabar (short).

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Distinct meaning from the 'short' sense.

definitions.meaning: Pawis ng kili-kili na bumabakat o nagmamarka sa damit.
Sweat in the armpits that becomes visible as a stain or mark on clothing.

examples.example: Kanina pa siya tumakbo. May jabar na tuloy.
He's been running for a while. Now he has jabar (armpit sweat stains).

etymology: Gay slang, likely onomatopoeic or playful term related to ejaculation.

definitions.meaning: (Png.) Ang likido (semen) na lumalabas mula sa ari ng lalaki habang orgasm; (Pd.) Ang akto ng paglabas nito (mag-jaboom, nag-jaboom).
(N.) Ejaculate, semen; (V.) To ejaculate, to come.

examples.example: Ang daming jaboom ang lumabas kay Ian.
There was so much jaboom (cum) from Ian.
Nagjaboom na naman si Miguel sa banyo.
Miguel jaboom-ed (came) in the toilet again.

etymology: From the name of Filipina actress Jackielou Blanco. Used figuratively.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa kalagayan ng pagiging wala sa sarili, lutang, natulala, o pansamantalang nalilito o hindi makapag-isip nang maayos.
Describing a state of being mentally lost, spaced out, dazed, blank, or temporarily confused or unable to think clearly.

examples.example: Biglang na-jackielou blanco si Marites nang makita niya ang bill ng koryente.
Marites suddenly felt jackielou blanco (spaced out/dazed) after looking at the electric bill.

definitions.meaning: Isang napakagwapong lalaki; isang magandang 'nakuha' o 'panalo'.
A very handsome or attractive man; considered a 'good catch' or a 'win'.

examples.example: Jackpot ang nabingwit ni Gitri na afam.
Gitri got a jackpot (handsome man/good catch) with that expat.

etymology: Gay slang, possibly derived from Michael Jackson's perceived persona or dance moves, implying flirtatiousness or attention-seeking.

definitions.meaning: Kalandian, kaharutan, o pagiging mapaglaro sa pakikipag-ugnayan, lalo na sa romantiko o sekswal na konteksto.
Flirtatiousness, coquettishness, naughtiness, or playfulness in interaction, especially in a romantic or sexual context.

examples.example: Hindi nahihiya si Felix na ipakita ang jackson niya sa mga lalaki sa opisina.
Felix is not shy of showing his jackson (flirtatiousness) to the male employees of the office.

etymology: From the name of the music group 'The Jackson 5', known for their afros in their early years.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa kulot na buhok, lalo na ang istilong afro.
Referring to curly hair, especially an afro hairstyle.

examples.example: Maswerte pa rin si Pido dahil bagay sa kaniya ang jackson five.
Pido is lucky that jackson five (curly hair/afro) suits him well.

etymology: Bekimon/gay slang alteration of English 'fake', possibly influenced by other 'ja-'/'j-' prefixed slang terms.

definitions.meaning: Peke, huwad, o hindi totoo.
Fake, counterfeit, false, or phony.
Tumutukoy sa isang babae na maganda o kaakit-akit.
Referring to a woman who is beautiful or attractive.

examples.example: Ay pak! Jagan na naman ang kandidata natin sa MU (Miss Universe).
Wow! Our Miss Universe candidate is jagan (beautiful) again.

definitions.meaning: Salitang balbal para sa guwardiya o security guard, mula sa binaligtad na baybay ng 'guwardiya'.
Slang term for a security guard, derived from the inverted spelling of 'guwardiya'.

examples.example: KJ (Killjoy) nung jaguar na nagpapatahimik sa sinehan.
The jaguar (guard) who calls out people who make noises in the cinema is so KJ (killjoy).

etymology: From Hokkien Chinese 'hia-si' (shy), common Philippine slang.

definitions.meaning: Nahihiya, mahiyain, o naiilang.
Shy, embarrassed, timid, or bashful.

examples.example: Jahe talaga ang kapatid na lalaki ni Eric. Takot makipag-usap sa ibang tao.
Eric's brother is jahe (shy), so afraid to talk to other people.

definitions.meaning: Magsalsal; palibugin ang sarili sa pamamagitan ng kamay (karaniwang tumutukoy sa lalaki).
To masturbate (typically referring to males).

examples.example: Nahuli ang guwardiya na nagjajakol sa sinehan.
The guard was caught doing jakol (masturbating) in the movie theater.

etymology: From the name of Filipino basketball player James Yap, known for relationship dynamics (e.g., marrying older). Used figuratively.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang lalaking partner na mas bata kaysa sa kaniyang karelasyon (babae man o bakla).
Referring to a male partner who is significantly younger than his significant other (whether female or gay man).

examples.example: Ang pogi ng james yap ni Marta.
Marta's james yap (younger boyfriend) is handsome.

etymology: From the name of Filipino singer/actor Janno Gibbs. Figurative use, possibly a pun ('Gibbs' -> 'give').

definitions.meaning: Magbigay o mag-abot, lalo na ng pera.
To give or hand over, especially money.

examples.example: Tuwing araw ng suweldo ay nag-janno gibbs ng pera si Peter sa kaniyang nanay.
Peter janno gibbs-es (gives) money to his mother every payday.

etymology: Derived from 'Japan' + '-era' suffix. Refers to Filipinos (often entertainers, gay men, or transgender women) who worked or lived in Japan.
synonyms: trans woman who worked/transitioned in Japan

definitions.meaning: Isang Pilipino/Pilipina (madalas ay bakla, transgender na babae, o babaeng entertainer) na nagtrabaho o tumira sa Japan, o isang transgender na babae na doon sumailalim sa sex reassignment.

A Filipino/Filipina (often a gay man, transgender woman, or female entertainer) who worked or lived in Japan, or a transgender woman who underwent sex reassignment surgery there. Can overlap with 'Japayuki'.

examples.example: Limang taon nang japanera si Luis bago nakabalik ng Pilipinas.
Luis was a japanera (worked/lived in Japan, implies being gay/trans) for five years before he returned to the Philippines.

etymology: From Japanese 'Japayuki-san', a term originally referring to Southeast Asian women (often Filipinas) migrating to Japan for work, frequently in the entertainment or sex industry. Often carries derogatory connotations.

definitions.meaning: Isang Filipina (o taga-Timog-Silangang Asya) na nagtatrabaho sa Japan, karaniwan bilang entertainer o sa sex industry. Ang termino ay maaaring ituring na mapanlait.
A Filipina (or other Southeast Asian woman) working in Japan, often as an entertainer or in the sex industry. The term can be derogatory.

examples.example: Hindi naman porket naging Japayuki ay masama nang babae.
Being a japayuki doesn't mean a girl is sinful.

etymology: Slang, likely derived from 'Hapon' (Japanese person/language) with playful alteration.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Taong Hapon.
(Slang) A Japanese person.

examples.example: Akala ko nakajackpot na ako sa japok na nakilala ko, magsasaka pala.
I really thought I hit a jackpot with my japok (Japanese) husband who turned out to be a farmer. Now I help in his farm.

etymology: Combination of a slang prefix 'ja-'/'j-' and 'porma' (style, form, being fashionable).

definitions.meaning: Maporma, istaylis, o mahilig sumunod sa uso sa pananamit.
Stylish, fashionable, trendy, or having a good sense of style, especially in clothing.

examples.example: Japorms ka pa kahit wala ka namang pera.
You may be japorms (stylish) but you don't have money.

etymology: Gay slang, possibly related to 'ebak' (standard Tagalog for feces).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Dumi o tae ng tao o hayop.
(Slang) Feces, excrement (human or animal).

examples.example: May jebak ang shorts mo.
There's jebak (poop) on your shorts.

etymology: From 'jejeje' (representing laughter like Spanish 'jajaja') + '-mon' (from PokÃ©mon 'pocket monsters'). Refers to a specific internet/texting subculture characterized by unconventional spelling/capitalization (e.g., 'jEjEje', 'aQcKuH puh').

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na nauugnay sa isang subculture na kilala sa kakaibang paggamit ng malalaki at maliliit na titik, numero, at simbolo sa pagte-text o online (hal., 'aQcKuH puh c JeJe'). Madalas itong tinitingnan nang negatibo.

A person associated with a specific subculture known for unconventional capitalization, spelling, and use of symbols in text messages and online communication (e.g., 'aQcKuH puh c JeJe', '3ow ph0w, mUsZtAh nA?'). Often viewed negatively.

examples.example: Hirap basahin ng text niya, Jejemon kasi.
It's hard to read his texts, he's a Jejemon.

etymology: From English 'jealous', adapted into Bekimon/gay slang.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal na Pnr./Pd.) Nagseselos; naninibugho.
(Slang adj./v.) Jealous; feeling or showing envy.

examples.example: Huwag ka nang mag-jelling. Tikboy loves only you.
Don't get jelling (jealous). Tikboy loves only you.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain, playful term for 'cellphone'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Cellphone.
(Slang) Cell phone.

examples.example: Parang kamukha ng binibenta yung jelpack kong ninakaw nung isang linggo.
The one they sell looks exactly like my jelpack (cellphone) that was stolen last week.

etymology: Slang, likely related to 'hippie', possibly influenced by 1970s culture. Origin details unclear.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Isang babaeng hippie.
(Slang) A hippie girl or woman.

examples.example: Mukhang jepay yung babae sa park.
The girl in the park looks like a jepay (hippie).

etymology: Slang, likely the male counterpart to 'jepay', related to 'hippie', possibly influenced by 1970s culture.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Isang lalaking hippie.
(Slang) A hippie guy or man.

examples.example: Bagay lang sila. Jepoy yung ex mo, di ba? Palaging mukhang bagong gising.
They are a match. Your ex is a jepoy (hippie guy), right? He always looks like he just woke up.

etymology: Slang term popularized in the 1970s Philippines, notably by Mike Hanopol's song "Laki sa Layaw Jeproks". Associated with the hippie counterculture, implying a carefree, non-conformist, sometimes rebellious or rugged style. The origin 'from project' is likely folk etymology.

definitions.meaning: (Pnr.) May istilong hippie, malaya, palaboy, o hindi alintana ang pormal na kaayusan; (Png.) Taong may ganitong istilo o pamumuhay.
(Adj.) Having a hippie, bohemian, rugged, or unkempt style; non-conformist; (N.) A person with such a style or lifestyle.

examples.example: Hindi ko gusto ang pormang jeproks ni Kiel.
I don't like Kiel's jeproks (hippie/rugged) style.

etymology: From the name of Filipina journalist Jessica Soho. Used figuratively in gay slang, possibly as a pun ('Soho' ~ 'baho' - bad smell).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Mabaho o hindi kaaya-aya ang amoy (lalo na sa hininga).
(Slang) Having a bad or unpleasant smell; stinky (especially referring to bad breath).

examples.example: Nica, magsipilyo ka naman. Ang jessica soho ng bibig mo!
Nica, brush your teeth. Your mouth is jessica soho (stinky)!

etymology: From English 'jive' or 'jibe' (meaning to agree, fit, or be in accord).

definitions.meaning: Magkasundo, magtugma, o umakma (ang mga ideya, personalidad, plano, atbp.).
To agree, fit, match, or be in accord (of ideas, personalities, plans, etc.); to click or mesh well.

examples.example: Hindi kami nag-jibe ng mga ka-team ko sa project.
My personality didn't jibe with my teammates on the project.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Isang lalaking bayaran o nagbibigay ng sekswal na serbisyo kapalit ng pera o suporta; gigolo.
(Slang) A male escort or prostitute; gigolo.

examples.example: Inamin ni Ruel kay Roger na dati siyang jigs.
Ruel admitted to Roger that he used to be a jigs (gigolo).

definitions.meaning: Nabigo, iniwan, o tinanggihan sa isang romantikong relasyon.
Rejected or abandoned by a lover; heartbroken.

examples.example: Naglasing si Ben kagabi dahil jilted na naman siya.
Ben got drunk last night because he was jilted again.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Ang bilang na lima.
(Slang) The number five.

examples.example: 'Di ko kaya jima guys sabay-sabay!
I can't handle jima (five) guys simultaneously!

etymology: Bekimon/gay slang alteration of 'simbahan' (church) or 'simba' (to attend mass), adding a playful suffix '-ers'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Lugar kung saan nagdaraos ng misa; simbahan.
(Slang) A place where Mass is celebrated; church.

etymology: Slang term, possibly a playful reference to 'jingle bells' or another obscure association. Used in the context of pickpocketing tools or techniques. 'Pringles' appears as an alternative term.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Isang kasangkapan, kagamitan, o paraan na ginagamit sa pandurukot.
(Slang) A tool, device, or method used for pickpocketing.

examples.example: Nakalimutan ni Cesar na dalhin ang kaniyang jingerbells bago pumunta sa palengke.
Cesar forgot to bring his jingerbells (pickpocketing tool) before going to the market.

etymology: From English 'jingle' or 'tinkle', used euphemistically for urination.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Euphemism) Umihi.
(Slang/Euphemism) To urinate.

examples.example: Pare, jingle lang ako, walang silipan.
Bro, let me jingle (pee) in peace, no peeking.

etymology: Combination of 'jinit' (Bekimon/slang alteration of 'init' - hot) and English 'ever'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Napakainit o sobrang alinsangan.
(Slang) Extremely hot or sweltering.

examples.example: Ang jinit ever dito, nagpapawis ang singit ko!
It's so jinit ever (very hot) here, my crotch is getting sweaty!

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Jeepney.
(Slang) Jeepney.

examples.example: Kaloka! May nag-DIY (do-it-yourself/masturbate) doon sa jipamy, ang aga-aga!
It was shocking! Someone was doing DIY (masturbating) on the jipamy (jeepney) so early in the morning!

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Naiinis, nayayamot, o naiirita.
(Slang) Irritated, annoyed, or exasperated.

examples.example: Najijiririt na ako sa kakahintay kay Oscar.
I'm getting jiririt (irritated) waiting for Oscar.

etymology: Combination of 'jiririt' (slang for irritated) and English suffix '-ation'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pagkainis, pagkayamot, o iritasyon.
(Slang) Annoyance, irritation, or exasperation.

examples.example: Jiritation sa mga balita ngayon puro kabobohan!
Nothing but jiritation (annoyance/irritation) while reading all this foolish news!

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Ang bilang na isa.
(Slang) The number one.

examples.example: Jisa lang naman ang gusto ko, ikaw.
There is only jisa (one) that I want, you.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Itlog (ng manok, pugo, atbp.).
(Slang) Egg (chicken, quail, etc.).

examples.example: Ano ba itong nabili mong mga jitlog, puro bugok!
My goodness. All the jitlog (eggs) you bought are rotten!

etymology: Acronym/initialism from English 'jack off' or 'jerk off'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Vulgar) Magsalsal o magbate (karaniwan tumutukoy sa lalaki).
(Slang/Vulgar) To masturbate (typically referring to males); jack off, jerk off.

examples.example: Mahilig mag-JO si kuya sa banyo.
My brother likes to JO (jack off) in the bathroom.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Used figuratively to describe someone (usually female) who is flat-chested. Possibly related to a known person or character.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Mapangutya) Babae o dalagang patag o maliit ang dibdib.
(Slang/Derogatory) A flat-chested woman or girl.

examples.example: Naku, wala kang suwerte diyan, joana 'yan!
Well, you're not lucky with her, she's a joana (flat-chested)!

etymology: From the name of Filipina actress 'Joey Paras' (feminized to Joana?). Playful term for spouse.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Asawa (lalaki o babae).
(Slang) Spouse (husband or wife).

examples.example: Ano ang gagawin mo kapag nahuli mong nagsasarili (nag-JO) ang joana paras mo?
What will you do if you catch your joana paras (spouse) masturbating?

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Mataba; (Balbal Png.) Taong mataba.
(Slang adj.) Fat, overweight; (Slang n.) A fat person.

examples.example: Hindi na raw niya mahindot, majoba na raw siya, madali nang mapagod.
He no longer has the stamina to have sex with me because he got joba (fat), he gets tired easily.

etymology: Elaborate gay slang term, likely based on names or playful combinations ('Jobert', 'Tina', 'Sucaldito'/'Sukal Dito' - trash here?, 'Doon' - there). Refers to someone sexually active or promiscuous.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Isang taong (karaniwan ay bakla) na napakalibog, napaka-aktibo sa sex, o promiscuous.
(Slang) A person (typically a gay man) who is very libidinous, sexually active, or promiscuous.

examples.example: Lumipat man si Wilson ng tirahan, mananatili pa rin siyang jobertina sucaldoon-sucaldito.
Wilson can move to another place, however, he will always be a jobertina sucaldoon-sucaldito (highly sexed/promiscuous). It's in his blood.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Vulgar) Magjakol o magsalsal.
(Slang/Vulgar) To masturbate.

examples.example: Walang masama magjockals. Ang masama ay magjockals sa pampasaherong bus o jeep!
There's nothing wrong with doing jockals (masturbating). What's wrong is doing jockals on a passenger bus or jeep!

etymology: From the name of Filipina actress Jodi Sta. Maria. Used figuratively in gay slang.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Hindi nagsasabi ng katotohanan; sinungaling.
(Slang) Untruthful; a liar.

examples.example: Walang naniniwala kay Karen. Jodi Sta. Maria kasi siya!
Nobody believes Karen. She is such a Jodi Sta. Maria (liar)!

etymology: Gay slang, likely alteration of 'dyoga' (Filipino slang for breasts).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Suso ng babae; dibdib.
(Slang) Breasts, boobs.

examples.example: Magkano pa-enhance mo ng joga?
How much did you spend for your joga (boob) enhancement?

etymology: Slang, from the English name 'Johnny'. Used figuratively for janitor or cleaner.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Tagalinis o dyanitor.
(Slang) Janitor or cleaner.

examples.example: Binigyan ng regalo ni Max ang bagong johnny ng kompanya.
Max gave the new johnny (janitor) a gift.

etymology: Taglish phrase combining English 'join' and 'club' with Filipino preposition 'sa' (in/to the).

definitions.meaning: (Mabalbal na idyoma) Isang paanyaya o paghimok na umamin na bilang bakla at sumama sa grupo.
(Slang idiom) An invitation or encouragement to come out as gay and become part of the group/community.

examples.example: Edge, magpakatotoo ka na. Join sa club na!
Edge, it's time to be true to yourself. Join sa club (Join the club/Come out) already!

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Biro.
(Slang) Joke.

examples.example: Kapag kaming mga accla ang inaalaska ninyo, sumasakay kami sa jok, pero kapag kami ang nag-jok, may pananakit?
Us gays can take your jok (jokes), but when we make jok (jokes), you resort to harassment?!

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly an alteration of 'lakad' (plan, errand, walk) or a playful invention.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Plano, balak na gawin, o pupuntahan.
(Slang) Plan, intention, activity, or a place to go.

examples.example: May jokad ka ba mamaya? Tara, rampa!
Do you have any jokad (plans/place to go) later? Let's hang out!

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Png.) Lalaking homoseksuwal; bakla. (Balbal Pnr.) Tumutukoy sa pagiging bakla.
(Slang Noun) Homosexual male; gay man. (Slang Adj.) Gay.

examples.example: Oo, jokla ako, pero hindi lang iyon ang pagkatao ko!
Yes, I am jokla (gay), but I am so much more than that!

etymology: From the name of the popular Filipino fast-food chain 'Jollibee'. Used figuratively and humorously in gay slang.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Mapagbiro) Madumi o malibag na dibdib o suso.
(Slang/Humorous) Dirty or grimy breasts.

examples.example: Maghilod ka nga, ang jollibee mo na!
Scrub yourself, your boobs are so jollibee (dirty/grimy)!

etymology: Gay slang, likely derived from 'jologs' (tasteless, low-class) with a diminutive or playful suffix '-inding'. Refers specifically to a gay person perceived negatively.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Mapangutya) Baklang itinuturing na baduy, mahirap, walang pinag-aralan, o walang modo.
(Slang/Derogatory) A gay person considered tasteless, poor, uncultured, or mannerless.

examples.example: Sa Sabado ay tuturuan ko ang mga jologinding na ito kung paano magbihis nang maayos.
On Saturday, I will teach these jologindings (tasteless/uncultured gays) how to dress well.
