etymology: Filipino slang popularized in the late 1990s or early 2000s, often associated with perceived lack of taste, lower socioeconomic status, or being 'uncool'. Origin debated, possibly from 'diyologs' (related to 'diyos ko Lord'? unlikely), or related to specific trends/groups at the time.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Baduy; walang class; hindi marunong pumorma o manamit; hindi sunod sa uso. (Balbal Png.) Taong baduy o jologs.
(Slang Adj.) Tasteless, unfashionable, uncool, low-class, tacky. (Slang Noun) A person perceived as jologs.

examples.example: Jologs naman ng porma mo, para kang napag-iwanan ng panahon!
Your style is so jologs (tasteless/outdated)! It's so old-fashioned.

etymology: Gay slang, likely a blend of 'jeep'/'jipney' and 'pamasahe' (fare).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pamasahe sa dyip.
(Slang) Jeepney fare.

examples.example: Mauuna pa yatang magbente ang jomasahe kaysa bumaba ang presyo ng bigas!
The jomasahe (jeepney fare) seems likely to hit twenty [pesos] before the price of rice goes down!

etymology: Gay slang, possibly an alteration of 'bugbog' (to beat up, maul) or 'tumbok' (hit directly), or a playful onomatopoeic invention.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Suntukin; birahin; bugbugin.
(Slang) To punch, hit, or strike someone.

examples.example: Najombag si pare, nabuking kasi ng misis na may kulasisi.
My buddy got jombagged (punched/hit) after his wife found out about his mistress.

etymology: Gay slang, nominal form related to the verb 'jombag' (to punch/hit).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Suntok, bira, o pananakit; pambubugbog.
(Slang) A punch, hit, strike, or act of violence/hitting.

examples.example: Isang malakas na jombag ang tumama sa panga niya.
A strong jombag (punch) landed on his jaw.

etymology: Gay slang, likely an alteration of 'ambon' (drizzle).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Ambon; mahinang ulan.
(Slang) Drizzle; light rain.

examples.example: Sarap magkape habang may jombon sa labas.
It's nice to drink coffee while looking outside the window when there is jombon (drizzle).

etymology: Gay slang, likely an alteration of 'sampalin' (to slap).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Sampalin o tampalin.
(Slang) To slap someone.

examples.example: Jojompalin ko si Erning pagdating niya sa bahay. Gabing-gabi na 'di pa umuuwi!
I will jompalin (slap) Erning when he arrives home. It's very late already, and he's still not home!

etymology: Gay slang, likely an alteration of 'matanda' (old).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Matanda. (Balbal Png.) Matandang tao.
(Slang Adj.) Old. (Slang Noun) An old person.

examples.example: Mukha ka nang jonda sa stress.
You already look jonda (old) from stress.

etymology: Gay slang, likely an alteration of 'panget' (ugly).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pangit; hindi maganda o kaakit-akit ang itsura (karaniwan sa mukha).
(Slang) Ugly; unattractive (usually referring to facial features).

examples.example: Hindi bale nang jonda kesa jonget tulad ng asawa mo!
It's better to have an old partner than a jonget (ugly) one like yours!

etymology: Gay slang, likely an alteration of 'hantay' or 'hintay' (wait).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Maghintay o mag-antay.
(Slang) To wait.

examples.example: May sabunutan daw ng mga hitad. Jonta sila diyan, papunta na ako!
They say there's a catfight nearby among the bitches. Tell them to jonta (wait), I'm coming!

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Buntis.
(Slang) Pregnant.

examples.example: Totoo ba na jontis na naman si Maricel?
Is it true that Maricel is jontis (pregnant) again?

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Refers specifically to fake or augmented breasts.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pekeng suso o dibdib; suso na may implant o retoke.
(Slang) Fake breasts; breast implants.

examples.example: Ang damot-damot niyan ni Tess! Ang sarap tusukin ng jopek niya!
Tess is very selfish. It would be very satisfying to prick her jopek (fake boobs)!

etymology: Gay slang, likely from the name 'Michael Jordan', used figuratively to mean handsome.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Gwapo; magandang lalaki. (Balbal Png.) Lalaking gwapo.
(Slang Adj.) Handsome; good-looking. (Slang Noun) A handsome guy.

examples.example: Ang jordan at bango ng pinsan ni Mike!
Mike's cousin smells good and is jordan (handsome)!

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Kuripot; sobrang matipid o madamot.
(Slang) Stingy; miserly.

examples.example: Joripot daw iyan kaya nakaipon.
They say he was joripot (stingy), that's why he was able to save money.

etymology: Filipino colloquialism/slang, contraction/alteration of 'Diyos ko' (My God).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Kolokyal) Pandamdam na nagpapahayag ng pagkagulat, pagkadismaya, pagkatakot, o iba pang matinding emosyon; pinaikling 'Diyos ko'.
(Slang/Colloquial) Interjection expressing surprise, dismay, fear, or other strong emotion; contraction of 'My God'.

examples.example: Josko, hindi ka pa naliligo, mag-iilang araw na! Tutong na ang punja mo!
Josko (My God), you haven't showered in days! Your clothes are filthy!

etymology: Gay slang alteration of 'pasok' (enter, come in).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pumasok o tumuloy (sa loob).
(Slang) To enter or come in.

examples.example: Josok ka. Mabait ang aso namin. Dalawa pa lang ang nakakagat niyan.
Come in, josok (enter). Don't mind our dog. He has bitten only two people so far.

etymology: Combination of 'hosto' (host, likely borrowed from Japanese nightlife context) and potentially 'Japayuki' or a gay slang alteration 'jo-'. Refers specifically to Filipino male entertainers/hosts working in Japan.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Lalaking Pilipinong entertainer o host na nagtatrabaho sa Japan.
(Slang) A Filipino male entertainer or host working in Japan; a male Japayuki.

examples.example: Maraming raket ang mga josto doon.
The josto (male Filipino hosts) have many side jobs there.

etymology: Gay slang, likely alteration of 'bata' (young child, young person).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Bata pa; nasa murang edad. (Balbal Png.) Taong bata pa.
(Slang Adj.) Very young; underage. (Slang Noun) A young person; a minor.

examples.example: Hindi mo naman sinabi na jota pa pala itong nirereto mo sa akin!
You didn't mention that the person you're setting me up with is still jota (very young/underage)!

etymology: Common Filipino slang, widely adopted beyond gay slang. Likely derived or evolved from 'asawa' (spouse), possibly influenced by gay slang sound changes. Refers to a boyfriend, girlfriend, or romantic partner.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Kolokyal) Kasintahan; nobyo o nobya; karelasyon.
(Slang/Colloquial) Boyfriend or girlfriend; romantic partner.

examples.example: May jowa ka na ba?
Do you have a jowa (boyfriend/girlfriend) already?

etymology: Gay slang, combination of 'jowa' (boyfriend/girlfriend, derived from 'asawa') and the playful suffix '-wiz'. Usually refers to a spouse or long-term partner.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Asawa; kabiyak; kinakasama (live-in partner).
(Slang) Spouse; partner (often implying a more serious or established relationship than 'jowa').

examples.example: Nakita ko ang jowawiz mo na may angkas na iba sa motor papuntang sabungan!
I saw your jowawiz (spouse/partner) with someone else riding pillion on the motorcycle heading to the cockpit arena!

etymology: Gay slang, likely a playful alteration or code word for 'bakla' (gay man), possibly based on a common name like 'Judy' feminized, or related to 'jologs'/'jokla'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Lalaking homoseksuwal; bakla.
(Slang) Gay man; homosexual.

examples.example: Maraming juding sa salon na iyon.
There are many juding (gay men) in that salon.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Payong.
(Slang) Umbrella.

examples.example: Saka pa umulan kung kailan wala akong dalang joyong, shuta!
Now it rains when I didn't bring my joyong (umbrella), damn it!

etymology: Gay slang, likely a blend of 'juvenile' or 'junjun' (common term for a young boy) with a feminizing or diminutive suffix '-ita'. Refers to a young gay person.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Batang bakla; kabataang homoseksuwal.
(Slang) A young gay person (often male).

examples.example: Napakasipag at bait ng jubelitang anak ni Arnold.
Arnold's jubelita (young gay son/child) is very industrious and kind.

etymology: Gay slang alteration of 'taba' (fat), possibly influenced by 'chubby' or 'obese'. Similar to 'joba'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Mataba; (Balbal Png.) Taong mataba.
(Slang Adj.) Fat, overweight; (Slang Noun) A fat person.

examples.example: Ang jubis-jubis ko na! Kailangan ko na talagang bumalik sa gym.
I'm so jubis (fat/chubby) already! I really need to go back to the gym.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Hindi.
(Slang) No, not.

examples.example: Judi tao, judi hayop, anes itech?
Judi (Not a) person, judi (not an) animal, what is this?

etymology: Gay slang, humorous alteration of English 'due date', referencing the name 'Judith'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Takdang araw o petsa ng pagbabayad (ng bill, utang, atbp.); hango sa 'due date'.
(Slang) Due date (for bills, payments, etc.); from the English phrase 'due date'.

examples.example: Ang bilis ng panahon! Judith na naman ng kuryente!
How time flies! It's the judith (due date) for the electric bill again!

etymology: Gay slang alteration of 'uwi' (go home, return home).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Umuwi (sa bahay).
(Slang) To go home.

examples.example: Berto, tara na, juela na tayo!
Berto, let's go, let's juela (go home) already!

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'jogjog' (shake, referring to movement?) or a playful term. Refers to a gay person who has undergone cosmetic surgery or enhancements ('retokada').

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Baklang nagparetoke o may pinagawang bahagi ng katawan (hal. ilong, dibdib).
(Slang) A gay person who has had cosmetic surgery or enhancements.

examples.example: In fairness kay Mario, gumanda siya pagka-jugjog niya. Mukhang natural!
In fairness to Mario, he looks better after his jugjog (enhancements/surgery). It looks natural!

etymology: Popularized Filipino expression, often used humorously or euphemistically. Playful phonetic similarity to 'Diyos ko, Lord' (My God, Lord) or simply 'Diyos ko Lord'.

definitions.meaning: (Mabalbal na Idoyma/Ekspresyon) Pandamdam na katulad ng 'Diyos ko Lord', nagpapahayag ng matinding pagkagulat, pagkamangha, pagkadismaya, atbp.
(Slang Idiom/Expression) Interjection similar to 'Oh my God', expressing strong surprise, amazement, dismay, etc. A humorous phonetic play.

examples.example: Juice colored, magiging tatay na ako!
Juice colored (Oh my God), I'm going to be a father soon!

etymology: Slang, from English 'juice' (referring to alcoholic drinks) + '-er' suffix. Means someone who drinks excessively.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Taong malakas uminom ng alak; lasenggo.
(Slang) Drunkard; someone who drinks alcohol excessively.

examples.example: Hindi kami nagtagal ni Moi dahil juicer siya.
My relationship with Moi didn't last long because he is a juicer (drunkard).

etymology: Gay slang, likely a playful or emphatic alteration of 'papatayin' (will kill).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Hyperbole) Papatayin (madalas ginagamit nang pasobra o pabiro).
(Slang/Hyperbole) To kill (often used hyperbolically or humorously).

examples.example: Ay! Jujutayin mo sa takot si accla! Wag kang manggulat!
Ay! You'll jujutayin (kill) sis with fear! Don't startle people!

etymology: Gay slang, vulgar term. Likely an alteration of the English vulgarism 'puke', used sometimes in Filipino slang for vagina, or a direct alteration of 'puki' (vagina).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Bulgar) Puki; ari ng babae.
(Slang/Vulgar) Vagina.

examples.example: Nalaman kong juding ako noong nasusuka ako kapag nakakakita ng juke.
I realized I was gay when I felt nauseated at the sight of a juke (vagina).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Buksan.
(Slang) To open.

examples.example: Juksan mo kasi ang mga mata mo! Pineperahan ka lang ng jowa mong 'yan!
Juksan (Open) your eyes! Your partner is just using you for money!

etymology: Gay slang, humorous alteration of 'ulan' (rain), referencing the names of Canadian singer 'Alanis Morissette' and possibly Filipino singer 'Jolina Magdangal' ('Julanis'?).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Ulan.
(Slang) Rain.

examples.example: Nagju-julanis morisette na tuwing hapon. Tapos na talaga ang summer.
We've been having julanis morisette (rain) every afternoon. Summer is indeed over.

etymology: Gay slang, elaborated alteration of 'halata' (obvious, noticeable), possibly with suffixes '-ers' or '-ers'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Halata; kitang-kita; lantad.
(Slang) Obvious; noticeable.

examples.example: Julataers naman na bading 'yang si Arnie. Sana magpakatotoo na siya.
It's julataers (obvious) that Arnie is gay. I hope he comes out already.

etymology: Filipino slang, alteration of 'pulis' (police). Often used playfully or sometimes with negative connotation.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pulis; alagad ng batas.
(Slang) Police officer; cop.

examples.example: May nahuling magnanakaw ang mga julis kanina.
The julis (cops) caught a thief earlier.

etymology: Gay slang, elaborated form of 'jombag' (to punch, hit) with a possibly Italian-sounding or feminizing suffix '-ella'. Implies violent hitting.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Saktan o bugbugin nang matindi; gulpihin.
(Slang) To hit violently; to beat up severely; to assault.

examples.example: Mahirap magmahal ng lalaking mahilig mang-jumbagella kapag lasing.
It's hard to love a man who likes to jumbagella (violently beat) you when he is drunk.

etymology: Filipino slang, alteration of 'anak' (child, son/daughter), often with the suffix '-is' ('junakis'). Common colloquial term.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Kolokyal) Anak.
(Slang/Colloquial) Child (son or daughter).

examples.example: Pang-ilang junak mo na 'yan, beh? Parang kada Pasko, jontis ka.
How many junak (kids) do you have already, dear? It seems like you're pregnant every Christmas.

etymology: Filipino slang, from the name 'Jun Lozada' (a known figure in a Philippine political scandal, often perceived negatively by some). Used figuratively to mean 'loser' or someone who failed.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Talo; bigo. (Balbal Png.) Taong natalo o nabigo.
(Slang Adj.) Lost; failed. (Slang Noun) A loser; someone who failed.

examples.example: Jun Luzada na umalis ng sabungan si Mack matapos matalo lahat ng manok niya.
Mack left the cockpit a Jun Luzada (loser) after all his chickens lost.

etymology: Gay slang, likely a humorous alteration of 'an-an' (tinea versicolor, a common fungal skin infection causing white spots), possibly referencing a name like 'Jun'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) An-an; puting marka o patse-patse sa balat na dulot ng fungal infection (tinea versicolor).
(Slang) An-an; Tinea versicolor; white spots or patches on the skin caused by a fungal infection.

examples.example: Girl, gamutin mo naman 'yang junanis mo sa mukha. Ang pangit tingnan!
Girl, you should treat the junanis (an-an/tinea versicolor) on your face. It looks ugly!

etymology: 1. Common Filipino nickname for a young boy. Used in gay slang to refer to a young gay person. 2. Colloquial/childish term for penis.

definitions.meaning: 1: (Balbal) Batang bakla.
1: (Slang) Young gay person (male).
2: (Kolokyal/Pambata/Balbal) Titi; ari ng lalaki.
2: (Colloquial/Childish/Slang) Penis.

examples.example: (Sense 1) Junjun pa lang ako, alam ko nang beki ako.
(Sense 1) Ever since I was a junjun (young boy/young gay), I knew I was gay.
(Sense 2) Hinubaran siya at nakita ang junjun niya.
(Sense 2) He was stripped and his junjun (penis) was exposed.

etymology: From English slang 'junk', referring to heroin.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal mula sa Ingles) Heroin (ipinagbabawal na gamot).
(Slang from English) Heroin (illicit drug).

examples.example: Guard, may nakitang junk dito sa basurahan!
Security, some junk (heroin) was found here in the trash!

etymology: Gay slang, alteration of 'buntis' (pregnant). Variant of 'jontis'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Buntis.
(Slang) Pregnant.

examples.example: Girl, juntis ka na naman? Mag-family planning ka nga!
Girl, are you juntis (pregnant) again? Try family planning!

etymology: Gay slang, likely a playful, intensified alteration of 'pangit' (ugly). Similar to 'jonget'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pangit; masagwa ang itsura (lalo na ang mukha).
(Slang) Ugly; unattractive (especially facial features).

examples.example: Diday, iwasan mong sumimangot, para 'di ka magmukhang jupang-pang buong araw.
Diday, avoid frowning so you won't look jupang-pang (ugly) all day.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Supot; hindi tuli. (Balbal Png.) Lalaking hindi tuli.
(Slang Adj.) Uncircumcised. (Slang Noun) An uncircumcised male.

examples.example: Okay lang na jupÃ³t, basta malinis sa katawan.
It's okay if he is jupÃ³t (uncircumcised) as long as he maintains good hygiene.

etymology: Filipino colloquialism, reduplication of English 'just'. Implies something ordinary, common, low-quality, or unimportant.

definitions.meaning: (Kolokyal) Basta-basta; ordinaryo lang; mababang klase; walang espesyal.
(Colloquial) Ordinary; common; low-class; nothing special; mediocre; run-of-the-mill.

examples.example: Ano ang palagay mo sa akin? Just-just lang?
What do you take me for? Just-just (Someone ordinary/unimportant)?

etymology: Gay slang, likely related to 'juts' or 'tingting' (thin stick), referring to small size, specifically often used for a small penis.
sangkahulugan: maliit (lalo na sa ari ng lalaki)

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Maliit, lalo na kapag tumutukoy sa ari ng lalaki.
(Slang) Small, especially when describing a penis.

examples.example: Jutay man ang ari niya, bumawi naman sa dila.
His penis may be jutay (small), but whatever he lacks down there, he makes up for with his tongue.

etymology: Filipino slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'dyuts' or a playful alteration. Refers to marijuana.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Marijuana; damo.
(Slang) Marijuana.

examples.example: Bakit konti lang ang dala mong jutes? Bawal magdala rito nang konti lang dapat marami!
Why did you bring only a little jutes (marijuana) here? Don't you know it's forbidden to bring so little? You should bring a lot!

etymology: Gay slang, combination of 'tingting' (thin stick, implies smallness) and the surname 'Cojuangco' (prominent political family), possibly referencing Tingting Cojuangco. Used humorously to mean very small or tiny.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Napakaliit; munting-munti (madalas tumutukoy sa ari ng lalaki).
(Slang) Very small; tiny (often referring to penis size).

examples.example: Alam mo, sekreto lang natin ha... ang jutingting cojuangco ng junjun ni Odip!
You know, let's keep this between ourselves... Odip's junjun (penis) is jutingting cojuangco (tiny)!

etymology: 1. From English 'okay' or Filipino 'okey', shortened to 'k'. Common text/chat slang. 2. Shortening of 'karapatan' (right).

definitions.meaning: 1: (Balbal/Textspeak) Okey; oo; payag; tanggap.
1: (Slang/Textspeak) Okay; yes; agreed; accepted.
2: (Balbal) Karapatan.
2: (Slang) Right.

examples.example: (Sense 1) Pupunta ka ba? Reply: k.
(Sense 1) Are you going? Reply: k.
(Sense 2) Wala kang K sabihin 'yan!
(Sense 2) You have no K (right) to say that!

etymology: From English text/internet slang 'k thx bye', an abbreviation of 'Okay, thanks, bye'. Often used dismissively or sarcastically to end a conversation abruptly.
synonyms: okay thanks bye (often sarcastic or dismissive)

definitions.meaning: (Ekspresyon/Textspeak mula sa Ingles) Pinaikling 'Okay, thanks, bye'; madalas gamitin sa sarkastiko o mapangmaliit na paraan para tapusin ang usapan.
(Expression/Textspeak from English) Abbreviation for 'Okay, thanks, bye'; often used sarcastically or dismissively to abruptly end a conversation.

examples.example: Wala na akong masasabi pa sa iyo, Jonas. Ang tanging reaksyon ko sa ginawa mo ay: k tnx bye.
I don't have anything more to say to you, Jonas. My only reaction to what you did is: k tnx bye.

etymology: Elaborate gay slang phrase, likely playful and nonsensical combination of words/sounds. 'Kabilya' (steel bar?) 'Mane' (from 'many'? or a name?) 'Fuderanan' (playful alteration related to English vulgarism?). Implies treachery.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Sukab; hindi mapagkakatiwalaan; traydor. (Balbal Png.) Taong traydor o sukab.
(Slang Adj.) Untrustworthy, treacherous. (Slang Noun) A traitor, an untrustworthy person.

examples.example: Karding, mag-ingat ka diyan kay Lito. Siya ay kabilya mane fuderanan!
Karding, be wary of Lito. He is a kabilya mane fuderanan (untrustworthy/traitor)!

etymology: Gay slang, likely an alteration of 'kadiri' (disgusting).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Nakapandidiri; nakasusuka.
(Slang) Disgusting; gross.

examples.example: Kaders ng feslak (mukha) mo, dzai! Ang oily, ha!
Your face is kaders (disgusting/gross), sis! It's too oily!

etymology: Taglish expression combining Filipino 'kadiri' (disgusting) and English phrase 'to death' (meaning extremely or excessively).

definitions.meaning: (Ekspresyon/Taglish) Sobrang nakapandidiri; kasuklam-suklam.
(Expression/Taglish) Extremely disgusting; utterly revolting.

examples.example: Kadiri to death na ang ginagawa mong paghabol kay Boogie. Mag-move-on ka na!
Still chasing after Boogie is kadiri to death (extremely disgusting) already. It's time to move on!

etymology: From Cebuano/Visayan 'kadiyot' meaning 'a moment', 'briefly', or 'quickly'. Adopted into some forms of Tagalog/Filipino slang.

definitions.meaning: (Binisaya/Balbal) Sandali; saglit; mabilis lang.
(Visayan/Slang) For a moment; briefly; quickly; wait a moment.

examples.example: Kadyot lang, sis, aayusin ko lang ang buhok ko.
Kadyot (Wait a moment/Quickly), sis, I'm just fixing my hair.

etymology: Gay slang, likely derived from 'federation', implying membership in the 'gay federation' or community. Playful term for a confirmed gay person.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Kumpirmadong bakla; miyembro o kasapi (ng 'pederasyon' ng mga bakla).
(Slang) A confirmed gay person; a member (of the gay 'federation').

examples.example: Alam ko nang kafederasyon talaga si Alex mula pa noon.
I knew from the start that Alex is really a kafederasyon (confirmed gay).

etymology: Gay slang alteration of 'ka-face' (having the same face as) or 'kamukha' (look-alike).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Kamukha; kahawig. (Balbal Png.) Taong kamukha o kahawig.
(Slang Adj.) Look-alike. (Slang Noun) Someone who looks like another person.

examples.example: Alam mo, kafez mo sana si Coco Martin kung hindi lang pango ang ilong mo.
You know what, you would be Coco Martin's kafez (look-alike) if only your nose wasn't flat.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain, possibly onomatopoeic or a playful invention. Refers specifically to sexual intercourse between two gay men.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Png.) Pagtatalik ng dalawang lalaking homoseksuwal. (Balbal Pd.) Makipagtalik (sa kapwa lalaking homoseksuwal).
(Slang Noun) Sexual intercourse between two gay men. (Slang Verb) To have sex (with another gay man).

examples.example: Hindi ko makalilimutan ang pagka-kai-kai namin ni Joey dahil iyon ang una ko.
I will never forget the kai-kai (gay sex) Joey and I had because that was my first time.

etymology: Filipino slang, from Spanish 'causa' (cause, case), likely via prison slang where inmates involved in the same 'case' became associates ('kasama sa causa'). Extended to mean close friend or associate.

definitions.meaning: 1: (Balbal) Kasamahan sa kulungan o bilangguan.
1: (Slang) Prison mate; fellow inmate.
2: (Balbal/Kolokyal) Malapit na kaibigan; katropa; kasangga.
2: (Slang/Colloquial) A close friend; buddy; pal.

examples.example: (Sense 2) Kakosa ko iyang si Elmer mula pa high school, mapagkakatiwalaan 'yan.
(Sense 2) Elmer is my kakosa (close friend/buddy) since high school, he's trustworthy.

etymology: From Filipino 'kalabasa' (squash). Used figuratively in student slang to mean failing ('bagsak') or getting a zero score, often represented by a squash-like shape for zero. Extended to mean feeling stupid or clueless.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Estudyante Slang) Bumagsak o makakuha ng zero (sa pagsusulit); maramdamang parang bobo o walang alam.
(Slang/Student Slang) To fail or get a zero (on an exam); to feel stupid or clueless.

examples.example: Grabe, nangalabasÃ¢ ako sa physics exam kanina! Ang hirap!
Wow, I totally got a kalabasa (failed/felt stupid) in the physics exam earlier! It was so hard!

etymology: From Filipino 'kalabaw' (carabao/water buffalo). Used figuratively in gay slang, often humorously or sometimes derogatorily, to refer to an older gay person, perhaps implying being sturdy, large, or past their prime like an old carabao.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Mapagbiro) Matandang bakla.
(Slang/Humorous) An older gay person (usually male).

examples.example: Bilib talaga ako kay Gwen. Kalabaw na pero ang ganda pa rin ng kutis!
I really admire Gwen. Though already a kalabaw (older gay person), he still has beautiful skin!

etymology: Gay slang, playful and possibly nonsensical construction. Origin uncertain, perhaps related to 'tutay' (puppy?) or 'tutoy' (small boy?). Refers to an unpleasant or ugly-sounding name.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pangalan na pangit o hindi magandang pakinggan.
(Slang) An unpleasant or ugly-sounding name.

examples.example: Ayaw na ayaw niyang binabanggit ang kanyang kalamantutay na pangalan.
He really hates it when someone mentions his kalamantutay (ugly-sounding) name.

etymology: Filipino idiom literally meaning 'low-flying dove'. A common euphemism for a prostitute or sex worker.

definitions.meaning: (Idyoma/Eupemismo) Babaeng nagbebenta ng aliw; puta; babaeng bayaran.
(Idiom/Euphemism) A prostitute; a sex worker.

examples.example: Maraming kalapating mababa ang lipad sa lugar na iyon pagsapit ng gabi.
There are many kalapating mababa ang lipad (prostitutes) in that area when night falls.

etymology: Filipino word 'kalembang' typically means the ringing sound of a large bell. Used figuratively here to refer to bell-bottom trousers, referencing the bell-like shape.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Figuratibo) Pantalon na may malapad na ibabang bahagi; bell-bottoms.
(Slang/Figurative) Bell-bottom trousers.

examples.example: Naka-kalembang na naman si Riri, parang bumalik sa 70s!
Riri is wearing his kalembang (bell-bottoms) again, like he's back in the 70s!

etymology: Filipino word 'kalog' means 'to shake'. Used figuratively to describe someone who is 'shaken up' in a playful way - crazy, wacky, playful, funny, or sometimes ditzy.

definitions.meaning: 1: (Pd.) Alugin o kalugin (hal. ang isang bote).
1: (Verb) To shake or rattle (e.g., a bottle).
2: (Pnr./Kolokyal) Tumutukoy sa isang taong masayahin, makulit, pilyo, o tila may pagka-loko-loko o 'may sayad'.
2: (Adj./Colloquial) Refers to someone who is playful, wacky, zany, funny, mischievous, or endearingly crazy/ditzy.

examples.example: (Sense 2) Hindi ako nababato kapag kasama kita, Lena, dahil napaka-kalog mo!
(Sense 2) I never get bored when I'm with you, Lena, because you're so kalog (wacky/playful)!

etymology: Filipino word, stronger than 'batok' (hit on the nape). Refers to a knock or hit on the head, often with knuckles.
sangkahulugan: hampas sa ulo (gamit ang kamao o buko ng daliri)

definitions.meaning: (Png.) Hampas o pukpok sa ulo, karaniwan gamit ang buko ng daliri (knuckles). (Pd.) Hampasin o pukpukin sa ulo.
(Noun) A knock, rap, or hit on the head, often with the knuckles. (Verb) To hit or knock on the head.

examples.example: Akin na ang libro ko kundi isang malakas na kaltok ang aabutin mo!
Give me back my book or you'll get a strong kaltok (hit on the head)!

etymology: From Filipino 'kamatis' (tomato). Used figuratively to describe an inflamed, red, and swollen wound or boil, resembling a ripe tomato.

definitions.meaning: 1: Isang uri ng mapulang prutas na gulay.
1: A type of red fruit, used as a vegetable.
2: (Figuratibo) Sugat o pigsa na namumula, namamaga, at tila nagnanaknak, na kahawig ng hinog na kamatis.
2: (Figurative) A wound or boil that is red, swollen, and possibly festering, resembling a ripe tomato.

examples.example: (Sense 2) Huwag mong tirisin 'yang pigsa mo, baka lalong mag-kamatis 'yan!
(Sense 2) Don't squeeze your boil, it might become even more kamatis (inflamed and swollen)!

etymology: Gay slang, from the Japanese dish 'kamameshi' (rice cooked in an iron pot). Used humorously and figuratively to mean masturbation ('sariling sikap' - self-effort).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Magsalsal; magsariling sikap (masturbate).
(Slang) To masturbate.

examples.example: Mag-jowa ka na kasi, bes, para hindi ka lang puro kamameshi!
You should find a partner already, bestie, so you don't just kamameshi (masturbate) all the time!

etymology: Gay slang alteration of the Filipino pronoun 'kami' (we, us - exclusive).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Kami (panghalip panao, hindi kasama ang kausap).
(Slang) We/us (exclusive pronoun, not including the person being spoken to).

examples.example: Ilibre mo naman kamenchi, Bert, dahil na-promote ka!
Bert, you should treat kamenchi (us) because you got promoted!

etymology: From Filipino 'kamote' (sweet potato). Figuratively used in student/colloquial slang, similar to 'kalabasa', meaning to perform poorly, be clueless, or be stupid ('nangangamote').

definitions.meaning: 1: (Png.) Isang uri ng halamang-ugat na matamis ang laman.
1: (Noun) Sweet potato.
2: (Pnr./Balbal) Bobo; tanga; walang alam; nangangamote (lalo na sa pagsusulit o pag-intindi).
2: (Adj./Slang) Dumb; stupid; clueless (especially in exams or understanding something).

examples.example: (Sense 2) Ang malas mo talaga! Wala kang aasahan sa katambal mong kamote!
(Sense 2) You're very unlucky! You can't expect anything from your kamote (dumb/clueless) partner.

etymology: Shortened form of 'Amerikana' (American woman), derived from 'Kano' (American man). Often used colloquially.

definitions.meaning: (Kolokyal) Pinaikling tawag sa babaeng Amerikana.
(Colloquial) Shortened term for an American woman.

examples.example: Wow, ang ganda ng KanÃ¢ na napangasawa mo, pare!
Wow, the KanÃ¢ (American woman) you married is beautiful, buddy!

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'karot' (carrot?) or a playful alteration of 'makulit'/'malikot' (naughty/restless). Means boisterous, hyperactive, or annoyingly restless.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Makulit; malikot; magulo kumilos; hyperactive.
(Slang) Boisterous; hyperactive; unruly; overly restless.

examples.example: Kanino ba nagmana iyang anak mong kangkarot? Nakakahilo!
From whom did your child inherit that kangkarot (boisterous/hyperactive) attitude? It's making me dizzy!

etymology: From standard 'kanibal' (cannibal). Used figuratively in gay slang to refer to a gay person who is attracted to or has relationships with other gay people (eating one's 'own kind').
synonyms: gay person attracted to other gay people

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Figuratibo) Bakla na pumapatol o naaakit sa kapwa bakla.
(Slang/Figurative) A gay person who is attracted to or has relationships with other gay people.

examples.example: Choco, magkwento ka naman ng mga karanasan mo bilang isang kanibal.
Choco, please share some of your experiences as a kanibal (gay person into other gays).

etymology: Gay slang, likely a shortening or alteration of 'magkano' (how much). Used as an interjection to ask for the price.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Magkano? (Ginagamit sa pagtatanong ng presyo).
(Slang) How much? (Used to ask the price of something).

examples.example: Kanik 'yang apat na piraso ng hotdog, Brando?
Kanik (How much) are these four pieces of hotdog, Brando?

etymology: Gay slang, contraction of 'magkano, kuya?' (how much, brother/sir?). Similar to 'kanik'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pinaikling 'Magkano, kuya?'; ginagamit sa pagtatanong ng presyo sa lalaking tindero o drayber.
(Slang) Contraction of 'Magkano, kuya?' (How much, brother/sir?); used to ask the price, typically addressing a male vendor or driver.

examples.example: Kanikuya, bayad ho.
Kanikuya (How much, sir?), here's my payment.

etymology: From Filipino 'kanta' (song, to sing). Used figuratively in slang, especially police/criminal contexts, meaning 'to sing' like a canary - i.e., to confess, squeal, or tell the truth.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Figuratibo) Umamin; magtapat; magsabi ng katotohanan (lalo na tungkol sa kasalanan o krimen).
(Slang/Figurative) To confess; to tell the truth; to squeal (especially about a crime or wrongdoing).

examples.example: Kumanta ka na. Alam naming kasabwat mo ang taxi drayber, ano?
Kanta (Confess/Squeal) already! We know you conspired with the taxi driver, right?

etymology: Shortened form of 'Amerikano' (American man). Common Filipino colloquialism, sometimes used neutrally, sometimes pejoratively.

definitions.meaning: (Kolokyal) Pinaikling tawag sa lalaking Amerikano.
(Colloquial) Shortened term for an American man.

examples.example: Nakapag-asawa ng KanÃ³ si Marites at malapit na silang lumipad patungong States.
Marites married a KanÃ³ (American man) and they'll soon fly to the States.

etymology: Taglish/Filipino slang, from 'kapal ng mukha' (thick face) with '-muks' as a slang alteration of 'mukha' (face). Means shameless, thick-skinned, or brazen.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Makapal ang mukha; walang hiya. (Balbal Png.) Taong makapal ang mukha.
(Slang Adj.) Shameless; thick-skinned. (Slang Noun) A shameless or thick-skinned person.

examples.example: Kapalmuks talaga si Ferdie. Hindi pa rin nagbabayad ng utang niya!
Ferdie is such a kapalmuks (shameless/thick-skinned). He still hasn't paid his debt!

etymology: From Filipino 'kape' (coffee). Used figuratively in the expression 'magkape ka' (have coffee), meaning 'wake up and smell the coffee' - i.e., face reality, stop dreaming or being delusional.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Figuratibo) Harapin ang katotohanan; gumising sa realidad; huwag mangarap nang gising.
(Slang/Figurative) To face reality; to wake up and smell the coffee; to stop being delusional.

examples.example: Mag-kape ka nga! Hindi ka niya mahal!
Kape (Wake up/Face reality)! He doesn't love you!

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'kaplog' (hit/slap?) or a playful invention. Refers to sexual intercourse.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pagtatalik; pagsisiping.
(Slang) Sexual intercourse; sex.

examples.example: Umaga na natapos ang kaplugan nina Nora at Tirso sa motel.
Nora and Tirso's kaplugan (sex) at the motel finished in the morning.

etymology: Standard Filipino idiom 'kapos-palad' (short of palm) meaning unfortunate or poor. Reinterpreted humorously in slang to mean a man whose hands ('palad') are too small ('kapos') to fully cup his partner's large breasts.

definitions.meaning: 1: (Idyoma) Mahirap; dukha.
1: (Idiom) Poor; unfortunate.
2: (Balbal/Mapagbiro) Lalaking may kasintahan na malaki ang dibdib na hindi kayang sakupin ng kanyang mga palad.
2: (Slang/Humorous) A guy whose girlfriend has breasts too large for his hands ('palad') to fully cup ('kapos').

examples.example: (Sense 2) Ako na siguro ang pinakaswerteng kapus-palad sa buong mundo dahil sa laki ng hinaharap ng jowa ko!
(Sense 2) I might be the luckiest kapus-palad (guy with hands too small for his girl's boobs) in the whole world because of how big my girlfriend's chest is!

etymology: Filipino slang, likely related to Spanish 'rancho' (ranch, group) or possibly 'gancho' (hook, associate). Means close friend or buddy.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Malapit na kaibigan; kasama; katropa.
(Slang) Close friend; buddy.

examples.example: Karantso ko na si Jason simula pa noong elementary.
Jason has been my karantso (close friend/buddy) since we were kids in elementary school.

etymology: From English 'career'. Used figuratively in Filipino/gay slang to mean putting effort into pursuing something, especially a romantic interest; to actively flirt or court someone.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Lumandi; kumiri; manligaw; magpursige (lalo na sa pag-ibig); hango sa salitang Ingles na 'career'.
(Slang) To actively flirt with or court someone; to pursue romantically; from the English word 'career'.

examples.example: Gustong karirin ni Bella si Von kaya lagi siyang nagpapapansin.
Bella wants to karir (pursue/flirt with) Von, that's why she's always trying to get his attention.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Kotse; sasakyan.
(Slang) Car.

examples.example: Wow, bago ang kariret mo!
Wow, your kariret (car) is new!

etymology: Slang, shortened from 'karugtong' (extension). Refers to the 'extension' of hair connecting the navel area to the pubic hair (treasure trail).
sangkahulugan: buhok mula pusod pababa sa ari

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Buhok sa tiyan sa pagitan ng pusod at ng bulbol; pinaikling 'karugtong'.
(Slang) Hair between the navel and pubic area; treasure trail; shortened from 'karugtong' (extension).

examples.example: Ahitin mo na 'yang karog mo, Mars, kasi ang pangit tingnan kapag naka-two-piece ka.
You should shave your karog (treasure trail) already, Mars, because it doesn't look good when you wear a two-piece.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to Spanish 'carta' (letter, card - implying something shown) or 'cortada' (cut - referring to style?). Means outfit or getup.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Porma; bihis; kasuotan.
(Slang) Outfit; getup.

examples.example: Ang ganda ng kartada mo ngayon, pare! Mai-inlab na niyan si Tisay sa iyo.
Your kartada (outfit) is great today, bro! Tisay will fall for you for sure.

etymology: Filipino slang, derogatory or humorous alteration of 'Kastila' (Spaniard, Spanish person), often implying mestizo features or affectations.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Kolokyal) Kastila o Espanyol; taong may lahing Kastila o mukhang Kastila.
(Slang/Colloquial) A Spaniard or person of Spanish descent; someone who looks Spanish (mestizo).

examples.example: Sosyal naman pala ang jowa mo, mukhang Kastilaloy!
Your partner looks so classy, like a Kastilaloy (Spaniard/mestizo)!

etymology: Gay slang, from the name 'Katkat de Castro' (likely a real or fictional socialite). Used figuratively for a social climber, someone pretending to be rich.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Tumutukoy sa pagiging social climber o mapagpanggap na mayaman. (Balbal Png.) Taong mahirap na nagpapanggap na mayaman.
(Slang Adj.) Referring to being a social climber or pretending to be rich. (Slang Noun) A poor person pretending to be rich; a social climber.

examples.example: Sinabi sa akin ni Mary noon na mas mabuting mabuhay nang simple kaysa maging Kat Kat de Castro.
Mary told me once that it's better to live a simple life than to be a Kat Kat de Castro (social climber).

etymology: Shortened form of 'katamaran' (laziness). Common Filipino colloquialism.

definitions.meaning: (Kolokyal) Katamaran.
(Colloquial) Laziness.

examples.example: Nagkasakit na naman ng katam si Ella kaya hindi pumasok.
Ella caught the katam (laziness) bug again, that's why she didn't come to work.

etymology: Filipino idiom literally meaning 'juice/extract of Saudi'. Refers to the fruits of labor, savings, investments, or possessions acquired from money earned working in Saudi Arabia (or often, by extension, any overseas work, especially in the Middle East).

definitions.meaning: (Idyoma/Kolokyal) Mga naipundar, naipon, o nabili mula sa perang kinita sa pagtatrabaho sa Saudi Arabia (o sa ibang bansa).
(Idiom/Colloquial) Savings, investments, or possessions acquired from money earned working in Saudi Arabia (or overseas).

examples.example: Pare, ang bahay at lupa na ito ay katas ng Saudi.
Bro, this house and lot are katas ng Saudi (the result of my earnings from Saudi).

etymology: Filipino slang, likely an alteration or playful version of 'komisyon' (commission) or possibly related to 'tongpats' (kickback). Refers to a commission or kickback from a deal.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Komisyon o porsyento (madalas ilegal o lihim) mula sa isang transaksiyon o kasunduan; tongpats.
(Slang) Commission or percentage (often illicit or secret) from a transaction or deal; kickback.

examples.example: May katkong daw si Mayor sa pagpapagawa ng tulay kaya substandard.
They say the Mayor got a katkong (kickback/commission) from the bridge construction, that's why it's substandard.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'katok' (knock - implying stealth?) or a playful name construction. Means thief.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Magnanakaw.
(Slang) Thief.

examples.example: Huli na nang malaman ni Mary na katokling pala ang kanyang napangasawa dahil unti-unti nang nauubos ang mga alahas niya.
It was too late when Mary learned that she married a katokling (thief) because her jewelry was slowly disappearing.

etymology: Shortened from 'katulong' (helper, maid). Used derogatorily to mean looking like or acting like a maid/helper, implying low status or lack of refinement.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Mapangmaliit) Mukhang katulong o alila; kilos-katulong; mababang uri tingnan.
(Slang/Derogatory) Looking or acting like a maid or servant; appearing lowly or unrefined.

examples.example: Ayusin mo nga 'yang itsura mo, ang ganda mo ay pang-katol!
Fix your appearance, your beauty is katol (maid-like/unrefined)!

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'tsoka' (friend?) or a playful alteration of 'kasama' (companion) or 'kaibigan' (friend).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Kaibigan; kasama.
(Slang) Friend; companion.

examples.example: Katsokaran ko 'yang si Melai. Ako na ang bahala, ipapakilala kita.
Melai is my katsokaran (friend). I'll take care of it, I'll introduce you.

etymology: Acronym/portmanteau from 'kain' (eat), 'tsupa' (blowjob slang), and 'puwit' (buttocks, often implying anal sex). Refers to a combination of these sexual activities.
synonyms: rimming, fellatio, and anal sex combo?

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Akronim) Daglat ng 'kain' (pagkain sa ari o puwit), 'tsupa' (oral sex), at 'puwit' (anal sex).
(Slang/Acronym) Abbreviation of 'kain' (eat - implying oral sex on genitals or anus), 'tsupa' (blow job), and 'puwit' (buttocks - implying anal sex).

examples.example: Sana bukas ang isip ni Larry sa katsupit ngayong gabi.
I hope Larry is open to katsupit (eat-blowjob-butt sex acts) tonight.

etymology: Acronym from 'kain' (eat), 'tulog' (sleep), and 'gala' (wander, roam, go out). Describes a lifestyle of only eating, sleeping, and going out.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Akronim Png.) Ang paulit-ulit na gawain na pagkain, pagtulog, at paggala lamang. (Balbal Pd.) Mag-'kain, tulog, gala'.
(Slang/Acronym Noun) The routine of only eating, sleeping, and wandering/going out. (Slang Verb) To engage in only eating, sleeping, and wandering.

examples.example: Ang sarap ng buhay ng mga batang ito. Puro sila katuga!
These kids are so lucky. All they do is katuga (eat, sleep, wander)!

etymology: Gay slang, likely related to 'katulong' (helper) or 'katol' (maid-like), possibly referencing the 'katuray' flower/vegetable (associated with simple/rural life?). Means looking like a maid, specifically referring to a gay person.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Mapangmaliit) Baklang mukhang katulong o alila; mababang uri tingnan.
(Slang/Derogatory) A gay person who looks like a maid or servant; appearing lowly or unrefined.

examples.example: Hector, makinig ka sa payo ko para hindi ka magmukhang katuray!
Hector, listen to my advice so you won't look like a katuray (maid-like gay person)!

etymology: Acronym for 'Kasal, Binyag, Libing' (Wedding, Baptism, Funeral). Used humorously or cynically to refer to someone who only appears or contacts others for these major life events, often expecting financial support or sponsorship.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Akronim) Daglat ng 'Kasal, Binyag, Libing'; tumutukoy sa mga okasyong ito, lalo na kung inaasa sa iba ang gastos, o sa taong lumalapit lang para sa mga okasyong ito.

(Slang/Acronym) Abbreviation for 'Kasal, Binyag, Libing' (Wedding, Baptism, Funeral); refers to these events, especially when expecting others to pay, or to a person who only shows up for these events (often implying freeloading).

examples.example: Si Ninang, pang-KBL lang kung maalala ako.
My godmother only remembers me for KBL (Weddings, Baptisms, Funerals - implying she expects gifts/sponsorship).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Textspeak) Kasi.
(Slang/Textspeak) Because.

examples.example: Late ako kc traffic.
I'm late kc (because) of traffic.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'keri' (can handle) implying one can handle not caring, or a playful invention. Means 'don't care', 'whatever'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Walang pakialam; hindi alintana; bahala na.
(Slang) Don't care; not giving a damn; whatever.

examples.example: Naglayas siya at wala akong keber! Bahala siya sa buhay niya!
Keber (I don't care) if she ran away! Let her manage her own life!

etymology: Gay slang, from the name of Filipino actor/comedian Keempee de Leon. Used figuratively to mean 'tight' or 'constricted', possibly a pun on 'keep tightly' or sound association.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Mahigpit; masikip; makipot (madalas tumutukoy sa ari o puwit).
(Slang) Tight; constricted; narrow (often referring to genitals or anus).

examples.example: Ay, Keempee de Leon pala ang jowa mo, sis!
Oh, your boyfriend is Keempee de Leon (tight), sis!

etymology: Gay slang, possibly from Japanese 'dekiru' (can do, possible) or related to 'keri' (can handle). Implies someone is 'possible' as a boyfriend.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Lalaki na maaaring maging kasintahan o boyfriend; boyfriend material.
(Slang) A man who could potentially be a boyfriend; boyfriend material.

examples.example: Naramdaman ko na kekiru 'yan si Eric, at balang araw ay magiging kami, kahit beki ako!
I sense that Eric is a kekiru (boyfriend material), and that one day we'll be together, even though I'm gay!

etymology: Gay slang, from the name of American singer Kelly Clarkson. Used humorously as a rhyme or sound-alike for 'kili-kili' (armpit).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Kili-kili.
(Slang) Armpit.

examples.example: Mag-aahit na nga ako ng buhok sa kelly clarkson ko mamaya.
I'll shave my kelly clarkson (armpit) hair later!

etymology: Filipino slang, popular in the 1970s. Origin uncertain. A general term for a man or guy.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Lumang Slang) Lalaki.
(Slang/Dated Slang) Man; guy.

examples.example: Sino 'yung kelot na kasama mo kahapon?
Who was that kelot (guy) with you yesterday?

etymology: From the brand name 'Kelvinator' (refrigerators, etc.). Used humorously in gay slang to refer to someone getting fat, possibly referencing the large size of appliances or the 'coldness'/'slowness' associated with being overweight.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Png.) Taong tumaba o mataba. (Balbal Pnr.) Tumaba.
(Slang Noun) A person who got fat; a fat person. (Slang Adj.) Fat; got fat.

examples.example: Hindi ka naman masyadong naging kelvinator matapos ang ilang araw na pagkain sa buffet, konti lang!
You didn't turn into too much of a kelvinator (fat person) after eating at the buffet for days, just a little!

etymology: From 'Francisco 'Kenkoy' Harbat', a popular Filipino cartoon character known for his antics. Used to describe someone funny, playful, wacky, or clownish.

definitions.meaning: (Kolokyal Pnr.) Palabiro; nakakatawa; mapagpatawa; kalog. (Kolokyal Png.) Taong palabiro o nakakatawa.
(Colloquial Adj.) Funny; comical; jocular; playful; wacky. (Colloquial Noun) A funny or comical person; a joker; a clown.

examples.example: Masarap kasama sa inuman si Gardo dahil kenkoy siya at laging may baong joke.
It's fun drinking with Gardo because he's kenkoy (funny/wacky) and always has jokes ready.

etymology: Gay slang alteration of 'kayo' (you - plural or polite singular).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Kayo (panghalip panao, pangmaramihan o magalang na pang-isahan).
(Slang) You (pronoun, plural or polite singular).

examples.example: Saan pupunta keo?
Where are keo (you - plural/polite) going?

etymology: Filipino slang, shortened from 'kepyas' (vulgar term for vagina).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Bulgar) Ari o kaselanan ng babae; pinaikling 'kepyas'.
(Slang/Vulgar) Vagina; shortened from 'kepyas'.

examples.example: Maghugas ka ng keps mo!
Wash your keps (vagina)!

etymology: Filipino slang, possibly related to 'kiri' (flirtatious) or 'kengkay' (affectedly feminine). Means flirtatious, coquettish, or sometimes overly flamboyant or attention-seeking.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Malandi; makiri; maharot. (Balbal Png.) Taong malandi o makiri.
(Slang Adj.) Flirtatious; coquettish. (Slang Noun) A flirtatious person; a flirt.

examples.example: Huwag kang masyadong kerengkeng sa jowa ni Riri. Nambubunot 'yon ng buhok!
Don't be too kerengkeng (flirtatious) with Riri's boyfriend. She pulls hair!

etymology: Gay slang, likely derived from English 'carry' or 'can carry on', meaning can handle, manage, or endure. Extended to mean 'okay', 'all right', 'possible'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pdm.) Sige; okay; ayos lang. (Balbal Pnr.) Kaya; puwede; posible.
(Slang Interj.) Okay; all right. (Slang Adj.) Can handle; possible; feasible.

examples.example: Keri mo ba 'yan?
Keri (Can you handle) that?
Okay lang ba? Reply: Keri lang.
Is it okay? Reply: Keri lang (It's okay/Alright).

etymology: From Spanish vulgarism 'Â¡Que se joda!' meaning 'Let him/her/them be screwed/damned!' or 'To hell with him/her/them!'. Used as an interjection expressing strong indifference, annoyance, or dismissal.

definitions.meaning: (Mura mula sa Espanyol) Ekspresyong nagpapahayag ng matinding pagkainis, pagwawalang-bahala, o pagka-walang pakialam; 'Bahala na!'; 'Wala akong pakialam!'
(Vulgarism from Spanish) Interjection expressing strong annoyance, indifference, or dismissal; 'To hell with it!'; 'I don't give a damn!'

examples.example: Kesehoda mo ba 'yan?
Kesehoda (To hell with it) that?

etymology: From Spanish vulgarism 'Â¡Que se joda!' meaning 'Let him/her/them be screwed/damned!' or 'To hell with him/her/them!'. Used as an interjection expressing strong indifference, annoyance, or dismissal.

definitions.meaning: (Mura mula sa Espanyol) Ekspresyong nagpapahayag ng matinding pagkainis, pagwawalang-bahala, o pagka-walang pakialam; 'Bahala na!'; 'Wala akong pakialam!'
(Vulgarism from Spanish) Interjection expressing strong annoyance, indifference, or dismissal; 'To hell with it!'; 'I don't give a damn!'

examples.example: Hindi ko siya mapapatawad kesehodang umiyak pa siya ng mga bato!
I won't forgive him, kesehoda (to hell with it/I don't care) even if he cries tears of stone!

etymology: Gay slang, likely related to 'keme' or 'echos' (meaning nonsense, pretense, joke). Used to indicate something is not serious, untrue, or just a joke.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Png.) Biro; bagay na walang katotohanan. (Balbal Pdm.) Isang ekspresyon na nagsasabing hindi totoo o biro lang ang sinabi.
(Slang Noun) Joke; untruth. (Slang Interj.) Expression indicating the previous statement was a joke or untrue; just kidding.

examples.example: Sobrang gwapo mo... kheme!
You're so handsome... kheme (just kidding/not!)!

etymology: Filipino slang, likely derived from Hokkien Chinese, referring to a thousand. Specifically used for the one-thousand-peso bill.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Papel na salaping nagkakahalaga ng isang libong piso (â‚±1,000).
(Slang) One-thousand-peso bill (â‚±1,000).

examples.example: Uy, sis! May barya ka ba para sa bagong kiaw ko?
Hey, sis! Do you have change for my new kiaw (â‚±1,000 bill)?

etymology: Filipino colloquial term, often used affectionately. Refers to a girl or woman who is overtly feminine, fashion-conscious, interested in cosmetics and accessories, and often bubbly or playful. Can sometimes imply being slightly ditzy or overly concerned with appearance.

definitions.meaning: (Kolokyal Pnr.) Tumutukoy sa pagiging mahilig sa pagpapaganda, moda, at mga pambabaeng bagay. (Kolokyal Png.) Babae o dalagang mahilig magpaganda at sumunod sa uso; madalas ay masayahin o pilya din.

(Colloquial Adj.) Girly; fashion-conscious; interested in feminine things like makeup and accessories. (Colloquial Noun) A girl or woman who is overtly feminine, fashion-conscious, and often bubbly or playful.

examples.example: Mahilig siyang magdala ng kikay kit saan man pumunta.
She likes to bring her kikay kit (makeup/accessories kit) wherever she goes.

etymology: Taglish idiom combining Filipino 'kilig' (romantic thrill/excitement) and English 'to the bones' (meaning deeply or extremely).

definitions.meaning: (Idyoma/Taglish) Nakakaramdam ng matinding kilig (romantikong tuwa o excitement) na para bang tumatagos hanggang sa buto.
(Idiom/Taglish) Feeling an intense romantic thrill or giddiness ('kilig') that feels like it penetrates to the bones; extremely thrilled or giddy.

examples.example: Lihim siyang kinikilig to the bones kapag nginitian siya ni Diego.
She's secretly kilig to the bones (extremely thrilled/giddy) whenever Diego smiles at her.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'kimkim' (hold back, suppress) or 'kunwari' (pretend) with playful suffixes. Means pretentious, fake, or 'as if'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Kunwari; nagpapanggap; hindi totoo.
(Slang) Pretentious; fake; as if; not real.

examples.example: Pete, kimiladoo na mag-jowa tayo para pagselosin natin si Luis!
Pete, let's kimiladoo (pretend) that we are together to make Luis jealous!

etymology: Gay slang phrase combining 'King Kong' (large, strong, maybe masculine?) and 'Barbie' (doll, beautiful, feminine). Used paradoxically or humorously to describe a beautiful gay person, possibly implying a blend of masculine physique and feminine beauty/presentation, or just emphasizing extreme beauty.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Png.) Napakagandang bakla. (Balbal Pnr.) Tumutukoy sa pagiging napakaganda (ng isang bakla).
(Slang Noun) An exceptionally beautiful gay person (usually male). (Slang Adj.) Exceptionally beautiful (referring to a gay person).

examples.example: Ang daming beki na matutulungan ng kingkong barbie na si Jake kapag nag-vlog siya ng mga beauty lesson.
Jake, a kingkong barbie (beautiful gay person), could help a lot of other gays if he vlogs about beauty lessons.

etymology: Slang/vulgar term for vagina, origin uncertain. May be related to 'kepyas' or 'kipsi'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Bulgar) Ari o kaselanan ng babae; puki.
(Slang/Vulgar) Vagina.

examples.example: Kadiri ang amoy ng kipay niya.
The smell of her kipay (vagina) is disgusting.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly referencing a character perceived as ugly, or a playful alteration of 'pangit' (ugly) or related words.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pangit; hindi maganda.
(Slang) Ugly; unattractive.

examples.example: Hindi na ako kirara ngayon. Salamat sa mga beauty tip ni Jake sa kanyang vlog!
I'm no longer kirara (ugly). Thanks to Jake's beauty tips in his vlog!

etymology: Filipino word meaning flirtatious or coquettish, often with a negative connotation of being overly forward or promiscuous.

definitions.meaning: (Pnr.) Malandi; maharot; mapang-akit sa paraang hindi kaaya-aya. (Png.) Taong makiri o malandi.
(Adj.) Flirtatious or coquettish, often in an excessive or unseemly way. (Noun) A flirtatious person; a flirt (often with negative connotation).

examples.example: Kilala siya sa pagiging kiri sa opisina.
She's known for being kiri (overly flirtatious) at the office.

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'kiri' (flirtatious - implying wandering to flirt?) or 'gala' (wander). Means to wander around, roam, or loiter.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Gumala; maglakwatsa; maglibot.
(Slang) To wander about; to roam; to go out.

examples.example: Kirig tayo mamaya sa mall, Cess, bili tayo ng bagong damit!
Let's kirig (go out/wander) at the mall later, Cess, let's buy new clothes!

etymology: Portmanteau of English 'kiss' and 'aspirin'. A humorous, often romantic term suggesting a kiss is the cure for an ailment (like aspirin).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Mapagbiro) Pinagsamang 'kiss' (halik) at 'aspirin'; isang halik na itinuturing na lunas sa sakit o sama ng pakiramdam.
(Slang/Humorous) Portmanteau of 'kiss' and 'aspirin'; a kiss considered as a cure for illness or feeling unwell.

examples.example: Mukhang kailangan mo lang ng konting kisspirin mula sa jowa mo.
Looks like you just need a little kisspirin from your partner.

etymology: Filipino colloquialism, playful reduplication/alteration of 'kita-kita' (see each other, meet). Used informally to mean 'see you' or 'let's meet'.

definitions.meaning: (Kolokyal) Magkita-kita; magkita tayo. (Ginagamit bilang paalam na nangangahulugang 'magkita na lang tayo').
(Colloquial) Let's meet; see each other. (Used as a farewell meaning 'see you later/then').

examples.example: Sige, kita-kits na lang sa Lunes sa opisina, sis!
Okay, kita-kits (see you/let's meet) on Monday at the office, sis!

etymology: Filipino colloquial contraction of 'kita mo' (you see) or 'nakita mo' (did you see). Used like 'See?' or 'Told you so!'.

definitions.meaning: (Kolokyal) Pinaikling 'Kita mo?' o 'Nakita mo na?'; ginagamit para ipakita na tama ang sinabi o nangyari nga ang inaasahan.
(Colloquial) Contraction of 'Kita mo?' (You see?); used like 'See?' or 'Told you so!' to point out that one was right or something expected happened.

examples.example: Kitams! Sabi ko sa'yo mananalo tayo e!
Kitams (See)! I told you we would win!

etymology: Gay slang, variant of 'kheme', related to 'keme'/'echos'. Used to indicate something is not serious, untrue, or just a joke.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Png.) Biro; bagay na walang katotohanan. (Balbal Pdm.) Isang ekspresyon na nagsasabing hindi totoo o biro lang ang sinabi; katulad ng 'kheme'.
(Slang Noun) Joke; untruth. (Slang Interj.) Expression indicating the previous statement was a joke or untrue; just kidding; same as 'kheme'.

examples.example: Mahal kita... kiyeme!
I love you... kiyeme (just kidding)!

etymology: Common Filipino acronym for 'Kaniya-Kaniyang Bayad' (Each one pays their own). Refers to splitting the bill, going Dutch.

definitions.meaning: (Akronim/Idyoma) Daglat ng 'Kaniya-Kaniyang Bayad'; nangangahulugang bawat isa sa grupo ay magbabayad para sa sariling gastos.
(Acronym/Idiom) Abbreviation for 'Kaniya-Kaniyang Bayad' (Each one pays their own); means each person in a group pays for their own expenses; go Dutch.

examples.example: O, KKB tayo sa dinner mamaya ha?
Okay, let's KKB (go Dutch/split the bill) for dinner later, alright?

etymology: Filipino acronym, variant of KKB, standing for 'Kaniya-Kaniyang Hakot' (Each one brings/carries their own). Used for potlucks or situations where everyone brings their own contribution (food, items, etc.).

definitions.meaning: (Akronim/Idyoma) Daglat ng 'Kaniya-Kaniyang Hakot'; nangangahulugang bawat isa ay magdadala ng sariling ambag (pagkain, gamit, atbp.).
(Acronym/Idiom) Abbreviation for 'Kaniya-Kaniyang Hakot' (Each one brings their own); means each person brings their own contribution (food, items, etc.); potluck style.

examples.example: KKH tayo ng handa para sa party para marami tayong pagkain mamayang gabi!
Let's do KKH (potluck/bring our own) for the party preparations so we can have lots of food tonight!

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Tumutukoy sa pagiging killjoy. (Balbal Png.) Taong pumapatay sa kasiyahan; hindi marunong makisama; panira ng saya.
(Slang Adj.) Acting as a killjoy. (Slang Noun) Someone who spoils the fun for others; killjoy.

examples.example: Huwag ka ngang KJ, Kat! Sumama ka na sa amin sa sinehan, masaya 'to!
Don't be such a KJ (killjoy), Kat! Come with us to the theater, this will be fun!

etymology: Gay slang, origin uncertain. Possibly related to 'club' or 'kalabaw' (older gay) or just a playful sound. Means gay.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Bakla.
(Slang) Gay (man).

examples.example: Sa mga salita at kilos niya, alam ko nang klaboom siya.
From the way he talks and moves, I'm sure he's a klaboom (gay).

etymology: Gay slang, intensified form of 'klaboom' (gay) through reduplication.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Baklang-bakla; lantad ang pagiging bakla.
(Slang) Very gay; flamboyantly gay.

examples.example: Klaboomboom na ang datingan niya ngayon!
His vibe now is totally klaboomboom (very gay)!

etymology: Gay slang, playful onomatopoeic reduplication resembling the sound of clapping.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal) Pumalakpak.
(Slang) To clap.

examples.example: Magaling ang performance niya, klapeypey-klapeypey naman diyan!
Her performance was great, let's klapeypey-klapeypey (clap)!

etymology: Text/chat slang abbreviation for 'ka na ba?' (Are you already? / Have you already?).

definitions.meaning: (Balbal/Textspeak) Pinaikling 'ka na ba?' (hal. Kumain knb? - Kumain ka na ba?).
(Slang/Textspeak) Short for 'ka na ba?' (e.g., Kumain knb? - Have you eaten already?).

examples.example: Naligo knb? Ang baho mo pa rin.
Took a bath knb (Have you taken a bath already)? You still stink.

etymology: Gay slang, combination of English 'know' and a playful suffix '-sung'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pd.) Alam; nalalaman. (Balbal Pnr.) Tumutukoy sa pagkakaroon ng kaalaman.
(Slang Verb) To know; to be aware of. (Slang Adj.) Having knowledge.

examples.example: Hindi ko knowsung ang sagot sa tanong niya.
I don't knowsung (know) the answer to her question.

etymology: From the animal 'koala'. Used figuratively in gay slang, possibly referencing the animal's perceived sleepiness or slowness to mean crazy, insane, or 'out of it'.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Wala sa matinong pag-iisip; baliw. (Balbal Png.) Taong baliw.
(Slang Adj.) Insane; crazy. (Slang Noun) An insane or crazy person.

examples.example: Marites, umayos ka nga sa meeting mamaya, para hindi ka mapagkamalang koala!
Marites, act properly in the meeting later so people won't mistake you for a koala (crazy person)!

etymology: Gay slang, from the name of basketball player Kobe Bryant. Used figuratively to mean fat or chubby, possibly referencing his physique later in his career or just a random association.

definitions.meaning: (Balbal Pnr.) Mataba; chubby. (Balbal Png.) Taong mataba.
(Slang Adj.) Fat; chubby. (Slang Noun) A fat or chubby person.

etymology: Derived from the English word 'cowboy', used figuratively.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang tao na hindi maarte, madaling makibagay o makisama sa iba't ibang tao o sitwasyon, at hindi mapili.
Refers to someone who is not picky, easy-going, adaptable to different people or situations, and not fussy.

etymology: Derived from the brand name 'Kodak' with the Tagalog suffix '-an'.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagkuha ng litrato o retrato.
To take a picture or photograph.

examples.example: Punta tayo sa Luneta, tapos kodakan tayo.
Let's go to Luneta then let's take some pictures!

etymology: Derived from the English term 'call boy'.

definitions.meaning: Isang lalaking nagbebenta ng serbisyong sekswal kapalit ng bayad.
A male prostitute; a man who sells sexual services.

examples.example: Nagkalat ang kolboy sa mga sinehan.
There are a lot of kolboys in the movie houses.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagsasagawa ng oral sex sa isang lalaki.
To perform oral sex on a male; to perform fellatio.

examples.example: Kahit kailan ay hindi ko ikokopas ang asawa ko.
I will never perform oral sex on my husband.

etymology: Colloquial term, likely echoic or reduplicative for humorous emphasis on 'oldness'. Often used with 'nineteen-' to mean an unspecified time long ago.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa napakalumang panahon o bagay; sinauna o laos na.
Referring to a very old time or thing; ancient, old-fashioned, or outdated.

examples.example: Ipinanganak siya noong nineteen kopong-kopong.
She was born way back in nineteen kopong-kopong (a very long time ago).

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of the English word 'correct'.

definitions.meaning: Tama o wasto.
Correct or right.

examples.example: Kung hinihinala mong may ibang jowa siya, korakding ka diyan, sis.
If you suspect she has another lover, you are correct, sis!

etymology: Colloquial term, origin uncertain. Refers specifically to petty extortion, usually by authorities.

definitions.meaning: Pera o halagang hinihingi (karaniwan ng nasa awtoridad tulad ng pulis o traffic enforcer) bilang suhol o para maiwasan ang parusa o abala; panghihingi o pangunguwarta.
Money demanded, typically by someone in authority (like police or traffic enforcers), as a bribe or to avoid punishment or hassle; petty extortion.

etymology: Descriptive phrase: 'kotse' (car) + '-ng' + 'kuba' (hunchback), referring to the distinctive shape of the Volkswagen Beetle.

definitions.meaning: Kolokyal na tawag o palayaw para sa modelong Volkswagen Beetle na kotse, dahil sa hugis nitong tila kuba.
Colloquial name or nickname for the Volkswagen Beetle car model, due to its distinctive 'hunchbacked' shape.
Tumutukoy sa pagiging mataba.
Referring to being fat.
Tumutukoy sa katawan na kaakit-akit o angkop para sa romansa o gawaing sekswal.
Refers to a body that is attractive or deemed suitable for romance or sexual activity; a sexy body.

etymology: Slang term, likely onomatopoeic (imitating stomach sounds) or bekimon.

definitions.meaning: Nakakaramdam ng gutom.
Feeling hungry.

examples.example: Saan ba masarap kumain? Krang-krang na ako.
Do you know a good place to eat? I'm krang-krang already (I'm hungry already).

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of the English word 'face'.

definitions.meaning: Ang mukha ng isang tao.
A person's face.

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of the Tagalog word 'dalawa' (two).

definitions.meaning: Ang bilang na dalawa.
The number two.

examples.example: Hindi lang isa, kundi krolawa ang summa cum laude sa batch natin.
Not just one, but there are two summa cum laudes from our batch.

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of the Tagalog word 'sampu' (ten).

definitions.meaning: Ang bilang na sampu.
The number ten.

etymology: Slang term popularized in the Philippines by Sandara Park, meaning wacky or eccentric. Origin uncertain.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa pagiging kakatwa, sira-ulo, o wala sa tamang pag-iisip, madalas ginagamit sa pabirong paraan.
Refers to being crazy, wacky, eccentric, or weird, often used playfully.

etymology: Acronym for the Tagalog phrase 'kulang sa pansin'.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang tao na labis na naghahanap o humihingi ng atensyon mula sa iba o papansin.
Refers to someone who excessively seeks attention from others; an attention seeker.
Mga sinasabi, madalas ay walang katuturan o paulit-ulit na reklamo (parang nagna-nagging).
Things said, often in a nagging or rambling way; chatter.

examples.example: Ayaw ko na sa nanay mo, ang dami niyang kuda.
I don't like your mother, she has so many kuda.

definitions.meaning: Kotse.
Car.

etymology: Association with a celebrity name ('Kuh Ledesma'), playful coinage possibly related to 'kulob' (stuffy) or 'baho' (stinky).

definitions.meaning: Hindi mabango; tumutukoy sa masamang amoy ng katawan (putok).
Not fragrant; refers to having an unpleasant body odor.

examples.example: Ivan, binilhan kita ng deodorant para mawala ang kuh ledesma mo.
Ivan, I bought you a deodorant for your kuh ledesma.

etymology: Origin uncertain, possibly onomatopoeic or playful coinage.

definitions.meaning: Libag o namuong pulbos (o dumi) sa ilalim ng suso.
Accumulated dirt or powder formed under the breasts.

examples.example: Ang dami niyang nilagay na pulbos. Puro siya kukurikapu ngayon.
She put in so many powder. Now she's full of kukurikapu.

definitions.meaning: Isang ekspresyon na nagpapahiwatig ng labis na pagsamba o paghanga sa isang minamahal.
An expression used to show excessive adoration or admiration for a loved one.
Tawag pabalbal o slang para sa St. Scholastica's College.
Slang term for St. Scholastica's College.

etymology: Possibly related to the term for students of St. Scholastica's College ('Kulasa'), but used here for 'maid'.

definitions.meaning: Isang katulong o kasambahay na babae.
A female domestic helper or maid.

etymology: From 'kulasisi', a type of bird (Philippine hanging parrot), known for being noisy or sometimes kept as pets.

definitions.meaning: Ang babaeng kinakasama ng isang lalaking may asawa na; kabit.
The other woman in an extramarital affair; a mistress.

examples.example: Wala kang mapapala sa pagiging kulasisi lang.
You won't gain anything from being a kulasisi.

etymology: From Spanish 'culata' (butt of a rifle), implying being hit with it.

definitions.meaning: Ang gulpihin o bugbugin, lalo na gamit ang puluhan ng baril.
To beat up or hit someone, especially with the butt of a rifle.
Palaging nahuhuli o laging nasa huling puwesto, lalo na sa mga paligsahan o laro.
Always finishing last or being at the bottom rank, especially in contests or games.

etymology: From 'kuliling' (small bell, tinker), implying a screw loose or head rattling.

definitions.meaning: May sayad sa ulo o loko-loko.
Crazy or eccentric; having a screw loose.
Kulot ang buhok.
Having curly hair.

examples.example: Hayun ang syota kong kulutrang. Ang ganda, ano?
There's my girlfriend who's kulutrang. Isn't she beautiful?

definitions.meaning: Ang misis o asawang babae ng isang lalaking 'ander de saya' (sunud-sunuran sa asawa).
The wife of a man who is subject to her authority (henpecked).

examples.example: Pinayagan ako ni kumander na uminom basta dalawang bote lang ng beer.
Kumander said that I can drink two bottles of beer.

definitions.meaning: Ang umamin sa mga nagawang kasalanan o pagkakamali.
To confess one's mistakes or wrongdoings.

examples.example: Siguraduhin mo na ikumpipi lahat kung hindi ay iiwanan kita.
Make sure that you kumpipi all or else I will leave you!

definitions.meaning: Ginagamit upang ipahiwatig na ang sinabi ay hindi totoo, nagpapanggap lamang, o may pag-aalinlangan; kunwari o daw.
Used to indicate that something said is untrue, pretended, doubtful, or based on hearsay; supposedly, allegedly, or pretending.

examples.example: Ang talino talaga niya, kuno!
You're really smart, kuno!

definitions.meaning: (png.) Libag o namuong dumi (smegma) sa ulo ng ari ng lalaki.
(n.) Smegma; dried sebum around the head of the penis.
(pnr.) Isang taong makapal ang mukha, walanghiya, o may hindi kanais-nais na ugali.
(adj.) Having a disagreeable or shameless character; asshole.

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of 'kupal' (possibly linking the unpleasantness to difficult exams).

definitions.meaning: Eksamen o mahirap na pagsubok.
An exam or difficult challenge.
Pangit ang mukha o mukhang halimaw.
Having an ugly or monstrous face.

examples.example: Ang daming nagmamaganda riyan pero kurimaw naman.
There are many people who pretend to be beautiful but they are really kurimaw.

definitions.meaning: Malakas na pagbatok o paghampas sa ulo o batok.
A strong hit on the back of the head or nape.
Mahinang pagbatok o pagpalo sa ulo o batok.
A soft hit or light tap on the back of the head or nape.
Ang kuhanin o dalhin ang tsinelas.
To get or fetch the slippers.

examples.example: Kuwatsi mo sa kuwarto. Pula ang akin.
Kuwatsi in the room. Mine is red.

etymology: Idiomatic phrase, literally 'barber's story'. Originates from the stereotype of barbershops being places for gossip and exaggerated tales.

definitions.meaning: Isang kuwento na hindi totoo, gawa-gawa lamang, o labis na pinalaking bersyon ng pangyayari; tsismis o imbento.
A story that is untrue, fabricated, or highly exaggerated; a rumor, tall tale, or fabrication.

examples.example: Ayan ka na naman sa mga kuwentong barbero mo.
There you go again with your tall tales.

etymology: Colloquial verb use derived from the standard Tagalog noun 'kuyog' (crowd, swarm).

definitions.meaning: Ang pagtulungan o sugurin ng isang grupo ng tao ang isang indibidwal.
To be ganged up on or attacked by a group of people; to be mobbed.
Pinaikling anyo ng panghalip na 'ikaw'.
Abbreviated form of the pronoun 'ikaw' (you).

etymology: Standard Tagalog filler word used when one cannot recall or prefers not to mention a specific noun, name, or action.

definitions.meaning: Salitang pamalit o pantawag sa isang bagay, tao, lugar, o aksyon na hindi maalala o ayaw tukuying direkta.
A filler word used as a substitute for a noun, name, place, or action that one cannot recall or chooses not to specify directly.

examples.example: Ang hilig mong gumamit ng kwan.
You like to use that placeholder 'kwan'.

etymology: Literally 'four corners', referring to the iconic square shape of the Ginebra San Miguel gin bottle.

definitions.meaning: Kolokyal na tawag sa alak na gin, partikular na tumutukoy sa tatak na Ginebra San Miguel dahil sa apat na kanto ng bote nito.
Colloquial term for gin, specifically referring to the brand Ginebra San Miguel due to its four-cornered bottle.

examples.example: Huwag ka nang malungkot. Kuwatro-kantos lang ang katapat niyan!
Don't be sad. You just need some gin!

etymology: Named possibly for the sound quail ('pugo') make, or simply a playful name. A popular Filipino street food.

definitions.meaning: Pagkaing kalye na gawa sa nilagang itlog ng pugo na binalutan sa matingkad na kahel na harina (batter) at saka pinirito nang malalim.
A street food made of hard-boiled quail eggs coated in a bright orange batter and then deep-fried.

etymology: Derived from the Spanish word 'cuidado' (care, be careful).

definitions.meaning: Mag-ingat; panawagan o paalala na maging maingat.
To be careful; an expression urging caution.

examples.example: Kwidaw ka riyan kay Kulasa. Anak 'yan ng Diyos.
Be careful with Kulasa. She's a child of God.

definitions.meaning: Nangangahulugang pantay na ang bayarin, puntos, o kalagayan; wala nang utang o lamang sa isa't isa.
Meaning that accounts, scores, or situations are even; having no outstanding debt or advantage over each other; settled.

examples.example: Ayan, nakabayad na ako sa iyo. Kwits na tayo.
There, I already paid you. We're quits now.

etymology: Likely onomatopoeic, imitating the sound of incessant chatter or nagging.

definitions.meaning: Walang tigil o walang katuturang pagdadaldal o pagsasalita, madalas na nakakairita o parang pagbubunganga.
Incessant or meaningless talking or chattering, often in an annoying or nagging manner.

examples.example: Kyawkyaw naman ang mga pulitiko dahil malapit na ang eleksyon.
Politicians keep on chattering (kyawkyaw) because election day is near.

definitions.meaning: Pangit o hindi kaaya-aya ang hitsura.
Ugly or unpleasant in appearance.
Mabaho o may hindi kaaya-ayang amoy.
Foul-smelling or stinky.

etymology: Bekimon slang, likely an elaboration of 'okay' or 'OK'.

definitions.meaning: Nangangahulugang okey, ayos lang, o katanggap-tanggap.
Meaning okay, alright, or acceptable.

examples.example: Mukha namang disente ang manliligaw mo kaya kyla na sa akin.
Your suitor looks decent so he's okay with me.

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of the Tagalog word 'paa' (foot/feet).

definitions.meaning: Ang mga paa.
Feet.

examples.example: Maghugas ka nga ng kyoastra mong amoy patay na daga.
Wash your feet! They smell like a dead rat.

etymology: Bekimon slang expression, origin uncertain, possibly onomatopoeic representing a reaction to a bad smell.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyon ng pagkadiri o pagkasuklam, lalo na dahil sa masamang amoy.
An expression of disgust, especially in reaction to a bad smell.

examples.example: Kyohmp! Sino ang umutot sa kuwarto?
Kyohmp! Who farted in the room?

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of the English word 'volleyball'.

definitions.meaning: Ang larong volleyball.
The sport of volleyball.

etymology: Bekimon phrase, euphemistic or poetic slang for vagina. 'Kyolting' origin uncertain, 'pangwakas' means final/ultimate.

definitions.meaning: Maseselang bahagi ng katawan ng babae; puki.
Vagina.

examples.example: Si Jake ang aking prinsipe at ang aking kyolting pangwakas ay para lamang sa kaniya.
Jake is my prince charming and my vagina is only for him.

etymology: Bekimon slang term, likely an elaboration related to 'tomboy'.

definitions.meaning: Isang babaeng homoseksuwal; lesbiyana o tomboy.
A homosexual woman; a lesbian or tomboy.

examples.example: Nakita ba ninyo 'yong bagong nars? That haircut makes me think she's a kyombers.
Have you seen the new nurse? That haircut makes me think she's a lesbian.

etymology: Bekimon phrase combining an elaboration of 'tomboy' with the name of Filipino TV host Boy Abunda, used playfully or ironically.

definitions.meaning: Isang babaeng homoseksuwal; tomboy o tibo.
A homosexual woman; tomboy or lesbian.

examples.example: Nasa ika-anim na grado ako nang sinabi ko sa mga magulang ko na ako ay isang kyomboy abunda.
I was in grade six when I told my parents that I'm a lesbian.

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of the Tagalog word 'anim' (six).

definitions.meaning: Ang bilang na anim.
The number six.

examples.example: Kyonim na taon rin bago ako naka-gradweyt ng kolehiyo.
I spent six years before I graduated from college.

etymology: Bekimon elaboration of the Tagalog word 'apat' (four).

definitions.meaning: Ang bilang na apat.
The number four.

examples.example: Kyopat na pala ang anak ninyo? Ang bilis ng panahon!
You have four children already? How time flies!

etymology: Abbreviation commonly standing for either 'Luneta' (Rizal Park in Manila) or 'La Union' (a province known for beaches).

definitions.meaning: Pinaikling tawag para sa Luneta (parke sa Maynila) o sa probinsya ng La Union.
Abbreviation for either Luneta (a park in Manila) or the province of La Union.

examples.example: Sayang, hindi natuloy ang pagpunta ko ng l.u. Sisiguraduhin kong tuloy na ito sa susunod na buwan.
Unfortunately, my trip to L.U. (likely La Union in this context) was canceled. I'll make sure it will push through next month.

etymology: Text speak and slang abbreviation for 'lips to lips'.

definitions.meaning: Ang paghalik sa labi ng ibang tao.
To kiss someone on the lips.

examples.example: Hindi na talaga nahiya ang dalawang iyon. Nag-l2l pa talaga in public!
Those two really have no shame. They even kissed lips-to-lips in public!

etymology: Bekimon phrase, likely a pun on 'laos' (obsolete, faded) combined with 'ocean deep' to imply disappearance, failure, or being profoundly out of fashion.

definitions.meaning: Bigo sa isang layunin o plano; hindi nagtagumpay.
Having failed in an objective or plan; unsuccessful.
Hindi na sikat o uso; laos na.
No longer famous or fashionable; has-been; outdated.

examples.example: Hindi ako nagsisisi na la ocean deep ang pagpunta ko sa Saudi Arabia dahil nakilala ko naman si Gloria sa Pilipinas.
I don't regret that my plan to go to Saudi Arabia failed (was la ocean deep) because I got to meet Gloria by staying in the Philippines.

definitions.meaning: Figuratibong 'lagnat' o pakiramdam na nararanasan ng isang taong umiibig o kinikilig.
A figurative 'fever' or feeling experienced by someone who is in love or infatuated.

examples.example: Hindi totoong sakit yan. Nila-labnat lang siya.
He's not really sick. He just has 'love fever' (labnat)!

etymology: Idiomatic phrase, literally 'unfurl the cape'. Figuratively means to reveal one's true self, often used in the context of coming out as LGBTQ+ or revealing a secret identity.
