definitions.meaning: Ang paglalantad o pag-amin sa tunay na pagkatao, kasarian, o damdamin na dating itinago.
To reveal one's true identity, gender, or feelings that were previously hidden; to come out (of the closet).

examples.example: Oras na para ako'y magladlad ng kapa. Ako si Darna!
It's time for me to reveal my true self (ladlad ng kapa). I'm Darna!

definitions.meaning: (Pandiwa) Kumain, lalo na nang may gana o marami.
(Verb) To eat, especially heartily or excessively.
(Pandiwa) Magsagawa ng oral sex sa lalaki; tsumupa.
(Verb) To perform oral sex on a male; to give a blowjob.
(Pangngalan) Pagkain.
(Noun) Food.
(Pang-uri) Mayabang o hambog.
(Adjective) Boastful or arrogant.

examples.example: Teka lang muna. Gutom na ako. Lafang muna me.
Wait a minute. I'm already hungry. I'll eat (lafang) first.

etymology: Derived from the slang verb 'lafang' (to eat) + '-an' (place suffix).

definitions.meaning: Isang lugar kung saan maaaring kumain; kainan.
A place where one can eat; an eatery or restaurant.

examples.example: Sunod ka sa amin sa lafangan mamaya pagkatapos ng trabaho mo.
Follow us at the eatery (lafangan) after your work.

etymology: Bekimon slang, variation or elaboration of 'lafang' (to eat).

definitions.meaning: Kumain.
To eat.

examples.example: Lafez ka na riyan. Nagluto ako ng paborito mong adobo.
You may now eat (lafez) there. I cooked your favorite adobo.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na palibut-libot, walang permanenteng tirahan, o mahilig maglakbay kung saan-saan.
A person who wanders about, has no permanent home, or likes to travel widely; a wanderer or vagrant.

examples.example: Halos malibot na niya ang mundo sa pagiging lagalag.
He has almost traveled around the world from being a wanderer (lagalag).

etymology: Standard Tagalog word, likely onomatopoeic for the sound of a heavy impact.

definitions.meaning: Ang malakas na tunog ng pagbagsak ng isang bagay.
The loud sound of something falling heavily; a thud or crash.

examples.example: Nakarinig ako ng lagapak sa kuwarto mo habang wala ka.
I heard a loud thud (lagapak) in your room while you were gone.

etymology: Figurative use of the standard Tagalog noun 'lagari' (a saw), referring to the back-and-forth motion, implying juggling multiple jobs, tasks, or commitments.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa kalagayan ng pagkakaroon ng maraming trabaho, gawain, o commitment nang sabay-sabay.
Refers to the state of having or juggling multiple jobs, tasks, or commitments simultaneously; moonlighting.

examples.example: Lagare ka na naman. Baka magkasakit ka na niyan.
You're juggling multiple commitments (lagare) again. You might get sick.

etymology: Colloquial meaning derived from the standard Tagalog word 'lagay' (act of putting/placing, state, condition), specifically referring to placing money for illicit purposes.

definitions.meaning: Perang ibinabayad bilang suhol, lalo na sa mga awtoridad, upang makalusot sa batas o makakuha ng pabor.
Money paid as a bribe, especially to authorities, to circumvent rules or gain favors; payoff.

examples.example: Binigyan nila ng malaking lagay ang enforcer para maabswelto.
They gave a big bribe (lagay) to the enforcer so they could be cleared.

etymology: Slang term created by inverting the syllables of the Tagalog word 'bulag' (blind).

definitions.meaning: Binaligtad na salitang 'bulag'; maaaring tumukoy sa literal na pagkabulag o, mas karaniwan, sa pagiging bulag sa katotohanan o pagkakamali (figuratibo).
Reversed form of 'bulag' (blind); can refer to literal blindness or, more commonly, being figuratively blind to the truth or faults.

examples.example: Niloloko ka na niya pero mahal mo pa rin. Lagbu ka na ba?
He's cheating on you yet you still love him. Are you blind (lagbu)?

etymology: Standard Tagalog verb, often used colloquially or hyperbolically to mean excessive or unrestrained consumption.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagkain o pag-inom nang labis, mabilis, o walang pagpipigil, lalo na ng alak.
To eat or drink excessively, rapidly, or without restraint; to guzzle or chug, especially alcohol.

examples.example: Mag-chill tayo sa Congo Bar para maka-laklak tayo hanggang umaga.
Let's chill at the Congo Bar so we can drink heavily (laklak) until the morning.

etymology: Colloquial nickname or shortening for 'La ConsolaciÃ³n College', likely derived from the first two syllables.

definitions.meaning: Palayaw o pinaikling tawag para sa paaralang La ConsolaciÃ³n College.
Nickname or shortened term for La ConsolaciÃ³n College.

examples.example: Sa LakÃ³ ka rin ba grumadweyt?
Did you also graduate from LakÃ³ (La ConsolaciÃ³n College)?

etymology: From Mexican Spanish 'cuacha' (lazy person/idler), adapted into Tagalog. Refers to aimless wandering, loitering, or playing truant.

definitions.meaning: Ang paggala o paglibot nang walang tiyak na pakay, madalas para sa pagliliwaliw o pag-iwas sa mga responsibilidad tulad ng pag-aaral o trabaho.
To wander or roam aimlessly, often for leisure or to avoid responsibilities like school or work; to gallivant or play truant.

examples.example: Pagkatapos ng exam, maglalakwatsa talaga ako kasama ng mga kaibigan ko.
After the exam, I will really go out and wander (lakwatsa) with my friends.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term, origin uncertain. Appears to be playful reduplication.

definitions.meaning: Isang tomboy o lesbiyana na itinuturing na labis na sabik o agresibo sa sekswal na paraan.
A lesbian perceived as overly eager or sexually aggressive.

examples.example: 'Wag kang masyadong mabilis sa panliligaw kay Julie baka isipin niya na lala lalu ka.
Don't be too aggressive in courting Julie because she might think that you're a lala lalu (overly eager/aggressive lesbian).

etymology: Slang term, likely a blend or portmanteau of 'lalaki' (man) and 'babae' (woman), used to refer to an effeminate or gay man.

definitions.meaning: Isang lalaking mahinhin kumilos o itinuturing na bakla.
An effeminate man; a gay man.

examples.example: Hindi ninyo siya kailangang tawanan dahil lang lalakwe siya.
You don't have to ridicule him just because he is a lalakwe (effeminate/gay).

etymology: Vulgar slang meaning derived from the standard Tagalog verb 'lamas' (to knead, mash, squeeze forcefully).

definitions.meaning: Ang paghawak, pagpisil, o paglaro sa dibdib ng isang babae, madalas sa bastos o hindi kanais-nais na paraan.
To touch, squeeze, or fondle a woman's breasts, often in a vulgar or unwanted manner; to grope.

examples.example: Binastos siya sa bus nang may lalakeng nagtangkang lamasin ang dibdib niya.
She was harassed on the bus when a man tried to grope (lamas) her breasts.

etymology: Colloquial term, likely a variant of 'lakwatsa', possibly influenced by other words. Used similarly to mean going out aimlessly or for leisure.

definitions.meaning: Ang paggala o pamamasyal nang walang tiyak na patutunguhan; maglakwatsa.
To go out wandering or strolling without a specific destination; to gallivant.

examples.example: Ang mabuting mag-aaral ay umuuwi sa bahay at hindi na nagla-lamierda.
A good student goes home after school and does not wander around (lamierda).

etymology: Slang term for 'gay man', origin uncertain.

definitions.meaning: Lalaking homoseksuwal; bakla.
A gay man.

examples.example: Nagpapanggap lang siyang lanak para mapalapit kay Aubrey.
He's just pretending to be a lanak (gay) to get close to Aubrey.

etymology: Figurative use of the standard Tagalog word 'langaw' (fly). Used colloquially to describe a place, typically a business establishment, that is deserted or has very few customers, implying it's being avoided.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang lugar, lalo na tindahan o restawran, na walang gaanong tao o customer; nilalayuan o iniiwasan.
Refers to a place, especially a store or restaurant, that is deserted or has very few customers; unpopular or avoided.

examples.example: Langaw na ang cafe mula nang umalis ang barista nila.
That cafe became deserted (langaw) when their barista left.

etymology: Figurative slang use of standard Tagalog 'langis' (oil), likely referencing 'padulas' (grease money/lubricant) or the idea that money makes things run smoothly.

definitions.meaning: Pera, lalo na kung ginagamit bilang pampadulas o suhol upang mapabilis ang proseso o makakuha ng pabor.
Money, especially when used as a bribe or incentive ('grease money') to expedite processes or gain favors.

examples.example: Kailangan ng konting langis para mapirmahan agad ang papeles mo.
You need a little 'oil' (langis/money) to get your papers signed quickly.

etymology: Standard Tagalog word meaning 'exposed', 'visible', 'open'. Commonly used colloquially, especially within the LGBTQ+ community, to mean 'out of the closet'.

definitions.meaning: Hayag, kita, o hindi na nakatago; partikular na tumutukoy sa pagiging bukas tungkol sa sekswalidad o pagkakakilanlan ng kasarian (hal., lantad na bakla).
Exposed, visible, or no longer hidden; specifically refers to being open about one's sexuality or gender identity (i.e., 'out of the closet').

examples.example: Lantad na ang pagiging beki ni Diego sa pamilya niya noong isang taon pa.
Diego being gay has been openly known (lantad) to his family since last year.

etymology: Figurative compound phrase from 'lanta' (wilted) + '-ng' + 'kulangot' (booger). Evokes an image of extreme tiredness or listlessness.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa sobrang pagod, kawalan ng lakas, o pagiging matamlay.
Refers to being extremely tired, lacking energy, or listless; exhausted.

examples.example: Ang aga-aga ay mukha ka na agad lantang-kulangot!
It's still early but you already look exhausted (lantang-kulangot)!

etymology: Slang meaning derived from standard Tagalog 'lapa' (to butcher, devour meat greedily), figuratively applied to the violent act of rape.

definitions.meaning: Ang marahas na paggahasa o sekswal na pagsasamantala sa isang tao.
To rape or sexually assault someone violently.

examples.example: Ikinuwento ng biktima kung paano siya nilapa ng mga salarin.
The victim recounted how she was raped (nilapa) by the perpetrators.

etymology: Slang term used primarily by Filipinos, especially those working abroad (OFWs), to refer to a 10,000 Japanese Yen banknote. The term 'lapad' means 'width' in Tagalog, possibly referring to the note's size or value.

definitions.meaning: Sampung libong Japanese Yen (Â¥10,000), karaniwang tumutukoy sa papel de bangko nito.
Ten thousand Japanese Yen (Â¥10,000), usually referring to the banknote.

examples.example: Yaman pala ni girl. Kumikita ng lapad kada linggo!
That girl is rich. She earns 10,000 yen (lapad) every week!

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon or gay slang, origin uncertain. Refers to passionate kissing.

definitions.meaning: Ang malalim o mapusok na halikan; French kiss.
Deep or passionate kissing; French kiss; making out.

examples.example: Nadurog ang puso ko nang mahuli kong nakikipaglapchukan si Bert kay Gil.
My heart broke into pieces when I caught Bert making out (lapchukan) with Gil. My husband is gay!

etymology: Slang term for 'loud voice'. Origin uncertain, possibly figurative or related to lapel microphones amplifying voice.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa pagkakaroon ng malakas o maingay na boses.
Refers to having a loud or noisy voice.

examples.example: Lapel ka masyado. Dinig kita hanggang sa kabilang building.
You are too loud-voiced (lapel). I can hear you from the other building. Keep your voice down.

etymology: Slang, likely a Bekimon variant spelling/pronunciation of 'lafang' or 'lafez'.

definitions.meaning: Kumain, lalo na nang may gana.
To eat, especially heartily.

examples.example: Tara, lapez na tayo, gutom na ako.
Come on, let's eat (lapez), I'm hungry.

etymology: Colloquial term, perhaps related to 'kurot' (pinch), implying repeated or intense pinching driven by affection ('gigil') or irritation.

definitions.meaning: Ang paulit-ulit o mariing pagpisil o pagkurot sa balat ng isang tao dahil sa matinding emosyon tulad ng panggigigil (sa tuwa o inis).
To pinch someone's skin repeatedly or forcefully due to strong emotion, such as overwhelming affection/cuteness ('gigil') or irritation.

examples.example: Kapag nagagalit si Nanay ay nilalapirot niya ang aking mga braso.
When Nanay gets mad, she pinches (lapirot) my arms.

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon, origin uncertain. Suggests vigorous or excessive eating.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagkain nang marami, mabilis, at may malaking gana.
To eat a large amount of food quickly and heartily; to wolf down food.

examples.example: Lapokstra ako sa birthday ni Reslor. Grabe, panalo lahat ng handa!
I ate voraciously (lapokstra) at Reslor's birthday! Wow, all the food was delicious!

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon or gay slang, origin uncertain. Refers to intense kissing or making out.

definitions.meaning: Masidhi o mapusok na halikan o paglalaplapan, madalas bilang panimula sa pagtatalik.
Intense or passionate kissing or making out, often as foreplay.

examples.example: Natuwa si Nena sa kanilang lapongga ni Borge.
Nena was aroused by her make out session (lapongga) with Borge.

etymology: Taglish phrase combining English 'laughing' and 'trip' (in the colloquial sense of a mood, state, or phase).

definitions.meaning: Isang kalagayan o mood kung saan ang isang tao ay natatawa nang husto, madaling matuwa, o gusto lamang tumawa.
A state or mood wherein someone finds things extremely funny, is easily amused, or simply feels like laughing uncontrollably.

examples.example: Ayoko ng malungkot, ateng. Laughing trip ako ngayon.
I don't want to be sad, sis. I'm in a laughing trip (mood) now!

etymology: Idiomatic Tagalog phrase from 'lawit' (hanging out) + '-ng' + 'dila' (tongue). Literally means 'tongue hanging out', figuratively used to describe intense craving, desire, or sexual arousal.

definitions.meaning: Nalilibugan o labis na nasasabik o naghahangad sa isang bagay o tao.
Sexually aroused or intensely craving or desiring something or someone.

examples.example: Lawit-dila ka na nang magsimulang maghubad 'yung macho dancer sa stage, ha!
You were practically drooling (lawit-dila) when the macho dancer started taking his shirt off on stage!

etymology: Tagalog slang adaptation or pronunciation of the English word 'lousy'.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang bagay na may mababang kalidad, pangit, o hindi kasiya-siya.
Refers to something of poor quality, bad, or unsatisfactory; lousy.

examples.example: Huwag mong gawin 'yang lawsi moves sa basketbol!
Don't make those lousy moves in the basketball game!

etymology: Slang term created by inverting the syllables of 'sosyal', which itself is derived from English 'social'. Means high-class, fancy, or sophisticated.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa pagiging sosyal, magarbo, o pang-mataas na lipunan.
Refers to being high-class, fancy, sophisticated, or characteristic of high society.

examples.example: Ang laysho ng mga bisita sa handaan ni mayora.
Mayora's visitors at the party are so posh/high-class (laysho).

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name of Filipino singer/actress Lea Navarro as a playful substitute for a similar-sounding word, English 'borrow'.

definitions.meaning: Ang paghiram o pag-utang ng isang bagay.
To borrow something.

examples.example: Puwede bang i-lea navarro muna ang ballpen mo?
Can I lea navarro (borrow) your ballpen for a moment?

etymology: Slang term playing on the political term 'leftist' and the Tagalog slang 'kaliwete' (literally 'left-handed'), which is used euphemistically for a man having an affair (from 'kaliwa' meaning 'left', implying something illicit or 'on the side').

definitions.meaning: Isang lalaking babaero o may ibang babae maliban sa kanyang asawa o kasintahan; kaliwete.
A womanizer or a man who has affairs outside of his main relationship; a philanderer.

examples.example: Kalimutan mo na siya. Balang araw ay kakarmahin din ang leftist na iyon.
Forget him. One day that womanizer (leftist) will get his karma.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name of Filipino politician Loren Legarda as a playful substitute for 'legs'.

definitions.meaning: Ang mga binti ng tao.
A person's legs.

examples.example: Sakto ang haba ng legarda mo para maging isa kang beauty queen.
Your legs (legarda) are long enough for you to be a beauty queen.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term, likely using a celebrity name (e.g., Leila Hermosa) playfully associated with being passive or allowing the partner to take control during sex.

definitions.meaning: Isang lalaki na hinahayaan ang kanyang kapareha (karaniwan ay babae) na manguna o maging dominante habang nagtatalik.
A man who prefers a passive role or lets his partner take the lead during sexual intercourse.

examples.example: Sa unang gabi namin ay magpapakaleila hermoza ako.
On our first night together, I'll be a leila hermoza (let her take the lead).

etymology: An affectionate or familiar term of address and reference for 'lola' (grandmother) in Tagalog.

definitions.meaning: Isang mapagmahal o pamilyar na tawag sa lola.
An affectionate or familiar term for grandmother.

examples.example: Tumakas ka na habang tulog pa ang lelang mo.
Sneak out while your grandma (lelang) is asleep.

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon or gay slang, origin uncertain. Refers to passionate kissing.

definitions.meaning: Mapusok o malalim na halikan; paglalaplapan.
Passionate or deep kissing; making out.

examples.example: Nakita ko ang leptolelang ni Gary at Cheny habang nasa loob ng sinehan.
I saw Gary and Cheny making out passionately (leptolelang) while inside the cinema.

etymology: Slang term created by inverting the syllables of the Tagalog word 'pulis' (police).

definitions.meaning: Isang pulis.
A police officer.

examples.example: Migs, dumistansiya ka dahil lespu ang jowa ni Melba.
Migs, you're treading on thin ice. Melba's boyfriend is a cop (lespu).

etymology: Slang use of the English word 'liberty', playing on the concept of 'freedom' from payment.

definitions.meaning: Walang bayad; libre.
Free of charge; gratis.

examples.example: Payday ni Lassy ngayon kaya lahat ng order natin ay liberty na!
It's Lassy's payday today so our orders are all free (liberty)!

etymology: Figurative slang use of the standard Tagalog verb 'ligwak' (to spill over, be eliminated from a container), applied to the state of being eliminated, disqualified, or having failed.

definitions.meaning: Tanggal na sa isang kompetisyon, eksamen, o proseso; hindi nakapasa o natalo.
Eliminated or disqualified from a competition, exam, or process; failed or lost.

examples.example: Ligwak na siya sa top payb. Bawi na lang sa susunod.
She's out (ligwak) from the top five. Better luck next time.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term, possibly referencing a celebrity named Lilet known for her youthfulness, used to refer to a young gay person.

definitions.meaning: Isang bata o binatang bakla.
A young gay person (boy or young man).

examples.example: Masyado ka pang lilet para umibig so focus on finishing school first.
You're too young and gay (lilet) to fall in love, so focus on finishing school first.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name of ballerina Lisa Macuja Elizalde as a playful, rhyming substitute for 'mandurukot' (pickpocket).

definitions.meaning: Isang mandurukot o magnanakaw.
A pickpocket or thief.

examples.example: Hinuli ng lespung si Jaime ang lisa macuja na tumakbo sa kalye.
The cop, Jaime, arrested the pickpocket (lisa macuja) who ran on the street.

etymology: From Spanish 'limpieza' (cleanliness). In Philippine prison slang, it refers to an inmate assigned cleaning duties.

definitions.meaning: Isang bilanggo na inatasang maglinis sa loob ng kulungan.
An inmate assigned to perform cleaning duties inside a prison.

examples.example: Kauumpisa ko pa lang isang linggo bilang limpiyesa sa bilibid, pero gusto ko na ulit lumabas at humanap ng bagong trabaho.
I just started as a prison cleaner (limpiyesa) last week in Bilibid, but I want to get out and look for a new job already.

etymology: Slang portmanteau combining 'limp' (referring to erectile dysfunction) and 'maniac' (implying excessive sexual desire, derived from nymphomaniac/satyromaniac).

definitions.meaning: Isang tao (karaniwang lalaki) na may matinding pagnanasang sekswal ngunit hindi makapagtalik dahil sa kawalan ng paninigas ng ari.
A person (typically male) who has strong sexual desires but is unable to perform sexually due to impotence (limp penis).

examples.example: Gusto mo na naman ng seks, limpomaniac ka talaga!
You want sex again, you're really a limpomaniac!

etymology: Slang term, likely a Bekimon alteration or playful corruption of the English word 'delicious'.

definitions.meaning: Masarap ang lasa.
Delicious; tasty.

examples.example: Doon tayo mag-almusal sa tapsilogan ni Mang Erning. Mura at lishie lahat ng mga luto niya.
Let's have breakfast at Mang Erning's tapsilogan. All his dishes are affordable and delicious (lishie).

etymology: Derogatory slang term using the Disney character 'The Little Mermaid' ironically to refer to a person (specifically a young gay male, per the source) perceived as unattractive.

definitions.meaning: Isang bata o binatang bakla na itinuturing na pangit.
A young gay man considered unattractive.

examples.example: Maniniwala ka ba na ang little mermaid na ito ay may milyong views sa Youtube?
Would you believe that this little mermaid (unattractive young gay guy) has a million views on Youtube?

etymology: Text speak abbreviation for the common Tagalog adverb 'lang' (only, just).

definitions.meaning: Pinaikling anyo ng salitang 'lang', na nangangahulugang 'lamang'.
Short form of the word 'lang', which means 'only' or 'just'.

examples.example: Ayos lng aq d2. Tnx sa concern, sis.
I'm just (lng) ok here. Thanks for the concern, sis.

etymology: Taglish slang from English 'low battery'. Applied literally to electronic devices and figuratively to people feeling tired or drained.

definitions.meaning: (Figuratibo) Pagod na, nanghihina, o wala nang lakas.
(Figurative) Tired, weak, or drained of energy.
(Literal) Mahina na o malapit nang maubos ang karga ng baterya (karaniwan ng cellphone o ibang gadget).
(Literal) Having low battery power (usually referring to a cellphone or other gadget).

examples.example: Lobat na ako. Gusto ko nang magpahinga.
I'm drained (lobat) already. I want to rest for a while.

etymology: Slang term using the animal 'lobster', based on the idea of enjoying the body (lobster meat) but discarding the head (face). Used derogatorily for a person with an attractive body but an unattractive face.
sangkahulugan: maganda ang katawan pero pangit ang mukha

definitions.meaning: Isang tao (karaniwan ay babae) na may maganda o kaakit-akit na katawan ngunit itinuturing na pangit ang mukha.
A person (usually a woman) who has an attractive body but is considered to have an unattractive face.

examples.example: Kahit lobster ang asawa ni Ben, sobrang bait at lambing naman.
Though Ben's wife is a lobster (great body, ugly face), she's very kind and sweet.

etymology: Internet acronym for the English phrase 'laughing out loud' or 'laugh out loud'.

definitions.meaning: Isang ekspresyon na ginagamit sa text o online chat upang ipahiwatig ang pagtawa o pagkakatuwa.
An expression used in text or online chat to indicate laughter or amusement (acronym for 'laughing out loud').

examples.example: Nakakatawa yung joke mo, lol!
Your joke was funny, lol!

etymology: Slang term created by inverting the syllables of the Tagalog word 'katulong' (helper, maid).

definitions.meaning: Isang katulong sa bahay.
A domestic helper or maid.

examples.example: Artistahin ang longkatuts n'yo, pare!
Your maid (longkatuts) looks like a movie star, man!

etymology: A Filipino breakfast dish name formed as a portmanteau of its main components: 'longganisa' (sausage) + 'sinangag' (fried rice) + 'itlog' (egg).
synonym: sausage, fried rice, and egg breakfast

definitions.meaning: Isang sikat na pagkaing pang-agahan sa Pilipinas na binubuo ng longganisa (isang uri ng Pilipinong sitsaron), sinangag (pritong kanin), at pritong itlog.
A popular Filipino breakfast meal consisting of longganisa (Filipino sausage), sinangag (garlic fried rice), and itlog (fried egg).

examples.example: Paborito kong almusal ang longsilog.
Longsilog is my favorite breakfast.

etymology: Slang term for 'pants', origin uncertain, possibly Bekimon.

definitions.meaning: Pantalon.
Pants or trousers.

examples.example: Nagsuot siya ng butas-butas na lonta sa grand ball, napakabaduy!
He wore tattered pants (lonta) during the grand ball, how lame!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name of Filipina actress Lorna Tolentino as a playful substitute for 'lips-to-lips kissing' or 'making out'.

definitions.meaning: Ang paghalik sa bibig o pag-make out.
To kiss on the lips or make out.

examples.example: Tol, 'wag naman kayong mag-lorna tolentino sa harap ni Roger. Kagagaling niya lang sa hiwalayan.
Bro, don't make out (lorna tolentino) in front of Roger. He just broke up with his girlfriend.

etymology: Slang/Bekimon phrase adopting the English song title 'Lost in Emotion' (by Lisa Lisa & Cult Jam) to playfully mean literally 'lost' (nawala).

definitions.meaning: Nawala o naligaw.
Lost or missing.

examples.example: Saan na ang wallet ko? Lost in emotion na yata!
Where's my wallet? I think it's lost in emotion (lost)!

etymology: Taglish phrase intensifying the English word 'lost' by repeating it with the Tagalog linker 'na'. Means completely or utterly lost.

definitions.meaning: Lubos na nawawala o naliligaw; walang ideya kung nasaan o ano ang gagawin.
Completely or totally lost; having no idea where one is or what to do.

examples.example: Hindi ko alam kung nasaan na tayo, lost na lost na ako!
I don't know where we are, I'm totally lost (lost na lost)!

etymology: Colloquial term, origin uncertain. Describes someone, usually a woman, who looks unkempt, frumpy, or has neglected their personal appearance.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang tao, lalo na babae, na pabaya sa sariling itsura, hindi na nag-aayos, o mukhang pagod at matanda.
Refers to a person, especially a woman, who appears unkempt, frumpy, or has neglected their personal appearance.

examples.example: Naku, mare, mag-ayos ka! Kapag losyang, baka tumingin si pare sa iba.
Oh dear, friend, fix yourself up! If you look frumpy (losyang), your husband might look for another woman!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term, likely using the name of actress Lotlot de Leon as a playful substitute for 'lost', often used in the context of losing a competition.

definitions.meaning: Natalo o hindi nagwagi, lalo na sa isang paligsahan.
Lost or defeated, especially in a competition.

examples.example: Lotlot and friends tayo ngayon. Sali na lang ulit tayo sa susunod na taon.
We lost (lotlot and friends) today. Let's just join again next year.

etymology: Slang/humorous phrase ironically borrowing the LGBTQ+ pride expression 'loud and proud' to refer to a loud, unapologetic fart.

definitions.meaning: Isang malakas at hindi ikinahihiyang utot.
A loud and unashamed fart.

examples.example: Nagalit sa akin si Mang Karding nang sabihin ko sa kaniya na kung puwede ay pumunta siya sa sulok kapag maglo-loud and proud.
Mang Karding got mad at me after I suggested to him that he should go to a corner when he's about to fart loudly (loud and proud).

etymology: From Spanish 'loca' (crazy female), reduplicated in Tagalog. Means crazy, mad, or eccentric.

definitions.meaning: Baliw, sira ang ulo, o kakatwa ang pag-uugali, karaniwang ginagamit para sa babae.
Crazy, mad, insane, or eccentric, typically used for females.

examples.example: Luka-luka talaga 'yang si Rea at walang makapipigil sa kaniya.
That girl Rea is really crazy (luka-luka) and no one can stop her.

etymology: Slang term for 'tomboy' or 'lesbian', origin uncertain, possibly Bekimon or older gay slang.

definitions.meaning: Isang tomboy o lesbiyana.
A tomboy or lesbian.

examples.example: Hindi ko alam na lulu pala siya. Mukha siyang tunay na lalaki.
I didn't know she's a tomboy/lesbian (lulu). She looks like a real man.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) verb, likely a playful elaboration related to the sound or concept of 'kulog' (thunder).

definitions.meaning: Ang pagkulog o paglikha ng malakas na dagundong ng kalangitan.
To thunder; to make the loud rumbling sound of thunder.

examples.example: Ay, grabe, Naomi, pati langit galit sa pagkanta mo. Biglang lumulungkuko at lulukuyki nang bumirit ka, eh!
Oh my, Naomi, even the sky dislikes your singing. It suddenly thundered (lulungkuko) and flashed lightning (lulukuyki) when you started hitting the high notes!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) verb, likely a playful elaboration related to 'kidlat' (lightning).

definitions.meaning: Ang pagkidlat o paglabas ng biglaang liwanag sa kalangitan.
To flash lightning.

examples.example: Ay, grabe, Naomi, pati langit galit sa pagkanta mo. Biglang lumulungkuko at lulukuyki nang bumirit ka, eh!
Oh my, Naomi, even the sky dislikes your singing. It suddenly thundered (lulungkuko) and flashed lightning (lulukuyki) when you started hitting the high notes!

etymology: Slang verb, likely Bekimon, related to 'lapa' (devour) or 'lafang' (eat).

definitions.meaning: Kumain, madalas nang may gana o marami.
To eat, often heartily or in large amounts.

examples.example: Ang sarap ng luto mo, napapalapang ako!
Your cooking is delicious, it makes me want to devour (lumapang) it!

etymology: Tagalog idiom, literally 'my eyebrow flew'. Expresses surprise, disbelief, or skepticism.

definitions.meaning: Isang idyoma na nagpapahayag ng pagkagulat, pagdududa, o hindi paniniwala sa narinig o nakita.
An idiom expressing surprise, disbelief, or skepticism about something heard or seen (similar to 'raised my eyebrows').

examples.example: Magpapatayo ka ng ganyang kalaking bahay? Naku, lumipad ang kilay ko!
You're saying you're going to build a house that big? Oh my, my eyebrows flew (lumipad ang kilay ko / I was surprised/skeptical)!

etymology: Vulgar slang term using the name of the food 'lumpia' (spring roll) metaphorically for masturbation performed by a massage therapist on a client, typically an illicit extra service.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagsasalsal o pagbibigay ng 'hand job' ng isang masahista sa kanyang kliyente (karaniwan ay lalaki).
The act of a massage therapist masturbating a client (usually male); giving a hand job.

examples.example: Naranasan mo na bang ilumpia ng taong 'di mo naman kilala?
Have you ever experienced being given a hand job (ilumpia) by a stranger?

etymology: Figurative slang use of standard Tagalog 'luto' (cooked), implying the outcome of a game, election, or contest was pre-arranged or rigged.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa resulta ng isang laro, eleksyon, o kompetisyon na pinaniniwalaang dinaya, inayos, o pinagpasyahan na bago pa man ito matapos.
Refers to the outcome of a game, election, or competition believed to be cheated, fixed, or predetermined.

examples.example: Magprotesta tayo. Maliwanag na luto ang resulta ng laban!
Let's protest. The results of the match are clearly rigged (luto)!

etymology: Idiomatic phrase combining 'luto' (cooked/rigged) and 'Makaw' (Macau). Refers to blatant or large-scale rigging or manipulation of results, especially in elections or games.

definitions.meaning: Malawakang pandaraya o manipulasyon sa resulta ng isang laro, eleksyon, o kompetisyon.
Blatant or large-scale cheating or manipulation of the results of a game, election, or competition.

examples.example: Ang pagkapanalo nila sa halalan ay halatang lutong makaw!
Their victory in the election was obviously due to blatant rigging (lutong makaw)!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name from the telenovela 'Luz Clarita' as a playful, rhyming substitute for 'lost' or 'loser', especially in contests.

definitions.meaning: Natalo o hindi nanalo sa isang kompetisyon o paligsahan.
Lost or defeated in a competition or contest.

examples.example: Luz clarita ang beauty ko sa pageant!
My beauty lost (luz clarita) in the pageant!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term, likely using a person's name playfully associated with 'lost' and perhaps 'sorry' (lalu ~ luoy?).

definitions.meaning: Nawala (ang isang bagay) o natalo (sa isang laro/kompetisyon), madalas may kasamang paghihinayang.
Lost (an item) or defeated (in a game/competition), often with a sense of regret or being sorry.

examples.example: Puwede mo ba akong tulungan hanapin ang kuwintas ko? Lucila lalu na naman.
Can you help me find my necklace? It's lost (lucila lalu) again.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name of actress Lucita Soriano as a playful substitute for 'lost and sorry'.

definitions.meaning: Natalo o nawalan at kasabay nito ay nanghihinayang o nagsisisi.
Lost or defeated, coupled with a feeling of being sorry or regretful.

examples.example: Nakalimutan kong i-save ang file ko bago nag-brownout, lucita soriano tuloy!
I forgot to save my file before the brownout, now it's lost and I'm sorry (lucita soriano)!

etymology: Euphemistic phrase popularized in media (e.g., game shows) referring to a live-in partner.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na kinakasama sa iisang bahay bilang mag-asawa ngunit hindi opisyal na kasal.
A person with whom one lives together as a couple but is not officially married; a live-in partner.

examples.example: Pitong taon na kaming magkasama ng aking lucky home partner.
My lucky home partner and I have been living together for seven years.

etymology: Acronym from English 'man to man', commonly used online and in LGBTQ+ contexts to refer specifically to sexual acts or relationships between men.
synonym: MSM (men who have sex with men)

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa sekswal na gawain o relasyon sa pagitan ng dalawang lalaki.
Refers to sexual activity or relationships between two men.

examples.example: Hindi pa ako nakakaranas ng m2m at malamang ay hindi kailanman.
I've never had m2m (male-to-male sex) before, and most likely never will.

etymology: Colloquial shortening of the Tagalog phrase 'Malay ko' (I don't know).

definitions.meaning: Isang ekspresyon na nangangahulugang 'hindi ko alam' o 'ewan'.
An expression meaning 'I don't know'.

examples.example: Tinanong niya kung saan ako pupunta, sagot ko 'Ma!'
He asked where I was going, I answered 'Ma! (I don't know!)'

etymology: Taglish adjective formed with the Tagalog prefix 'ma-' (having the quality of) + English 'articles'. Implies being overly concerned with details, fussy, or pretentious.

definitions.meaning: Sobrang mapili, maselan, o maarte sa mga bagay-bagay; mapagkunwari.
Overly picky, fussy, finicky, or pretentious.

examples.example: Kung magsalita ang mga kabataan ngayon ay napaka-ma-articles.
Young people nowadays speak in such a ma-articles (fussy/pretentious) way.

etymology: Colloquial portmanteau/blend of 'malay' (awareness, often in 'malay ko' - I don't know) and 'pakialam' (care, concern). Used negatively ('walang ma-at-pa') to express complete indifference.

definitions.meaning: Pariralang ginagamit, karaniwan sa anyong negatibo ('walang ma-at-pa'), upang ipahayag ang kawalan ng kaalaman at pakialam; katumbas ng 'I don't know and I don't care'.
Phrase typically used in the negative ('walang ma-at-pa') to express a complete lack of knowledge and care; equivalent to 'I don't know and I don't care'.

examples.example: Wala akong ma-at-pa kung ano man ang mangyari kay Vito. Wala na kaming kinalaman sa isa't isa.
I don't know and don't care (Wala akong ma-at-pa) whatever happens to Vito. We are no longer involved with each other.

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon or gay slang, origin uncertain. Means having a high sex drive.

definitions.meaning: Malibog o may mataas na pagnanasang sekswal.
Having a high sex drive; horny or lustful.

examples.example: Huwag mo ngang pagbibigyan lagi 'yang si Gino, masyadong ma-el!
Don't always give in to Gino, he's too ma-el (horny/oversexed)!

etymology: Tagalog idiom literally meaning 'foot/feet are heavy'. Figuratively describes someone who is lazy or slow to act.

definitions.meaning: Tamad kumilos, mabagal gumawa, o ayaw utusan.
Lazy, slow to move or act, or reluctant to do tasks.

examples.example: Hirap ang aabutin ni Lotti. Ang asawa niyang si Luis ay mabigat ang paa.
Lotti will face hardship. Her husband, Luis, is lazy (mabigat ang paa).

etymology: Tagalog idiom literally meaning 'heavy on the pocket'. Figuratively describes something as expensive.

definitions.meaning: Mahal ang presyo o nangangailangan ng malaking gastos.
Expensive or costly.

examples.example: Ang taas ng presyo ng gasolina, mabigat sa bulsa!
The fuel prices are too high, it's expensive (mabigat sa bulsa)!

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon, possibly related to English 'beyond' (implying beyond beautiful) or a playful elaboration of 'maganda'.

definitions.meaning: Maganda o kaakit-akit.
Beautiful or attractive.

examples.example: Mabyonda pa rin siya kahit may edad na.
She's still beautiful (mabyonda) even though she's aged.

etymology: Slang term referencing General Douglas MacArthur's quote 'I shall return'. Humorously applied to feces that resurface in the toilet bowl after flushing.

definitions.meaning: Dumi ng tao na lumulutang at bumabalik sa ibabaw ng tubig sa inidoro kahit ilang beses nang i-flush.
Feces that float and return to the surface of the toilet bowl even after being flushed several times.

examples.example: Pang-apat na flush ko na pero macarthur pa rin ang poo poo ko!
I've flushed four times already but my poop is still a macarthur (keeps returning)!

etymology: Slang term for 'tomboy' or 'lesbian', possibly an ironic play on 'macho' or influenced by Spanish 'macha'.

definitions.meaning: Isang tomboy o lesbiyana.
A tomboy or lesbian.

examples.example: Tingnan mo kung gaano kasaya ang macha na iyon kasama ang kaniyang girlfriend!
Wow, look how happy that lesbian/tomboy (macha) looks with her girlfriend!

etymology: From Spanish 'macho' (male). Widely used in Tagalog to mean manly, masculine, often implying physical strength or virility.

definitions.meaning: Nagpapakita ng katangian ng tunay na lalaki, tulad ng pagiging malakas, matipuno, o matapang.
Exhibiting traditional masculine qualities, such as strength, virility, or muscularity; manly.

examples.example: Nagtilian ang mga fangirls ni Lucio nang i-flex niya ang macho niyang mga braso.
Lucio's fangirls screamed when he flexed his macho (manly/muscular) arms.

etymology: Slang portmanteau combining 'macho' and 'masunurin' (obedient). Humorously or derogatorily refers to a man perceived as overly submissive to his wife.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang lalaki na labis na masunurin o sunud-sunuran sa kanyang asawa, kabaligtaran ng inaasahang pagiging 'macho'.
Refers to a man who is overly obedient or submissive to his wife, often used humorously or derogatorily; henpecked.

examples.example: Naniniwala ako sa kasabihang 'happy wife, happy life,' kaya naman machunurin ako kay Magda.
I believe in the saying 'happy wife means a happy life.' That's why I'm machunurin (obedient/submissive) to Magda.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term, likely combining 'Madam' with a name (Shuli?) or wordplay associated with intelligence.

definitions.meaning: Matalino o marunong.
Intelligent or smart.

examples.example: Ate, tulungan mo nga ako sa takdang aralin ko sa Algebra. Alam kong madam shuli ka lalo na pagdating sa numero.
Ate, please help me with my Algebra assignment. I know you're madam shuli (very smart) especially when it comes to numbers.

etymology: Slang adaptation and phonetic respelling of the English vulgarism 'motherfucker'.

definitions.meaning: Isang bulgar na pagmumura na katumbas ng 'motherfucker' sa Ingles, ginagamit upang ipahayag ang matinding galit o paghamak.
A vulgar curse word equivalent to 'motherfucker', used to express extreme anger or contempt.

examples.example: Hoy! Madapaka! Ibalik mo ang pera ko!
Hey! Motherfucker (Madapaka)! Give my money back!

etymology: Figurative slang use of standard Tagalog 'madugo' (bloody). Can mean difficult/grueling or expensive.

definitions.meaning: Mahirap, nakakapagod, o nangangailangan ng matinding pagsisikap.
Difficult, grueling, tough, or requiring great effort.
Mahal o mataas ang presyo; magastos.
Expensive or costly.

examples.example: Madugo ang exam natin sa Math kanina!
Our Math exam earlier was really difficult (madugo)!
Gusto ko sana 'yung sapatos na 'yun kaso madugo ang presyo.
I wanted those shoes, but the price is expensive (madugo).

etymology: Slang term for 'mother', origin uncertain, possibly Bekimon or regional slang.

definitions.meaning: Ina o nanay.
Mother.

examples.example: Umuwi ka. Hinahanap ka ng maduk mo.
Go home. Your mother (maduk) is looking for you.

etymology: Slang term for 'rich', origin uncertain, possibly Bekimon or gay slang.

definitions.meaning: Mayaman o maraming pera.
Rich or wealthy.

examples.example: May lima siyang kotse at tatlong rest houses, madya talaga!
She has five cars and three rest houses, truly rich (madya) indeed!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) phrase using the name of filmmaker Nick Deocampo as a playful, rhyming substitute for 'magkano' (how much?).

definitions.meaning: Isang paraan ng pagtatanong kung magkano ang halaga ng isang bagay.
A slang way of asking 'how much?' something costs.

examples.example: Magka-nick ocampo ang gintong singsing na 'yan?
How much (Magka-nick ocampo) is that gold ring?

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) elaboration of the Tagalog question word 'magkano' (how much?), adding the playful suffix '-etch'.

definitions.meaning: Isang paraan ng pagtatanong kung magkano ang halaga; bersyong bekimon ng 'magkano'.
A slang way of asking 'how much?'; Bekimon version of 'magkano'.

examples.example: Tinatanong ni Tara kung magkanetch ang sapatos mo, dzai.
Tara is asking how much (magkanetch) your shoes are, girl.

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon or gay slang, punning on the historical term 'Magna Carta' and its phonetic similarity to 'magnanakaw' (thief).

definitions.meaning: Isang magnanakaw o mandarambong, lalo na ang nagnanakaw ng malaking halaga.
A thief or plunderer, especially one who steals large amounts.

examples.example: Hindi ba't nahatulan siyang magna carta? Kailan ba siya makakulong?
Isn't she a convicted plunderer (magna carta)? When will she ever be imprisoned?

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon or gay slang, punning on the academic honor 'magna cum laude' and its phonetic similarity to 'magnanakaw' (thief).

definitions.meaning: Isang magnanakaw, lalo na kung tumutukoy sa mga tiwaling politiko o opisyal.
A thief, especially referring to corrupt politicians or officials.

examples.example: Sana hindi manalo ang mga magna cum laude sa eleksiyon.
I hope the thieves (magna cum laudes) do not win in the election.

etymology: From Spanish 'majadero/a' (annoying person, pest). In Tagalog, typically refers to a meddlesome, gossipy, or overly talkative woman.

definitions.meaning: Isang babaeng tsismosa, pakialamera, o sobrang madaldal at mahilig makialam sa buhay ng iba.
A gossipy, meddlesome, or overly talkative woman who interferes in others' affairs; a busybody.

examples.example: Iniiwasan kong magkuwento ng personal na bagay kay Sabel dahil siya ang pinuno ng mga mahadera rito sa aming barangay.
I avoid telling personal stories to Sabel because she is the leader of all the gossipmongers (mahaderas) here in our barangay.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name of actress Mahalia Mendez as a playful substitute for 'mahal' (expensive).

definitions.meaning: Mahal o mataas ang presyo.
Expensive or costly.

examples.example: Ang mahalia mendez naman pala ng singsing na 'yan! Nakakaloka!
That ring is so expensive (mahalia mendez)! Shocking!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the English word 'mahogany' as a substitute for 'mabaho' (foul-smelling), based on sound similarity.

definitions.meaning: Mabaho o may masamang amoy.
Foul-smelling or stinky.

examples.example: Dex, ang mahogany mo na! Hindi masamang maligo.
Dex, you're stinky (mahogany)! Taking a bath isn't a bad thing to do, man.

etymology: Colloquial pronunciation or form of the English word 'maid'.

definitions.meaning: Isang katulong sa bahay.
A domestic helper; a maid.

examples.example: Hindi mo ako maida! Maghanap ka ng magluluto at maglilinis para sa 'yo.
I'm not your maid (maida)! Find someone who'll cook and clean for you.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term, likely using the name of actress Maita Gonzales. Refers to a gay man pretending to be merely effeminate or bisexual ('silahis') to hide his true orientation.

definitions.meaning: Isang bakla na nagpapanggap na silahis (bisexual o effeminate lamang) upang itago ang kanyang tunay na sekswalidad.
A gay man pretending to be only effeminate or bisexual ('silahis') to hide his true sexuality; a closet queen.

examples.example: Nagkukunwari lang na maita gonzales si Ruthsen para mapalapit siya kay Mike.
Ruthsen is just pretending to be a maita gonzales (closeted/pretending) so that he could be close to Mike.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term punning on 'mahirap' (poor) and the name of former president Joseph 'Erap' Estrada, known for his slogan 'Erap para sa Mahirap' (Erap for the Poor).

definitions.meaning: Mahirap o walang pera.
Poor or lacking money.

examples.example: Kahit majerap estrada kami, masaya pa rin ang pamilya namin.
Even though we are poor (majerap estrada), our family is still happy.

etymology: Slang pronunciation/spelling of 'mainit' (hot), often associated with Bekimon or gay slang.

definitions.meaning: Mainit (temperatura).
Hot (temperature).

examples.example: Ayoko ng masikip. Ayoko ng majinit! Ayoko ng walang tubig!
I don't like crowded places. I don't like it hot (majinit)! I don't want no water!

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon or gay slang, meaning 'fat' or 'big'. Possibly related to 'joba' or 'jubis'.

definitions.meaning: Malaki o mataba (tao o bagay).
Big or fat (person or thing).

examples.example: Huwag mo akong tawaging majuba. Chubby lang ako!
Don't call me fat (majuba). I'm just chubby!

etymology: Slang expression, likely Bekimon/gay slang, origin uncertain. 'Juso' might playfully refer to the mouth. Means fond of spreading gossip or intrigue.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang tao na mahilig gumawa at magkalat ng tsismis o intriga.
Refers to a person who likes to create and spread gossip or intrigue; a gossipmonger.

examples.example: Iyang si Tetet ay majulis ang juso, maniwala ka.
Believe it or not, Tetet is a real gossipmonger (majulis ang juso)!

etymology: Tagalog slang expression literally meaning 'brief-dropping'. Used hyperbolically to describe a woman as extremely beautiful or sexually attractive.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyon na tumutukoy sa isang babae na sobrang ganda o kaakit-akit.
An expression describing a woman who is exceedingly beautiful or attractive.

examples.example: Wow, makalaglag-brip ang ganda ng bagong kapitbahay natin!
Wow, our new neighbor is stunningly beautiful (makalaglag-brip)!

etymology: Tagalog slang expression literally meaning 'panty-dropping'. Counterpart to 'makalaglag-brip', used hyperbolically to describe a man as extremely handsome or sexually attractive.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyon na tumutukoy sa isang lalaki na sobrang guwapo o kaakit-akit.
An expression describing a man who is exceedingly handsome or attractive.

examples.example: Artista ba 'yun? Makalaglag-panti ang kaguwapuhan!
Is he an actor? He's drop-dead gorgeous (makalaglag-panti)!

etymology: Tagalog idiom literally meaning 'hand is itchy'. Figuratively means being prone to stealing or having sticky fingers.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang tao na may tendensiyang magnakaw o mandukot.
Refers to a person who is prone to stealing or pickpocketing; light-fingered.

examples.example: Mag-ingat ka sa kasama mo, balita ko makati ang kamay niyan.
Be careful with your companion, I heard they have sticky fingers (makati ang kamay).

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon, combining 'ma-' prefix with 'kiyeme/kyeme' (fuss, pretense, unnecessary actions/talk).

definitions.meaning: Sobrang madaldal o masalita, madalas maraming sinasabing hindi kailangan o may kasamang kaartehan.
Overly talkative or verbose, often with unnecessary details or fussiness.

examples.example: Late na natapos ang check-up kasi masyadong makiyeme ang doktor ni Cara.
The check-up ended late because Cara's doctor is so talkative/long-winded (makiyeme).

etymology: Figurative slang use of standard Tagalog 'makunat' (tough, leathery, often for food) to mean stingy or tightfisted with money.

definitions.meaning: Kuripot o hindi galante sa paggastos ng pera.
Stingy or ungenerous with money; tightfisted.

examples.example: Makunat talaga 'yan. Hindi nagbabayad sa mga date namin.
He is so stingy (makunat). He never paid for our dates.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) elaboration of 'magkano' (how much?), similar to 'magkanetch'.

definitions.meaning: Isang paraan ng pagtatanong kung magkano ang halaga ng isang bagay.
A slang way of asking 'how much?' something costs.

examples.example: Makyonakels ang bagong lipstick mo, mamsh?
How much (Makyonakels) is your new lipstick, mamsh?

etymology: Tagalog idiom literally meaning 'big head'. Figuratively refers to being arrogant, conceited, or letting success get to one's head.

definitions.meaning: Mayabang o mapagmataas, lalo na dahil sa tagumpay o papuri.
Arrogant or conceited, especially due to success or praise; big-headed.

examples.example: Simula nang sumikat siya, lumaki na ang ulo niya.
Since he became famous, he's become big-headed (lumaki na ang ulo niya).

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) phrase using Philippine place names (Malaybalay City, Bukidnon Province) as a playful, rhyming substitute for 'Malay ko' (I don't know).

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyon na nangangahulugang 'Hindi ko alam' o 'Malay ko'.
An expression meaning 'I don't know'.

examples.example: Tinatanong mo ako kung papasa ka? Malaybalay bukidnon!
You're asking me if you'll pass? I don't know (Malaybalay bukidnon)!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) phrase using country names as puns for 'Malay ko' (I don't know) and 'Paki ko' (short for 'Pakialam ko' - I don't care).
synonym: I don't know, I don't care

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyon na nagpapahayag ng kawalan ng kaalaman at kawalan ng pakialam; katumbas ng 'Malay ko, paki ko'.
An expression indicating lack of knowledge and lack of concern; equivalent to 'I don't know, and I don't care'.

examples.example: Kung mag-break man sila, Malaysia at Pakistan!
If they break up, I don't know and I don't care (Malaysia at Pakistan)!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) phrase using country names, likely playing on 'Malay ko sa'yo, 'jan!' (I don't know about you, there!). Expresses dismissal or indifference.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyong nagpapahayag ng pagwawalang-bahala o hindi pag-alam tungkol sa sitwasyon ng iba; katumbas ng 'Malay ko sa'yo!' o 'Ewan ko sa'yo!'.
An expression of dismissal, indifference, or not knowing about someone else's situation; equivalent to 'I don't know about you!' or 'Whatever!'.

examples.example: Gusto mong sumama? Malaysia India Japan, bahala ka!
You want to come along? Whatever (Malaysia India Japan), do as you please!

etymology: From Spanish 'maldita' (feminine form of 'maldito' - cursed, wicked). In Tagalog, commonly means spiteful, bratty, snobbish, or ill-tempered, usually referring to a female.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang babae na masama ang ugali, mataray, suplada, o mapanira.
Refers to a female who is spiteful, bratty, snobbish, mean, or ill-tempered.

examples.example: Ayokong makipagkaibigan sa malditang babaeng 'yan. Grrr!
I don't want to be friends with that bitchy/spiteful (maldita) woman. Grrr!

etymology: Bekimon/gay slang phrase combining 'maloloko' (will go crazy) and 'aki' (variant of 'ako' - I). Means 'I will go crazy'.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyon na nagpapahiwatig ng matinding pagkabaliw, pagka-inis, o pagka-frustrate.
An expression indicating extreme frustration, annoyance, or exasperation, meaning 'I'll go crazy' or 'It's driving me crazy'.

examples.example: Maloloki aki sa boyfriend ko. Napakarami niyang drama sa buhay!
I'll go crazy (Maloloki aki) because of my boyfriend. He has so many issues in life!

etymology: Tagalog idiom literally meaning 'screw is loose'. Figuratively means crazy, eccentric, or mentally unsound.

definitions.meaning: Sira ang ulo, luko-luko, o wala sa tamang pag-iisip.
Crazy, eccentric, or not mentally sound; having 'a screw loose'.

examples.example: Mukhang maluwag ang turnilyo niyang si Mang Karding.
That Mang Karding seems to have a screw loose (maluwag ang turnilyo).

etymology: Slang term combining 'Mama' (term for an older woman, often used for a madam) and 'Monchang' (a name or derived term). Refers to an older female pimp.

definitions.meaning: Isang matandang babaeng bugaw o tagapamahala ng mga babaeng bayaran.
An older female pimp or madam who manages prostitutes.

examples.example: Kung si Mamita Tina pa rin ang mama monchang natin dito, hindi ganito kalaki ang kaltas sa kita natin.
If Mamita Tina was still our old madam (mama monchang) here, then the deduction from our earnings would not be as big as now.

etymology: Slang term combining 'Mama' (madam/pimp) and 'sang' (origin unclear). Variant of Mamasan.

definitions.meaning: Isang babaeng bugaw o tagapamahala ng mga babaeng bayaran.
A female pimp or madam who manages prostitutes.

examples.example: Itanong mo kay Mama Sang kung may bago silang recruit.
Ask the madam (Mama Sang) if they have new recruits.

etymology: Slang term for alcoholic drinks, possibly derived from baby talk for drinking ('inom' -> 'nomnom' -> 'mamam').

definitions.meaning: Inuming nakalalasing; alak.
Alcoholic drink(s).

examples.example: Sinabi ni Jake sa akin na mga imported na mamam ang iinumin natin sa kaarawan niya.
Jake told me that we would drink imported booze (mamam) on his birthday.

etymology: Affectionate/familiar term for 'mother', influenced by English 'Mommy'.

definitions.meaning: Isang mapagmahal o pamilyar na tawag sa ina o nanay.
An affectionate or familiar term for mother.

examples.example: Miss ko na si Mamie.
I miss my Mommy (Mamie).

etymology: Term of address/reference for an older sister or older woman, derived from Ilocano and other Philippine languages. Can be respectful or imply old-fashionedness.

definitions.meaning: Magalang na tawag sa nakatatandang kapatid na babae o sa mas matandang babae.
A respectful term for an older sister or an older woman.
(Negatibo) Isang babae na itinuturing na makaluma o baduy sa pananamit o kilos.
(Negative) A woman considered old-fashioned or frumpy in dress or manner.

examples.example: Manang, magkano po ito?
Ma'am (Manang), how much is this?
Ayaw niyang isuot 'yan kasi pang-manang daw.
She doesn't want to wear that because she says it's for old-fashioned women (pang-manang).

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, possibly related to 'manang' or 'nanay'.

definitions.meaning: Isang babae (pangkalahatan).
A woman (general).
Ina o nanay.
Mother.

examples.example: Sino 'yung manash na kasama mo kanina?
Who was that woman (manash) with you earlier?
Pupunta ako sa manash ko mamaya.
I'm going to my mother's (manash) place later.

etymology: Slang shortening of the Tagalog word 'mandurukot' (pickpocket).

definitions.meaning: Isang mandurukot.
A pickpocket.

examples.example: Nakuha ng mando 'yung wallet niya kanina sa Quiapo.
A pickpocket (mando) snatched her wallet awhile ago in Quiapo.

etymology: Standard Tagalog word derived from 'dugas' (cheating, trickery).

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na nandadaya, nanlilinlang, o nanloloko ng kapwa, lalo na para sa sariling kapakinabangan.
A person who cheats, swindles, or deceives others, especially for personal gain; a cheater or swindler.

examples.example: May nabiktima na naman si Edong mandurugas.
That swindler Edong (Edong mandurugas) has a new victim!

etymology: Slang phrase, likely Bekimon/gay slang. 'Mang-' is a verb prefix, 'keks' possibly related to 'cake' (implying something desirable) or 'look'. Refers to cruising or looking for men.

definitions.meaning: Ang paglabas o pag-ikot upang maghanap ng makakatalik o makakarelasyong lalaki; pagku-cruise.
To go out cruising or looking for male partners (sexual or romantic).

examples.example: Tara na at mang keks tayo sa Ali Mall mga beshie!
Let's go and cruise for guys (mang keks) at Ali Mall, besties!

etymology: Vulgar slang using the Tagalog word 'mani' (peanut) metaphorically for the clitoris.

definitions.meaning: Bulgar na tawag sa tinggil o klitoris.
Vulgar slang term for the clitoris.

examples.example: Fake yata ang sex change doctor ko. Tiningnan ko, walang mani!
I think my sex change doctor is fake. When I looked at what he did, I found no clitoris (mani)!

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name of actress Manilyn Reynes as a playful substitute for 'money'.

definitions.meaning: Pera.
Money.

examples.example: Walang-wala ako. Puwede bang humiram ng manilyn reynes?
I'm broke. May I borrow some money (manilyn reynes)?

etymology: Slang verb using the name of boxer Manny Pacquiao, likely playing on the term 'pakyaw' (wholesale buyout) which sounds similar, or referencing his ability to buy things wholesale.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagbili ng lahat ng paninda o produkto nang sabay-sabay; pakyawin.
To buy all the goods or products at once; to buy wholesale or buy out.

examples.example: Boss, manny pacquiao mo na ang mga paninda ko para makauwi na ako.
Boss, please buy out (manny pacquiao) all my goods so I can go home already. I'll give you a big discount.

etymology: Term of address/reference from Ilocano and other Philippine languages for an older brother or older man, used respectfully.

definitions.meaning: Magalang na tawag sa nakatatandang kapatid na lalaki o sa mas matandang lalaki.
A respectful term for an older brother or an older man.

examples.example: Kapag tinawag kang manong, ibig sabihin matanda ka na raw o iginagalang ka.
When someone calls you manong, it means you're considered old or they respect you.

etymology: Vulgar slang term for penis, origin uncertain.

definitions.meaning: Bulgar na tawag sa ari ng lalaki.
Vulgar slang term for penis.

examples.example: Takpan mo nga yang manoy mo!
Cover your penis (manoy)!

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon, playing on 'masarap' (delicious).

definitions.meaning: Masarap ang lasa.
Delicious; tasty.

examples.example: Ang manyorap ng luto mong adobo!
The adobo you cooked is so delicious (manyorap)!

etymology: Tagalog slang from 'papel' (paper; role) + 'ma-'. Implies someone who takes on unnecessary roles, tries to grab the spotlight, or interferes.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang tao na mahilig sumingit o makialam sa hindi naman niya dapat gawain o usapan, madalas upang mapansin o magpasikat.
Refers to someone who butts into situations or takes on roles unnecessarily, often to get attention or show off; officious or an attention seeker.

examples.example: Mapapel na naman si kapitan dahil malapit na ang eleksiyon.
Our barangay captain is being an attention seeker (mapapel) again because the election is near.

etymology: Colloquial shortening/variant of 'Mare' (term for a close female friend, from 'kumare'), sometimes extended to mean 'girlfriend'.

definitions.meaning: Isang malapit na kaibigang babae.
A close female friend.
Kasintahan o nobya.
Girlfriend.

examples.example: Kumusta ka na, Marce? Long time no see!
How are you, Marce (friend)? Long time no see!
Pakilala ko sa iyo, si Ana, ang marce ko.
Let me introduce you to Ana, my girlfriend (marce).

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, combining 'mare' (female friend term) with 'gay' or a playful suffix. Used for 'girlfriend'.

definitions.meaning: Kasintahang babae o nobya.
Girlfriend.

examples.example: Natuto akong magluto dahil sa marenggay kong kusinera.
I learned to cook because of my girlfriend (marenggay) who is also a chef.

etymology: Euphemistic slang phrase combining 'Maria' (a common female name) and 'palad' (palm), personifying the hand performing masturbation.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagsasalsal o masturbasyon.
To masturbate.

examples.example: Madalas daw mag-mariang palad ang mga binata.
They say young men often masturbate (mag-mariang palad).

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, playing on 'marine' (related to the sea) or the name 'Marina' to refer to fish dishes.

definitions.meaning: Ulam o putahe na ang pangunahing sangkap ay isda o pagkaing-dagat.
A dish whose main ingredient is fish or seafood.

examples.example: Mga marina ang paboritong pagkain ng aking kumare.
My friend's favorite foods are fish dishes (marina).

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name 'Martha' as a playful substitute for 'money'.

definitions.meaning: Pera.
Money.

examples.example: Pahiram naman ng martha. Balik ko bukas.
Please lend me some money (martha). I'll return it tomorrow.

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, using a person's name as a pun for 'maraming an-an' (has lots of tinea versicolor, a common fungal skin infection).

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na maraming an-an (tinea versicolor) sa balat.
A person with widespread tinea versicolor (a common fungal skin infection causing discolored patches).

examples.example: Huwag kang didikit diyan, baka mahawa ka sa pagka-mary anne murphy niya.
Don't get too close, you might catch his skin condition (mary anne murphy / tinea versicolor).

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, using a person's name (possibly Mary Ong, witness in a scandal). Meaning to stare blankly or zone out.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagtitig sa kawalan o pagiging tulala.
To stare blankly into space or zone out.

examples.example: Anong drama mo, ateng? Kanina ka pa nagme-mary ong diyan sa may bintana?
What's your problem, girl? You have been staring blankly (mary ong) near the window for a long time already.

etymology: Common English slang/code name ('Mary Jane') for marijuana, adopted into Tagalog slang.

definitions.meaning: Marihuwana.
Marijuana.

examples.example: Mahilig siyang gumamit ng maryjane.
He likes using marijuana (maryjane).

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, variation of 'matanda' (old).

definitions.meaning: Matanda.
Old or elderly.

examples.example: Respetuhin mo siya kahit mashonda na.
Respect him even though he's already old (mashonda).

etymology: Slang phrase combining 'mashonda' (slang for old) and English 'dressing' (style of dress).

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa pagiging makaluma o wala na sa uso ng istilo ng pananamit.
Refers to having an old-fashioned or outdated style of dress.

examples.example: In fairness, guwapo pa rin si Ralph kahit mashonda ang dressing niya.
In fairness, Ralph is still handsome though his style of dress is old-fashioned (mashonda ang dressing).

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, meaning 'fat'. Possibly related to 'majuba'.

definitions.meaning: Mataba.
Fat.

examples.example: Ang cute ng pusa mong mashuba!
Your fat (mashuba) cat is cute!

etymology: Slang phrase combining 'maski' (even if/any) and 'paps' (uncertain origin, possibly from 'papasok-pasok' or 'whatever'). Means 'anything goes', 'freestyle', or 'haphazardly'.

definitions.meaning: Sa paraang kahit ano na lang o walang sinusunod na partikular na hakbang o istilo, lalo na sa pagsasayaw.
In an 'anything goes' manner, haphazardly, or without following specific steps or style; freestyle, especially in dancing.

examples.example: Huwag ka nang mahiya. Sumayaw ka nang maski paps sa dance floor!
Don't be shy. You can just dance freestyle (maski paps) on the dance floor!

etymology: Standard Tagalog word meaning well-built, sturdy, handsome, elegant, or robust.

definitions.meaning: May magandang pangangatawan; malakas at matatag; makisig o elegante.
Having a good physique; well-built, strong, and sturdy; handsome or elegant.

examples.example: Hindi nakapagtataka na matikas si Gardo dahil madalas siya sa gym.
No wonder Gardo is well-built (matikas) because he goes to the gym often.

etymology: Slang term for 'thief', origin uncertain, possibly regional or Bekimon/gay slang.

definitions.meaning: Isang magnanakaw.
A thief.

examples.example: Kinuha ni Raina ang bracelet. Matod siya!
Raina stole the bracelet. She is a thief (matod)!

etymology: Figurative slang use of standard Tagalog 'matulis' (sharp, pointed). Implies being skilled or smooth with women; a womanizer.

definitions.meaning: Magaling o sanay sa panliligaw o pagpapa-ibig ng babae; babaero.
Skilled or adept at wooing women; a womanizer or smooth operator.

examples.example: Baon sa utang si Carlos dahil siya ay matulis at sugalero.
Carlos is buried in debt because he is a womanizer (matulis) and a gambler.

etymology: Slang term for a female thief, possibly related to 'tuso' (sly) or 'matod'. The '-a' ending typically denotes feminine gender.

definitions.meaning: Isang babaeng magnanakaw o mandurukot.
A female thief or pickpocket.

examples.example: Mag-ingat kayo. May matuserang papalapit sa 'tin!
Look out. There's a female thief (matusera) coming towards us!

etymology: Slang verb, origin uncertain, possibly related to 'giyera/guerra' (war) or 'wala'. Means to go wild, run amok, or cause a scene.

definitions.meaning: Ang magwala, mag-amok, o lumikha ng gulo o iskandalo, karaniwan dahil sa galit o pagka-frustrate.
To run amok, go wild, or cause a disturbance or scene, usually out of anger or frustration.

examples.example: May K akong mawarta kapag nakita kong may kasamang ibang babae ang mister ko!
I have the right to go wild (mawarta) if I see my husband with another woman!

etymology: Tagalog idiom literally meaning 'has a pocket in the skin'. Figuratively means prone to stealing.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang tao na may tendensiyang magnakaw o mandukot.
Refers to a person who is prone to stealing or pickpocketing; light-fingered.

examples.example: Hindi ko siya pinagkakatiwalaan ng pera dahil may bulsa siya sa balat.
I don't trust him with money because he's prone to stealing (may bulsa siya sa balat).

etymology: Slang expression abbreviating 'May karapatan' (Has the right), where 'K' stands for 'karapatan'.

definitions.meaning: May karapatan o nasa katwiran na gawin o sabihin ang isang bagay.
Having the right or justification to do or say something.

examples.example: May K siyang magtaray, nasa katwiran naman, eh.
She has the right (May K) to be snarky, she's justified after all.

etymology: Tagalog idiom, literally 'has a touch/scrape' (implying the mind is slightly damaged). Figuratively means slightly crazy, eccentric, or mentally unstable.

definitions.meaning: Medyo sira ang ulo, luko-luko, o kakatwa ang pag-iisip o kilos.
Slightly crazy, eccentric, or mentally unstable; 'touched in the head'.

examples.example: Ayaw niya na naman makipag-talking sa akin. Mukhang may sayad na naman siya.
She doesn't want to talk to me again. I think she's acting crazy (may sayad) again.

etymology: Tagalog idiom literally meaning 'has soy sauce'. Figuratively refers to being moody, temperamental, or unpredictable.

definitions.meaning: Sumpungin, madaling magbago ang mood, o iritable.
Moody, temperamental, easily irritated, or unpredictable.

examples.example: Ayaw niya na naman makausap ako. Mukhang may toyo na naman siya.
She doesn't want to talk to me again. I think she's moody (may toyo) again.

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, using the makeup brand name 'Maybelline' and its tagline ('Maybe she's born with it...') ironically to refer to a gay man who tries to hide his sexuality.

definitions.meaning: Isang bakla na ayaw umamin o itinatago ang kanyang pagiging bakla kahit halata na.
A gay man who denies or hides his homosexuality despite it being obvious.

examples.example: Bakla si Jerry, pero nananatili siyang maybeline para hindi matanggal sa pagiging guro.
Jerry is gay, but he stays closeted (maybeline) to avoid losing his teaching job.

etymology: Slang phrase combining 'mayda' (slang for maid) and 'fatale' (from French 'femme fatale'), implying a maid who is surprisingly effective or capable.

definitions.meaning: Isang katulong o kasambahay na napakahusay, episyente, o maraming nagagawang trabaho.
A very efficient, capable, or multi-tasking maid or domestic helper.

examples.example: Bibigyan ko ng bonus si Ate Melda dahil mayda fatale siya buong taon.
I will give Ate Melda a bonus because she has been an efficient maid (mayda fatale) for the whole year.

etymology: Bekimon (gay slang) term using the name of actress Monica Herrera as a playful substitute for 'uminom' (to drink), especially alcohol.

definitions.meaning: Ang pag-inom, lalo na ng alak.
To drink, especially alcoholic beverages.

examples.example: Mag-monica herrera tayo nila Julie pagkatapos nating sumuweldo.
Let's have drinks (monica herrera) with Julie after we receive our salary.

etymology: Slang term, origin uncertain, possibly Bekimon or a playful elaboration of 'antok' (sleepy).

definitions.meaning: Inaantok o pagod, lalo na dahil sa kulang sa tulog.
Feeling sleepy or tired, especially due to lack of sleep.

examples.example: Montokey talaga ako ngayong gabi at wala akong magawa para rito.
I'm feeling really sleepy (montokey) tonight and I can't do anything about it.

etymology: From English 'moocher' (one who exploits others' generosity), but used in Filipino slang to mean a glutton or someone who eats a lot.

definitions.meaning: Isang taong matakaw o malakas kumain; mahilig ubusin ang pagkain.
A person who eats a lot or likes to finish all the food; a glutton or big eater (differs from standard English meaning).

examples.example: Walang natitira at nasasayang na handa sa amin ni Lando. Moocher kami at parating busog!
With Lando, there are no leftovers and no food goes to waste. We are big eaters (moochers) and our stomachs are always full!

etymology: Slang term for 'mother', likely Bekimon/gay slang, possibly a playful alteration of 'mudra'.

definitions.meaning: Ina o nanay.
Mother.

examples.example: Kailangan ko nang umalis. Naghihintay na si moods sa bahay.
I have to go now. Mom (Moods) is waiting at home.

etymology: Slang phrase using the name of Filipina comedian Moody Diaz, playing on her name and the English word 'moody'.

definitions.meaning: Sobrang sumpungin o pabago-bago ang mood.
Very moody or temperamental.

examples.example: Moody diaz talaga siyaâ€”masaya lang siya kanina tapos biglang galit na!
She's such a moody diaz (so moody)â€”she was happy one minute and angry the next!

etymology: Slang phrase referencing the transformation phrase from the anime 'Sailor Moon'. Used humorously/derogatorily to describe someone who only looks attractive at night.

definitions.meaning: Tumutukoy sa isang tao na maganda o kaakit-akit lamang kapag gabi (hal., dahil sa makeup, dim light, atbp.).
Refers to a person who looks beautiful or attractive only at night (e.g., due to makeup, dim lighting, etc.).

examples.example: Si Lira ay parang bampira. Tuwing gabi ko lang nakikita ang tulad niyang moon crystal power.
Lira is like a vampire. I only see a 'night beauty' (moon crystal power) like her at night.

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, using the name of Morayta Street in Manila (associated with budget shopping/services) as a substitute for 'mura' (cheap).

definitions.meaning: Mura o mababa ang halaga.
Cheap or inexpensive.

examples.example: Liz, taasan mo ang presyo ng mga damit. Masyadong morayta!
Liz, raise the price of these clothes. They're so cheap (morayta)!

etymology: Slang verb derived from the Moriones festival (where participants wear masks/costumes). Figuratively refers to the act of a male dressing as a female.

definitions.meaning: Ang pagbibihis o pag-aayos ng isang lalaki na parang babae; mag-cross-dress.
For a male to dress up as a female; to cross-dress or dress in drag.

examples.example: Noong bata pa ako ay mahilig akong magmoriones gamit ang mga damit ni Ate Claudia.
When I was still a child, I loved to cross-dress (moriones) using Ate Claudia's clothes.

etymology: From the Moro-moro folk drama. Figuratively refers to a sham, farce, or situation characterized by pretense or insincerity.

definitions.meaning: Isang sitwasyon o palabas na puro pagkukunwari lamang, hindi totoo, o isang drama.
A situation or act characterized by pretense or insincerity; a sham, farce, or charade.

examples.example: Moro-moro lang pala ang paghingi niya ng tawad.
His apology turned out to be just a sham (moro-moro).

etymology: Slang term using the English phrase 'morning glory' euphemistically for 'muta' (sleep crust/eye discharge).

definitions.meaning: Dumi o namuong likido sa mata na karaniwang nakikita pagkagising sa umaga; muta.
The crusty discharge found in the corners of the eyes upon waking; sleep crust or rheum.

examples.example: Maghilamos ka nga, ang dami mong morning glory!
Wash your face, you have a lot of sleep crust (morning glory)!

etymology: Slang term for 'motorcycle', possibly a playful alteration or misuse of the scientific term 'motility' (ability to move).

definitions.meaning: Motorsiklo.
Motorcycle.

examples.example: Ingat ka sa pagmamaneho ng motility mo.
Be careful driving your motorcycle (motility).

definitions.meaning: Motel, karaniwan ay tumutukoy sa mga paupahang kuwarto para sa panandaliang pananatili o pagtatalik.
Motel, often referring to establishments offering rooms for short stays, frequently used for romantic or sexual encounters.

examples.example: Nag-check in sila sa motmot pagkatapos ng date nila.
They checked into a motel (motmot) after their date.

etymology: Slang term using the cleaning product brand name/character 'Mr. Clean' ironically to describe a gay man perceived as overly fastidious, self-righteous, or pretentious about cleanliness/morality ('nagmamalinis').

definitions.meaning: Isang bakla na nagmamalinis o nagkukunwaring napakalinis o napakabuti ng ugali.
A gay man perceived as self-righteous or pretending to be overly clean, virtuous, or morally upright.

examples.example: Huwag kang mag-alala diyan, masyadong Mr. Clean 'yan para gumawa ng kalokohan.
Don't worry about him, he's too much of a Mr. Clean (self-righteous) to do anything mischievous.

etymology: Slang acronym playing on the Metro Rail Transit (MRT) system abbreviation, standing for 'MaARTe' (fussy, picky).

definitions.meaning: Maarte, maselan, o mapili.
Fussy, picky, or finicky.

examples.example: Ayaw niyang kumain diyan, masyadong MRT.
She doesn't want to eat there, she's too picky (MRT).

etymology: Slang expression, likely Bekimon/gay slang, using 'Ms.' with 'Lux' (possibly referencing luxury or the soap brand) as a substitute for 'Good luck'.

definitions.meaning: Ekspresyong pambati na nangangahulugang 'Good luck' o 'Sana'y suwertehin ka'.
An expression used to wish someone good luck.

examples.example: Ms. Lux sa job interview mo, Gilbert! Kaya mo yan!
Good luck (Ms. Lux) on your job interview, Gilbert! You can do it!

etymology: Text speak abbreviation and respelling of the Tagalog greeting 'Kumusta ka?' (How are you?).

definitions.meaning: Pinaikling paraan ng pagtatanong ng 'Kumusta ka?' sa text o chat.
Abbreviated way of asking 'How are you?' in text or chat.

examples.example: Uy, long time no see! Msta k?
Hey, long time no see! How are you (Msta k)?

etymology: Acronym for the English phrase 'Mutual Understanding'. Refers to a stage in a relationship before becoming official.
synonym: more than friends, less than lovers

definitions.meaning: Isang yugto sa relasyon kung saan may pagtitinginan o romantikong pagkakaunawaan ang dalawang tao ngunit hindi pa sila opisyal na magkasintahan.
A stage in a relationship where two people have mutual romantic feelings or understanding but are not yet officially a couple.

examples.example: MU kami ni Roger pero nagpapakiramdaman pa rin.
Roger and I have a mutual understanding (MU) but we are still feeling things out.

etymology: From Spanish 'muchacha' (girl, young woman). Adopted into Tagalog primarily to mean a female domestic helper.

definitions.meaning: Isang babaeng katulong o kasambahay.
A female domestic helper or maidservant.

examples.example: Kailangan namin ng bagong muchacha.
We need a new housemaid (muchacha).

etymology: From Spanish 'muchacho' (boy, young man). Adopted into Tagalog primarily to mean a male domestic helper.

definitions.meaning: Isang lalaking katulong o utusan sa bahay.
A male domestic helper or manservant.

examples.example: Naghahanap sila ng muchacho na marunong magmaneho.
They are looking for a manservant (muchacho) who knows how to drive.

etymology: Slang term for 'mother', popularized in Bekimon/gay slang, possibly influenced by Spanish 'madre' or English 'mother'.

definitions.meaning: Ina o nanay.
Mother.

examples.example: Kapag 'di ako nakapasa sa exam, siguradong magagalit sa akin si mudra.
If I don't pass this exam, my mother (mudra) will surely get mad at me.

etymology: Slang term, likely related to 'mahadera', meaning vulgar, coarse, or obnoxious.

definitions.meaning: Bastos, maingay, o walang pinag-aralan kumilos o magsalita; mahadera.
Vulgar, coarse, loud, or ill-mannered in behavior or speech; obnoxious.

examples.example: Muhad talaga iyang si Diana. Talak nang talak sa kalsada.
Diana is really vulgar/loudmouthed (muhad). She always shouts in public places.

etymology: Derived from the slang verb 'lafang' (to eat) + '-an' (place suffix).

definitions.meaning: Isang lugar kung saan maaaring kumain; kainan o restoran.
A place where one can eat; an eatery or restaurant.

examples.example: Sunod ka sa amin sa lafangan mamaya pagkatapos ng trabaho mo.
Follow us at the eatery (lafangan) after your work.

etymology: Slang, likely Bekimon, variation or elaboration of 'lafang' (to eat).

definitions.meaning: Kumain.
To eat.

examples.example: Lafez ka na riyan. Nagluto ako ng paborito mong adobo.
You may now eat (lafez) there. I cooked your favorite adobo.

etymology: Standard Tagalog word meaning wanderer or vagrant.

definitions.meaning: Isang tao na palibut-libot, walang permanenteng tirahan, o mahilig maglakbay kung saan-saan; taong layas.
A person who wanders about, has no permanent home, or likes to travel widely; a wanderer or vagrant.

examples.example: Halos malibot na niya ang mundo sa pagiging lagalag.
He has almost traveled around the world from being a wanderer (lagalag).

etymology: Slang term, likely Bekimon/gay slang, for 'nose'.

definitions.meaning: Ilong.
Nose.

examples.example: Wow, ang ganda ng nafez mo! Natural ba 'yan o retoke?
Wow, your nose (nafez) is beautiful! Is that natural or retouched?

etymology: Slang phrase, likely Bekimon/gay slang, combining 'nakakapagod' (tiring) and 'arian' (genitals/property) for vulgar emphasis.

definitions.meaning: Sobrang nakakapagod, nakakainis, o nakakasawa.
Extremely tiring, annoying, wearisome, or exasperating.

examples.example: Nakakapagod-arian nang pakinggan ang mga reklamo mo!
It's extremely tiresome (nakakapagod-arian) to listen to your complaints!

etymology: Pronunciation spelling or regional variant (e.g., Visayan) of the Tagalog pronoun 'kami' (we/us, exclusive).

definitions.meaning: Kami (panghalip na hindi kasama ang kausap).
We or us (pronoun, excluding the person being addressed).

examples.example: Hintayin mo nami dito, ha.
Wait for us (nami) here, okay?
